e = \n| caption = Casillas with [[FC Porto|Porto]] in 2018\n| fullname = Iker Casillas Fern\u00e1ndez<ref>{{cite web|title=FIFA World Cup South Africa 2010: List of Players|url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/tournament/competition/01/22/85/78/fwc_2010_squadlists.pdf|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association (FIFA)|accessdate=13 September 2013|page=29|format=PDF|date=4 June 2010}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1981|5|20}}\n| birth_place = [[M\u00f3stoles]], Spain\n| height = 1.82 m<ref name=Soccerway>{{cite web|url=https://uk.soccerway.com/players/iker-casillas-fernandez/317/|title=Casillas: Summary|website=Soccerway|publisher=Perform Group|access-date=2 May 2019}}</ref>\n| position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1 = 1990\u20131998\n| youthclubs1 = [[Real Madrid CF (youth)|Real Madrid]]\n| years1 = 1998\u20131999\n| clubs1 = [[Real Madrid C]]\n| caps1 = 26\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1999\n| clubs2 = [[Real Madrid Castilla|Real Madrid B]]\n| caps2 = 4\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 1999\u20132015\n| clubs3 = [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]\n| caps3 = 510\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2015\u20132020\n| clubs4 = [[FC Porto|Porto]]\n| caps4 = 116\n| goals4 = 0\n| totalcaps = 656\n| totalgoals = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 1996\n| nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-15 football team|Spain U15]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1996\u20131998\n| nationalteam2 = [[Spain national under-16 football team|Spain U16]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 19\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 1997\u20131999\n| nationalteam3 = [[Spain national under-17 football team|Spain U17]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 10\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 1999\n| nationalteam4 = [[Spain national under-18 football team|Spain U18]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 4\n| nationalgoals4 = 0\n| nationalyears5 = 1999\n| nationalteam5 = [[Spain national under-20 football team|Spain U20]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 2\n| nationalgoals5 = 0\n| nationalyears6 = 1999\u20132000\n| nationalteam6 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]]\n| nationalcaps6 = 5\n| nationalgoals6 = 0\n| nationalyears7 = 2000\u20132016\n| nationalteam7 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]]\n| nationalcaps7 = 167\n| nationalgoals7 = 0\n| club-update = 18 February 2020\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{fb|ESP}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 South Africa]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[UEFA Euro 2008|2008 Austria\u2013Switzerland]]|}}\n{{Medal|W|[[UEFA Euro 2012|2012 Poland\u2013Ukraine]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA Confederations Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|3rd|[[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup|2009 South Africa]]|}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup|2013 Brazil]]|}}\n}}\n'''Iker Casillas Fern\u00e1ndez''' (<small>Spanish pronunciation:</small> [[Help:IPA/Spanish|[\u02c8ike\u027e ka\u02c8si\u028eas fe\u027e\u02c8nande\u03b8]]]; born 20 May 1981) is a Spanish former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]]. Popularly dubbed \"''San Iker''\" (\"Saint Iker\") for his ability to produce spectacular saves, Casillas is widely regarded by many to be one of the greatest goalkeepers of all time, and by some, as the greatest ever.{{refn|group=nb|*{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1516455-25-greatest-goalkeepers-in-football-history|title=25 Greatest Goalkeepers in Football History|last=Morgan|first=Richard|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/football/football-the-20-greatest-goalkeepers-of-all-time|title=Football's 20 greatest goalkeepers of all time|date=2013-07-22|website=www.sportskeeda.com|language=en-us|access-date=2020-02-19}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://www.givemesport.com/352480-top-five-greatest-goalkeepers-of-alltime|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150507233748/http://www.givemesport.com/352480-top-five-greatest-goalkeepers-of-alltime|url-status=dead|archive-date=2015-05-07|title=Top five: Greatest goalkeepers of all-time {{!}} GiveMeSport|date=2015-05-07|access-date=2020-02-19}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://bestfootballplayersever.com/top-10-best-football-goalkeepers-ever.php|title=Best Goalkeepers Ever - Top 10 list of the Greatest Football Goalkeepers Ever|website=bestfootballplayersever.com|access-date=2020-02-19}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/lists/buffon-or-yashin-top-10-goalkeepers-of-all-time/1mb2d3jk5w285150ykl834v60v|title=Buffon, Schmeichel or Yashin? Top 10 goalkeepers of all time {{!}} Goal.com|website=www.goal.com|access-date=2020-02-19 }}\n*{{cite web|url=http://en.espn.co.uk/football/sport/player/73939.html|title=Iker Casillas \u2013 Profile|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=21 October 2015}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.calciomercato.it/news/156356/Campioni-ai-Raggi-X-Iker-Casillas-il-capitano-perfetto.html|title=Campioni ai Raggi X: Iker Casillas, il capitano perfetto|trans-title=Champions X-rayed: Iker Casillas, the perfect captain|publisher=Calcio Mercato|language=Italian|date=7 May 2012|accessdate=21 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930155417/http://www.calciomercato.it/news/156356/Campioni-ai-Raggi-X-Iker-Casillas-il-capitano-perfetto.html|archivedate=30 September 2015}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/james-lawton-spanish-can-always-have-faith-in-miracle-saves-of-saint-iker-casillas-7897190.html|title=James Lawton: Spanish can always have faith in miracle saves of 'Saint' Iker Casillas|author1=James Lawton|publisher=The Independent|date=29 June 2012|accessdate=21 October 2015 }}}} Known for his athleticism, quick reactions and outstanding shot-stopping ability. Having spent the majority of his career at [[Real Madrid]], Casillas is one of the few players to achieve over [[List of footballers with the most official appearances|1000 professional career matches]], and holds the record for the most clean sheets in the [[UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions league]], as well as for the [[Spain national football team|Spanish national team]].\n\nAt club level, Casillas started his career with the [[Real Madrid CF (youth)|Real Madrid youth team]], eventually gaining promotion to the main team in 1999, where he became the youngest goalkeeper to play in the final of the Champions league, and to win the title, at 19 years and four days. Casillas became the first choice goalkeeper at Real Madrid, winning 2 champions leagues and la Liga titles in his first three seasons, establishing himself as one of the best goalkeepers in the world. During his highly successful career in Madrid, Casillas won all major club titles, including five [[La Liga]] titles, four [[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]] titles, two [[Copa del Rey]] titles, three [[UEFA Champions League|Champions leagues]], two [[UEFA Super Cup]]s, one [[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]] and the [[FIFA Club World Cup]]. After 25 years with Real Madrid, Casillas joined FC Porto in 2015 on a free transfer, where he won the [[2017\u201318 Primeira Liga|Primeira Liga]] and a [[2018 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira]] title. While at Porto, he broke the record for most consecutive seasons played in the champions league (20) and amassed the most appearances in the competition (177).\n\nWith 167 international caps, Casillas has the second most appearances for the Spanish national team, making him the joint tenth-[[List of men's footballers with 100 or more international caps|most capped footballer of all time]]. Becoming the nation's first choice goalkeeper at the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]], Casillas went on to play at [[UEFA Euro 2004]] and the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]]. In 2008, he was made [[List of Spain national football captains|captain]], and led the team to that year's [[UEFA Euro 2008|European Championship]]. Casillas also led Spain to their first [[2010 FIFA World Cup|World Cup win in 2010]], where he kept a record five clean sheets, winning the [[Yashin Award]] for best goalkeeper of the tournament. Spain became the first nation to retain the European Championship, winning again in [[UEFA Euro 2012|2012]], where he set the record for [[List of UEFA European Championship records and statistics|most consecutive minutes without conceding a goal]] in the competition (509). In 2014, Casillas became one of four players to [[List of players who have appeared in multiple FIFA World Cups|represent Spain at four World Cups]].\n\nIn 2008, Casillas placed Fourth overall in the [[Ballon d'Or]], and has been selected for the [[UEFA Team of the Year|UEFA Team of the year]] six consecutive times from 2007 to 2012, a record for a goalkeeper. Casillas was also selected in the [[FIFPro World XI|FIFPro world XI]] a record 5 times for a goalkeeper, and was named as the [[IFFHS World's Best Goalkeeper]] a record 5 times, alongside [[Gianluigi Buffon]]. He was named as the second best goalkeeper of the 21st century, behind Buffon, and the second best goalkeeper of the past 25 years by the same organisation.\n\n==Early life==\nCasillas was born on 20 May 1981 in [[M\u00f3stoles]], [[province of Madrid]], to Jos\u00e9 Luis Casillas, a civil servant in the [[Ministry of Education (Spain)|Ministry of Education]], and Mar\u00eda del Carmen Fern\u00e1ndez Gonz\u00e1lez, a hairdresser.<ref name=\"El Mundo Spain\">{{cite web|url=http://www.elmundo.es/magazine/m29/textos/iker1.html|title=Iker Casillas, portero del Real Madrid|trans-title=Iker Casillas, Real Madrid's goalkeeper|publisher=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]}}</ref> Both his parents had moved from their home of [[Navalacruz]], [[Province of \u00c1vila|\u00c1vila]].<ref name=\"El Mundo Spain\"/>\n\nCasillas has a brother, seven years younger, named Unai, who used to play as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]] for [[CD M\u00f3stoles]].<ref name=\"unamadridsta\">{{cite web|url = http://unamadridista.wordpress.com/2010/09/28/get-to-know-unai-casillas/ |title=Get to know... Unai Casillas |publisher=Una Madridista |date=28 September 2010 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> The brothers' forenames are of [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque]] origin due to a family connection to the region: their paternal grandfather \u2013 an officer in the [[Civil Guard (Spain)|Civil Guard]] \u2013 was posted to [[Bilbao]] and settled in the city, their father grew up there as a result and Iker also lived in the area as a small child before the family relocated to Madrid.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ianasagasti.blogs.com/mi_blog/2013/11/casillas-y-el-athletic.html|title=Casillas y el Athletic|trans-title=Casillas and Athletic|publisher=I\u00f1aki Anasagasti Blogs|language=Spanish|date=6 November 2013|accessdate=2 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn one occasion as a young child, Casillas forgot to post his father's football predictions for the weekend; his father had correctly predicted all 15 results, and the family lost out on an estimated \u20ac1.2&nbsp;million (\u00a31&nbsp;million).<ref>{{cite news|last1=McDermott|first1=Gerry|title=In off the post: Casillas drops a clanger on lottery|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/in-off-the-post-casillas-drops-a-clanger-on-lottery-25910835.html|accessdate=3 April 2018|work=Irish Independent|date=16 June 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lowe|first1=Sid|title=Casillas eyes win to unite a nation and repay a debt|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2004/jun/07/euro2004.sport147|accessdate=3 April 2018|work=The Guardian|date=7 June 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Real Madrid===\n====Early years====\nCasillas began his career in [[Real Madrid CF (youth)|Real Madrid's youth system]], known as [[La F\u00e1brica]], during the 1990\u201391 season. On 27 November 1997, at age 16 and still a junior, he was first called up to the senior team squad to face [[Rosenborg BK|Rosenborg]] in the [[1997\u201398 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]], although he remained on the bench throughout. After spending a season with the [[Real Madrid C|C-team]]<ref>{{cite web|url = https://unamadridista.wordpress.com/2011/02/11/iker-casillas-the-real-interview/ |title=Iker Casillas \u2013 the Real... interview |publisher=Following Real Madrid... |date=11 February 2011 |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> in the [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|fourth tier]], during which they won their regional group,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arquero-arba.futbolme.net/Nacionales/1998-99/9899-3-7.htm|title=Tercera Divisi\u00f3n (Grupo 7) 1998\u201399|language=Spanish|publisher=Arquero-Arba|date=|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> he came into contention as the club's first-choice between the posts. In starting the [[1999\u20132000 UEFA Champions League]] group stage fixture against [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiakos]] on 15 September 1999, he became the youngest goalkeeper ever to feature in the competition at the time, aged 18 years and 177 days; a record which was only broken in October 2017 by [[Mile Svilar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/club/benfica/1929/blog/post/3251492/meet-benficas-mile-svilar-the-youngest-keeper-in-champions-league-history|title=Meet Mile Svilar, the youngest keeper in Champions League history|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Michael Yokhin|date=31 October 2017|accessdate=31 October 2017}}</ref> Three days earlier, Casillas had made his [[La Liga]] debut in a 2\u20132 draw against [[Athletic Bilbao]] at [[San Mam\u00e9s Stadium (1913)|San Mam\u00e9s Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/3277/la-liga/2011/09/12/2662477/real-madrids-iker-casillas-making-my-debut-against-athletic|title=Real Madrid's Iker Casillas: Making my debut against Athletic Bilbao is the greatest memory I have|publisher=Goal|date=12 September 2011|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> In May 2000, he became the youngest ever goalkeeper to play in and win a Champions League final when Real Madrid defeated [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] [[2000 UEFA Champions League Final|3\u20130]], just four days after his 19th birthday.<ref name=\"Iker Casillas ESPN Profile\">{{cite web| url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/players/profile?id=11811&cc=4716 | title = Iker Casillas Fern\u00e1ndez Profile, Statis, News, Game Log | publisher = ESPN Soccernet | accessdate =8 February 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Champions League's greatest ever goalkeepers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2543201.html#/the+champions+leagues+greatest+ever+goalkeepers|title=The Champions League's greatest ever goalkeepers|publisher=UEFA.com|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2001\u20132010====\nCasillas lost his place in the side to backup [[C\u00e9sar S\u00e1nchez]] after poor performances in the [[2001\u201302 Real Madrid CF season|2001\u201302 campaign]], but redeemed himself when S\u00e1nchez suffered an injury in the final minutes of the [[2002 UEFA Champions League Final|2002 Champions League Final]]. Casillas came on and pulled off several key saves to deny a rampant [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]] the Champions League crown. Real Madrid won 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real crowned champions of Europe |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/champions_league/1984398.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=15 May 2002 |accessdate=31 December 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/UCL/News/Kind=128/newsId=23850.html|title=Madrid win ninth European crown|publisher=UEFA|date=15 May 2002|accessdate=8 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020606223553/http://www.uefa.com/competitions/UCL/News/Kind%3D128/newsId%3D23850.html|archivedate=6 June 2002}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Saca Iker Casillas (3869018560).jpg|thumb|255px|right|Casillas in action for Real Madrid at the [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium|Santiago Bernab\u00e9u]] in 2009]]\nThe [[2007\u201308 Real Madrid CF season|2007\u201308 season]] was a fruitful season for Casillas, as he helped Real Madrid reclaim their 31st [[La Liga]] [[List of Spanish football champions|title]] and conceded only 32 goals in 36 matches to claim the [[Zamora Trophy]]. On 14 February 2008, he and club captain [[Ra\u00fal (footballer)|Ra\u00fal]] were awarded contracts for life; Casillas signed a contract extension that would keep him at the club until 2017, with an automatic extension if he played 30 competitive matches during the final season of the contract and a buy-out clause of \u00a3113&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11827_3146197,00.html |title=Casillas and Raul commit to Real |publisher=Sky Sports |accessdate=7 May 2009| date = 14 February 2008}}</ref> His performances earned him a spot in the [[UEFA Team of the Year]] for the second time.\n\nIn February 2009, Casillas equalled [[Francisco Buyo|Paco Buyo]]'s record of 454 matches played for a goalkeeper and has since surpassed it to become Real Madrid's most-capped goalkeeper of all time at only 27 years old.<ref name=\"Casillas secures place in Madrid folklore\">{{Cite news|title=Casillas secures place in Madrid folklore|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=799092.html#casillas+secures+place+madrid+folklore|publisher=[[UEFA]].com|date=9 February 2009 | accessdate =8 February 2011}}</ref> During the 2009 summer transfer window, some Spanish media reported that [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] had launched a record \u00a3129&nbsp;million bid for the goalkeeper. The club denied the rumours, however, saying that no such offer had been made. [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] had been rumoured to have enquired about him, but no price was announced.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/manchester_city/s/1083265_city_deny_casillas_bid | title = City deny Casillas bid | date = 3 December 2008 | accessdate =20 October 2010 | first = James | last = Robson | publisher = Manchester Evening News}}</ref> He had been linked with other [[Premier League]] clubs before<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2325833/Iker-Casillas-in-the-dark-over-Tottenham-link.html | title = Iker Casillas in the dark over Tottenham link | date = 15 November 2007 | accessdate =20 October 2010 | publisher = The Telegraph | first1=Steve | last1=Wilson}}</ref> but Casillas himself stated that he \"had no intention of leaving\" his boyhood club.\n\nDuring the [[2009\u201310 La Liga|2009\u201310 season]] on 4 October in a game against [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]], Casillas made an extraordinary save, running from one side of his goal to the other to deny [[Diego Perotti]] in a one-on-one, close-range encounter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KIceM6T3o-g |title=Real Madrid Vs Sevilla Iker Casillas Huge Save Unbelievable!! HD |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref> After the match, he received praise from fellow Spanish goalkeepers and [[England national football team|England]] goalkeeper [[Gordon Banks]], who stated, \"Casillas' reflexes are incredible. If he continues to play this well he will become one of the best goalkeepers in the history of the game.\" ''[[Europa Press]]'' reported that Casillas was the second-most popular Spanish sportsman on the Internet in 2010. The study performed by company Vipnet360 examined the web presence on platforms like Facebook, Twitter and YouTube.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.europapress.es/deportes/futbol-00162/noticia-varios-iniesta-torres-nadal-alonso-nombrados-deportistas-espanoles-mas-importantes-internet-redes-sociales-20101227124812.html|title=Iniesta, Torres, Nadal y Alonso, deportistas espa\u00f1oles m\u00e1s importantes en Internet|work=[[Europa Press]]|date=27 December 2010 | language = Spanish}}</ref>\n\n====2010\u20132015====\n[[File:IkerCasillas2010.jpg|thumb|left|Casillas, wearing the captain's armband while playing for Real Madrid in 2010|120px]]\nDuring the [[2010-11 La Liga|2010\u201311 season]], after the departure of first and second captains of Real Madrid, Ra\u00fal and [[Guti (Spanish footballer)|Guti]] respectively, Casillas was selected as first captain with new vice-captains [[Sergio Ramos]], [[Marcelo (footballer, born 1988)|Marcelo]] and [[Gonzalo Higua\u00edn]].\n\nDuring the [[2011\u201312 La Liga|2011\u201312 season]], Casillas won the IFFHS Best Goalkeeper award, making him only the second goalkeeper behind [[Gianluigi Buffon]] to win it four times and the only goalkeeper to win the award four times in a row. Casillas played his 600th match for Real Madrid on 22 January 2012 in a 4\u20131 win against Athletic Bilbao. On 2 May 2012, Casillas clinched his fifth La Liga title and his first as a captain of Real Madrid, with a 3\u20130 win in Bilbao.\n\n[[File:Iker Casillas's gloves.jpg|thumb|250px|Casillas' gloves on display at the Santiago Bernabeu museum]]\nOn 22 December 2012, Casillas was dropped by [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]] for a Liga match against [[M\u00e1laga CF|M\u00e1laga]] in favour of [[Antonio Ad\u00e1n]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/liga-mourinho-drops-casillas-malaga-beat-real-madrid-205623479.html |title=Liga \u2013 Mourinho drops Casillas as Malaga beat Real Madrid |publisher=uk.eurosport.yahoo.com |date=22 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121225164516/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/liga-mourinho-drops-casillas-malaga-beat-real-madrid-205623479.html |archivedate=25 December 2012}}</ref> This was the beginning of a series of sour disagreements between the Portuguese coach and the player, some of which, along with other internal affairs, were allegedly aired to the press by Casillas himself. This generated a shift in the opinion of certain sectors of Real Madrid's fans, who gave Casillas the nickname \"''topor''\" (a [[portmanteau]] of \"''topo'',\" and \"''portero'',\" Spanish for \"[[Mole (espionage)|mole]]\" and \"goalkeeper,\" respectively).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vozpopuli.com/deportes/25614-madridismo-unido-los-mourinhistas-no-perdonan-a-florentino-ni-sobre-todo-a-casillas |title=\u00bfMadridismo unido? Los mourinhistas no perdonan a Florentino ni, sobre todo, a Casillas |publisher=Voz p\u00f3puli |date=22 May 2013 |accessdate=27 July 2013}}</ref> During the [[2012\u201313 La Liga|2012\u201313 season]], Casillas won the IFFHS Best Goalkeeper Award for the fifth consecutive time, making him the only goalkeeper in history to have ever won that award five times (in a row).\n\nIn January 2013, after a serious injury to Casillas, Mourinho signed [[Diego L\u00f3pez (footballer, born 3 November 1981)|Diego L\u00f3pez]] from Sevilla. L\u00f3pez was named first-choice 'keeper ahead of Antonio Ad\u00e1n and kept his place in the team even after Casillas had returned from injury. After the 2012\u201313 season, Mourinho left Madrid and soon after his departure, Spanish midfielder [[Andr\u00e9s Iniesta]] criticised him for benching Casillas.\n\nIn the middle of 2013, it was announced that [[Carlo Ancelotti]] would be Real Madrid's head coach for the [[2013\u201314 Real Madrid CF season|2013\u201314 season]]. Real Madrid started the season with a 2\u20131 victory over [[Real Betis]] in which Casillas was benched once again. He made his first start in 238 days in the [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] group stage match against [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]], but was injured in the 14th minute after Sergio Ramos caught him with an accidental elbow as the goalkeeper came from his line to make a routine catch.<ref>[http://espnfc.com/news/story/_/id/1556396/iker-casillas-injured-collision-real-madrid-team-mate-sergio-ramos?cc=3436 Iker Casillas suffers injury blow]. Espnfc.com (18 September 2013). Retrieved on 26 September 2015.</ref> Despite being the club's second-choice 'keeper in [[2013\u201314 La Liga|La Liga]], behind Diego L\u00f3pez, Casillas continued to be Madrid's first choice keeper in the Champions League and [[2013\u201314 Copa del Rey|Copa del Rey]], setting a new record of 962 minutes without conceding a goal in the latter competition.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2014/03/01/en/football/real_madrid/1393662091.html|title=Casillas to miss the derby|date=1 March 2014|accessdate=27 May 2014|work=Marca}}</ref> In February 2014, he became the first goalkeeper to play in every round of the [[Copa del Rey]] prior to the final without conceding a goal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kickoff.com/news/41452/iker-casillas-rewrites-spanish-history-books|title=Casillas makes history|date=12 February 2014|accessdate=27 May 2014|work=Kickoff|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527214024/http://www.kickoff.com/news/41452/iker-casillas-rewrites-spanish-history-books|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 16 April, he captained Madrid in [[2014 Copa del Rey Final|the final]] as they beat rivals [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] 2\u20131 at Valencia's [[Mestalla Stadium]]. On 24 May 2014, Casillas captained Real Madrid in the [[2014 UEFA Champions League Final|2014 Champions League final]], winning the title for the third time in his career with a 4\u20131 win over [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] in [[Lisbon]]; this was the tenth time Real Madrid had won the trophy. Although [[Diego God\u00edn]]'s opening goal resulted from an error by Casillas, Sergio Ramos tied the match for Real Madrid in injury time; the club went on to win the title in extra-time.<ref name=\"La D\u00e9cima\">{{cite web|url = http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2014/matches/round=2000483/match=2011883/postmatch/report/|title = Madrid finally fulfil D\u00e9cima dream|date = 24 May 2014|accessdate = 9 May 2015|website = UEFA|first = Andrew|last = Haslam}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27563098|title = Champions League: Real Madrid fans celebrate 'La Decima'|date = 25 May 2014|accessdate = 9 May 2015|website = BBC|publisher = |last = Burridge|first = Tom}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/27383593|title = Gareth Bale helped Real Madrid win their 10th European Cup as they finally overwhelmed arch-rivals Atletico Madrid in a compelling Champions League final in Lisbon.|date = 24 May 2014|accessdate = 9 May 2015|website = BBC Sport|publisher = |last = McNulty|first = Phil}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the Champions League win, the [[2014\u201315 Real Madrid CF season|2014\u201315 season]] saw Casillas return to being the club's first choice goalkeeper, despite competition from new arrival [[Keylor Navas]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/aug/03/real-madrid-confirm-keylor-navas-signing |title=Real Madrid confirm signing of Costa Rica\u2019s goalkeeper Keylor Navas |work=The Guardian |date=3 August 2014 |accessdate=11 October 2019 }}</ref> as he then went on to win the [[2014 UEFA Super Cup|UEFA Super Cup]], with Real Madrid defeating Sevilla 2\u20130 on 12 August 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/season=2014/matches/round=2000553/match=2014109/postmatch/report/|title = Ronaldo fires Madrid to Super Cup glory|date = 12 August 2014|accessdate = 9 May 2015|website = UEFA|publisher = |last = Hart|first = Simon}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.dw.de/kroos-shines-as-real-madrid-win-uefa-super-cup/a-17848608|title = Kroos shines as Real Madrid win UEFA Super Cup|date = 13 August 2014|accessdate = 9 May 2015|website = DW Sports|publisher = |last = Harding|first = Jonathan}}</ref> He then also won the [[2014 FIFA Club World Cup|FIFA Club World Cup]] later that year, making his 700th appearance for Madrid on 20 December 2014, in the [[2014 FIFA Club World Cup Final]], as Real Madrid defeated [[San Lorenzo de Almagro|San Lorenzo]] 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2014/12/casillas-won-his-first-club-world-cup-on-his-700th-appearance-with-real-madrid|title=Casillas won his first Club World Cup on his 700th appearance with Real Madrid|last=Navarro|first=Alberto|date=20 December 2014|publisher=Real Madrid|accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2014/dec/20/real-madrid-v-san-lorenzo-club-world-cup-live|title = Real Madrid 2\u20130 San Lorenzo: Club World Cup \u2013 as it happened|date = 21 December 2014|accessdate = 9 May 2015|website = The Guardian|publisher = |last = Miller|first = Nick}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.foxsports.com/soccer/story/real-madrid-defeat-san-lorenzo-to-win-fifa-club-world-cup-react-122014|title = Real Madrid claim FIFA Club World Cup title with win over San Lorenzo|date = 20 December 2014|accessdate = 9 May 2015|website = FOX Soccer|publisher = |last = McCarthy|first = Kyle}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://edition.cnn.com/2014/12/20/sport/football/real-madrid-win-club-world-cup/|title = Real Madrid end year with fantastic fourth title in Club World Cup|date = 3 January 2015|accessdate = 9 May 2015|website = CNN|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://sports.yahoo.com/news/real-madrid-win-club-world-cup-212643137--sow.html|title = Real Madrid win Club World Cup, fourth title of 2014|date = 20 December 2014|accessdate = 9 May 2015|website = Yahoo Sports|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n===Porto===\n{{Quote box|width=30%|align=Right|quote=\"You've always been a Real Madrid icon, but above all you've been one of the best representatives of our position on the pitch. Good luck in your new adventure, it'll be strange to see you in another shirt from now on. Go Iker!\"|source=\u2014Juventus and Italy goalkeeper [[Gianluigi Buffon]] on Casillas following his transfer to [[FC Porto|Porto]] in July 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/en/2015/07/13/en/football/real_madrid/1436812635.html|title=Buffon: \"Good luck Iker\"|publisher=Marca|date=13 July 2015|accessdate=13 July 2015}}</ref>}}\n[[File:DK-Porto15 (9).jpg|thumb|right|Casillas playing for Porto in 2015]]\nAfter much speculation about his future, on 11 July 2015 Casillas signed with Portuguese [[Primeira Liga]] side [[FC Porto|Porto]] on a two-year deal with the option of a one-year extension.<ref>{{cite web|title=Official Statement: Iker Casillas|url=http://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2015/07/official-statement-iker-casillas|work=realmadrid.com|accessdate=11 July 2015|date=11 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/69/transfer-zone/2015/07/12/13522722/casillas-signs-two-year-porto-contract|title=Casillas signs two-year Porto contract|date=12 July 2015|accessdate=12 July 2015|publisher=Goal.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/jul/13/real-madrid-iker-casillas-repair-damage|title=Real Madrid try to repair Iker Casillas damage \u2013 but only make things worse|date=14 July 2015|work=Guardian |accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> Real Madrid's conduct in his exit was criticised, with Casillas' parents claiming that he was being forced out of the club by president [[Florentino P\u00e9rez]], who received calls to quit from fans. Former international teammate [[Xavi]], who earlier that summer left Barcelona after a similarly long and successful career, claimed that Real Madrid were ungrateful of Casillas' service to the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=Xavi hits out at Real Madrid for treatment of departing Iker Casillas|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/jul/14/xavi-iker-casillas-real-madrid-porto|accessdate=16 August 2015|work=The Guardian|agency=Reuters|date=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nCasillas made his Primeira Liga debut on 15 August, keeping a clean sheet in a 3\u20130 win over [[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.|Vit\u00f3ria de Guimar\u00e3es]] at the [[Est\u00e1dio do Drag\u00e3o]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Untroubled debut for Iker Casillas|url=http://www.marca.com/en/2015/08/15/en/football/international_football/1439675958.html|accessdate=16 August 2015|publisher=Marca|date=15 August 2015}}</ref> On 29 September 2015, he overtook Xavi to become the player with the most appearances in the [[European Cup and UEFA Champions League records and statistics#Appearances|Champions League]], making his record 152nd [[2015\u201316 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] appearance in a 2\u20131 home win over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]. That season, Casillas also broke [[Edwin van der Sar]]'s record for the most clean sheets in Champions League history, keeping his 51st clean sheet in the competition on 20 October 2015, in a 2\u20130 win over [[Maccabi Tel Aviv F.C.|Maccabi Tel Aviv]], as his team climbed top of Champions League Group G.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/fc-porto/story/2674590/iker-casillas-breaks-champions-league-clean-sheet-record|title=Iker Casillas breaks Van der Sar's Champions League clean sheet record|publisher=ESPN FC|date=21 October 2015|accessdate=3 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Edward Bennett|title=Most clean sheets in Champions League history: Iker Casillas moves ahead of Chelsea & Man United legends|url=http://www.caughtoffside.com/2015/04/23/most-clean-sheets-in-champions-league-history-iker-casillas-moves-ahead-of-chelsea-man-united-legends/7/|accessdate=1 June 2015|date=23 April 2015}}</ref> In January 2016, he was blamed for the away loss at Vit\u00f3ria de Guimar\u00e3es (1\u20130) in the [[2015\u201316 Primeira Liga|league]], following a high-profile error.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/35343302 |title=BBC Sport \u2013 Vitoria Guimaraes 1\u20130 FC Porto |date=18 January 2016 |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March 2017, Casillas set a new personal record for clean sheets in a single season with his sixteenth clean sheet in a 4\u20130 away win over [[F.C. Arouca|Arouca]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.as.com/en/2017/03/11/football/1489228458_612855.html|title=Iker Casillas breaks own Real Madrid clean sheet record|publisher=AS.com|author1=David F. Sanchidri\u00e1n|date=11 March 2017|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calciomercato.com/en/news/spanish-goalkeeping-legend-breaks-his-own-record-set-at-real-mad-75686|title=Spanish goalkeeping legend breaks his own record set at Real Madrid|publisher=Calciomercato.com|date=11 March 2017|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref> On 14 March, Casillas made his 175th appearance in UEFA club competitions in a 1\u20130 away defeat to Juventus in the second leg of the round of 16 of the [[2016\u201317 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]], overtaking [[Paolo Maldini]] as the player with the [[UEFA club competition records and statistics#Top appearances in UEFA club competitions|most appearances in European club matches]].<ref name=\"record-setting UEFA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/soccer/gallery/iker-casillas-uefa-competition-record-real-madrid-porto-goalkeeper-paolo-maldini-031417|title=The biggest moments in Iker Casillas\u2019 record-setting UEFA career|publisher=Fox Sports|author1=Alex Dowd|date=14 March 2017|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 September, Casillas equalled [[Ryan Giggs]]'s record of playing in 19 consecutive UEFA Champions League campaigns when he appeared in Porto's 3\u20131 home defeat to [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]] in the [[2017\u201318 UEFA Champions League|2017\u201318 edition of the tournament]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/report?gameId=495317|title=Cenk Tosun stunner leads Besiktas past Porto at the Estadio do Dragao|publisher=ESPN FC|date=13 September 2017|accessdate=10 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Casillas equals Giggs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/en/football/international-football/2017/09/13/59b997f946163f51288b4603.html|title=Iker Casillas equals Giggs' Champions League record|publisher=www.marca.com|author1=Lorenzo Lara|author2=Geoff Gillingham|date=13 September 2017|accessdate=10 October 2017}}</ref> On 2 April 2018, Casillas played his 1,000th match as a professional in Porto's 2\u20130 loss at [[C.F. Os Belenenses|Belenenses]].<ref name=thousand>{{cite news|title=Spain legend Iker Casillas makes 1,000th appearances in Porto defeat|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/fc-porto/story/3440954/spain-legend-iker-casillas-makes-1000th-appearances-in-porto-defeat|accessdate=3 April 2018|publisher=ESPN FC|date=2 April 2018}}</ref> In May, he won his first trophy with the club as they won the league title for the first time since 2013.<ref name=talksport>{{cite news|title=Porto break Benfica dominance in Portugal to win first league title since 2013 and have a massive party|url=https://talksport.com/football/porto-break-benfica-dominance-portugal-win-first-league-title-2013-and-have-massive-party|accessdate=10 May 2018|publisher=Talksport|date=7 May 2018}}</ref> The [[2017\u201318 Primeira Liga]] title was confirmed after [[Sporting CP]] and [[Benfica]] tied their respective match.<ref>{{cite web|title=FC Porto crowned champions|url=http://theportugalnews.com/news/fc-porto-crowned-champions/45528|website=The Portugal News Online|publisher=Anglopress Lda|accessdate=12 May 2018}}</ref> On 17 May 2018, he renewed his contract with Porto for another year.<ref>{{cite news|last1=AS|first1=Diario|title=Casillas to continue with Porto for another year|url=https://en.as.com/en/2018/05/17/football/1526572595_088309.html|work=AS.com|date=17 May 2018|accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 August, Casillas started in Porto's 3\u20131 victory over [[C.D. Aves|Desportivo das Aves]] in the [[2018 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira]].<ref name=\"2018-Superta\u00e7a\"/> He surpassed Giggs' record during the 2018\u201319 season, appearing in his 20th consecutive UEFA Champions League campaign.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://en.as.com/en/2018/12/13/football/1544694127_187030.html |title=Champions League: Iker Casillas still setting European records |publisher=AS |last1=Vidal |first1=Miguel |date=13 December 2018 |accessdate=10 January 2019}}</ref> On 11 December, Casillas, in a 3\u20132 away win over Galatasaray, became the first player to reach the knock-out stage 19 times,<ref name=\"auto\"/> and become only the second player after Cristiano Ronaldo to win 100 Champions League matches.<ref name=\"100 wins UCL\"/> He made 31 league appearances throughout the season as Porto finished in second place, but his season was cut short after he suffered \"an acute myocardial infarction\" during training on 1 May 2019.<ref name=\"heart attack\"/><ref name=\"coaching-role\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48990814 |title=Iker Casillas given coaching role at Porto two months after having heart attack |work=BBC Sport |date=15 July 2019 |accessdate=25 July 2019 }}</ref> He was discharged from hospital on 6 May, but commented that he was uncertain about his future.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48179324 |title=Iker Casillas: Porto goalkeeper discharged from hospital after heart attack |work=BBC Sport |date=6 May 2019 |accessdate=5 November 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, following his heart attack two months earlier, Casillas returned for pre-season training.<ref>{{Cite web | URL = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48833021 |title = Iker Casillas reports for pre-season duty with Porto two months after having a heart attack | website = BBC | date = 1 July 2019 | access-date = 2 July 2019 }}</ref> Later that month, Porto announced that he had been given a role with the club's coaching staff as he continued his recovery.<ref name=\"coaching-role\"/> In August, he was named in Porto's squad for the 2019\u201320 season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/fc-porto/story/3916464/casillas-named-in-porto-squad-for-new-season |title=Casillas named in Porto squad for new season |work=ESPN FC |date=9 August 2019 |accessdate=2 September 2019 }}</ref> In September, he shared the results of his medical tests on social media;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.as.com/en/2019/09/16/football/1568668213_201967.html |title=Iker Casillas shares physical data analytics from Porto training session: \"I'm still in the fight...\" |publisher=AS.com |date=16 September 2019 |accessdate=30 October 2019 }}</ref> at the end of the month, he stated that he would wait until March of the following year to see how he is progressing with his recovery before deciding whether to return to playing or retire. In October, he posted a photo of himself working out in the club's gym on [[Instagram]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.as.com/en/2019/10/16/football/1571218498_759045.html |title=Iker Casillas delights fans with treadmill workout photograph |publisher=AS.com |date=16 October 2019 |accessdate=30 October 2019 }}</ref> He resumed training on 4 November.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://en.as.com/en/2019/11/04/football/1572880992_194193.html |title=Iker Casillas returns to training |work=AS.com |date=4 November 2019 |accessdate=5 November 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nOn 18 February 2020, Casillas announced his retirement from football.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/porto-reveal-casillas-retirement-as-he-runs-for-rfef/f8sfyqq7svx11jt5ylhj5jafk|title=Porto reveal Casillas retirement as he runs for RFEF presidency|website=Goal.com|date=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Youth career===\nCasillas debuted for Spain at the [[Spain national under-17 football team|under-17 level]]. At age 16, he was the youngest player in the Spanish squad that placed third at the [[1997 FIFA U-17 World Championship]] in Egypt. He was later made captain of the U17s. Two years later, he went on to win the [[1999 FIFA World Youth Championship|FIFA World Youth Championship]] and the [[1999 UEFA\u2013CAF Meridian Cup|UEFA\u2013CAF Meridian Cup]] that same year. Initially second-choice, he soon worked his way up to first-choice and eventually earned his first senior cap following some brilliant performances at club level.\n\n===Senior debut, Euro 2000 and 2002 World Cup===\nCasillas is currently the second most capped player in the history of the [[Spain national football team|Spain national team]]. Following his full international debut at the senior level on 3 June 2000 against [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]] (at 19 years and 14 days), Casillas was an unused substitute at [[UEFA Euro 2000]]. He was part of the roster for the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]], initially as the understudy to [[Santiago Ca\u00f1izares]]. Coincidentally, he became first-choice when Ca\u00f1izares had to withdraw from the tournament due to injury from a freak accident.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/team_pages/spain/newsid_1994000/1994707.stm | title = Canizares out of World Cup | website = BBC Sport | date = 17 May 2002 | access-date = 2 July 2019}}</ref> At 21, Casillas was one of the youngest first-choice goalkeepers in the tournament. He played an instrumental role in Spanish progression when he saved two penalties in the shoot-out during the round of 16 match against the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]], earning him the nickname \"The Saint\". One of his saves during the quarter-final against [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] during the 2002 World Cup was rated by [[FIFA]] as one of the top ten saves of all time.<ref>FIFA Fever Centennial Anniversary (1904\u20132004) DVD</ref>\n\n===Euro 2004 and 2006 World Cup===\nCasillas played in all eight Group six fixtures during [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]] [[UEFA Euro 2004 qualifying|qualifying]], conceding just four goals. He kept a clean sheet in the second leg victory of the playoff against [[Norway national football team|Norway]] which ended 3\u20130 in [[Oslo]], and started all of Spain's Euro 2004 matches. He was the first choice for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]], [[Captain (association football)|captaining]] the team twice, but could not prevent ''La Roja'' from losing 3\u20131 to a [[Zinedine Zidane]]-inspired [[France national football team|France]] in the Round of 16.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4991524.stm |title=Spain 1\u20133 France |work=BBC Sport |date=27 June 2006 |accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Euro 2008===\nWith the exclusion of his Real Madrid teammate [[Ra\u00fal (footballer)|Ra\u00fal]] from the squad for [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]], Casillas was given the captain's armband. He started the first two [[UEFA Euro 2008 Group D|Group D]] games against [[Russia national football team|Russia]] and Sweden before being rested in place of second-choice goalkeeper [[Pepe Reina]] for Spain's group stage elimination of [[Greece national football team|Greece]]. Casillas saved two penalties from [[Antonio Di Natale]] and [[Daniele De Rossi]] as Spain eliminated [[Italy national football team|Italy]] in the quarter-finals with a 4\u20132 shootout win following a goalless draw on 22 June.<ref>{{Cite news| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2008/7468465.stm | title = Spain 0\u20130 Italy (4\u20132 pens) | work=BBC News | date=22 June 2008 | accessdate=5 January 2010|first=Phil|last=McNulty}}</ref> Spain later went on to win the competition with a 1\u20130 win over [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in the [[UEFA Euro 2008 Final|final]] on 29 June. Casillas kept clean sheets in all of the quarter-final, semi-final and final matches, with Sweden's first round goal by [[Zlatan Ibrahimovi\u0107]] being the last one scored against him. On 29 June 2008, Casillas became the first goalkeeper-captain to lift the [[UEFA European Championship]] trophy when Spain beat Germany in the final.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=232286&cc=4716&league=UEFA.EURO | title = Germany 0\u20131 Spain: Torres ends Spain's pain | publisher = [[Soccernet]] | date = 29 June 2008 | accessdate =8 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2008, Casillas and back-up Pepe Reina broke the national record for the longest time spent without conceding a goal. The pair went unbeaten for 710 minutes, longer than Spain's longest-serving goalkeeper [[Andoni Zubizarreta]] and Paco Buyo. [[Wesley Sonck]] of [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] ended their goalless streak when he scored against them a [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualifying|2010 World Cup qualifying]] match.\n\nCasillas was the highest-ranked goalkeeper (fourth place) in the [[2008 Ballon d'Or]], behind [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], [[Lionel Messi]] and national teammate [[Fernando Torres]]. Also in 2008, Casillas was named the world's best goalkeeper by the [[International Federation of Football History & Statistics]] (IFFHS).<ref name=\"Faulhaber\">{{cite web|author=Ingo Faulhaber |url=http://www.iffhs.de/?388d85ff8b00388f05f68e05b85fdcdc3bfcdc0aec70aeedb8a212 |title=IFFHS |publisher=Iffhs.de |accessdate=7 May 2009}}</ref> He also came in third place in the best goalkeepers of all time ranking, beating [[Oliver Kahn]].<ref name=\"Faulhaber\" />\n\n===2009 Confederations Cup and 2010 World Cup===\nCasillas was Spain's starting goalkeeper during the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]] in South Africa, making four appearances as Spain finished the tournament in third place. On 5 September 2009, after a 5\u20130 win over Belgium in a [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group 5#Spain v Belgium|qualifying match for the World Cup]], Casillas equalled Andoni Zubizarreta's national record of 56 clean sheets, and during the Spanish team's next match, against [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]] on 9 September 2009, he surpassed Zubizarreta as the record holder for the most Spanish international clean sheets (this being achieved in Casillas' 98th appearance for the national team, while Zubizarreta made 126 before his retirement).<ref>{{cite web|title=PROBABILI FORMAZIONI/Spagna-Francia: ultime novit\u00e0 (qualificazioni mondiali gruppo I)|url=http://www.ilsussidiario.net/News/Calcio-e-altri-Sport/Altre-squadre/2012/10/16/PROBABILI-FORMAZIONI-Spagna-Francia-ultime-novita-qualificazioni-mondiali-gruppo-I-/329556/|accessdate=1 June 2015|language=Italian|date=16 October 2012}}</ref> Two months later, Casillas made his [[List of footballers with 100 or more caps|100th appearance]] for Spain in its friendly win over [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], making him only the third player in history of Spanish football to ever reach this far internationally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=284407&cc=5739&league=FIFA.FRIENDLY|title=Alonso bags brace as Spain underline World Cup credentials|date= 14 November 2009 |work=ESPN Soccernet|accessdate=8 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Casillas besando la Copa del Mundo de f\u00fatbol.jpg|thumb|Casillas with the [[FIFA World Cup Trophy|World Cup trophy]] during celebrations in Spain, July 2010]]\nOn 11 July 2010, Casillas captained Spain to [[2010 FIFA World Cup|their first ever World Cup title]] with a 1\u20130 win against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]].<ref name=\"Iniesta sinks Dutch with late strike\">{{Cite news|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=264123&cc=5739&ver=global|title=Iniesta sinks Dutch with late strike|date= 11 July 2010|work=[[ESPNsoccernet]]|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref> In so doing, he became the third ever goalkeeper to captain a World Cup winning side (along with [[Gianpiero Combi]] in [[1934 FIFA World Cup|1934]] and [[Dino Zoff]] in [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]]; the feat was later also achieved by [[Hugo Lloris]] in [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]]). He was voted the tournament's best goalkeeper and awarded the [[Yashin Award|Golden Glove]]. In the course of the finals in South Africa, he kept five clean sheets, conceded two goals and saved a penalty in the quarter-final against [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]]. In the [[2010 FIFA World Cup Final|final]], he made two crucial stops from Netherlands' [[Arjen Robben]] with the score at 0\u20130 after the Dutchman had passed all the defenders.<ref name=\"Iniesta sinks Dutch with late strike\"/> Before he went to pick up the [[FIFA World Cup Trophy|World Cup trophy]], Casillas would later state that images of the past captains doing the same was in his head, reeling them off in perfect order going back to the first World Cup he saw as a youngster:\n\n{{quote|\u201cFrom when I was small, I saw [[Lothar Matth\u00e4us|Matth\u00e4us]] lift it. I saw [[Dunga]] lift it, I saw [[Didier Deschamps|Deschamps]] lift it, I saw [[Cafu]] lift it, [[Fabio Cannavaro|Cannavaro]]\u2026 so to watch me lift it, I could watch it tomorrow, I could watch it within 10 years and it will always make me emotional because it\u2019s incomparable.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |title=A riot of colour, emotion and memories: the World Cup stands alone in the field of sport|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/world-cup-russia-2018-preview-lionel-messi-ronaldo-italia-90-98-england-brazil-germany-france-a8392211.html |accessdate=20 August 2018 |work=The Independent}}</ref>}}\n\nOn 15 November 2011, Casillas became Spain's most capped player, breaking Andoni Zubizarreta's record after starting for Spain in their 2\u20132 draw against [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Enis Koylu|title=Real Madrid's Iker Casillas hoping for many more Spain appearances even after equalling all-time record|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/real-madrids-iker-casillas-hoping-132500532.html|publisher=Sports Yahoo|accessdate=1 June 2015|date=11 November 2011}}</ref> On 29 February 2012, in Spain's 5\u20130 win over [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]], Casillas equalled Edwin van der Sar's record of 72 international clean sheets. On 30 May, in Spain's 4\u20131 win over South Korea, Casillas came on for Pepe Reina on the 82nd minute mark. This set the record for most international victories with 95 giving Casillas yet another record to his name. On 6 June, In Spain's 1\u20130 win over [[China national football team|China PR]], Casillas set the record for most international clean sheets with 74.<ref name=\"International feats\">{{cite web|url=http://m.fifa.com/news/y=2012/m=5/news=international-feats-and-fitting-farewell-1641297.html|title=International feats and a fitting farewell|publisher=FIFA|accessdate=1 June 2015|date=30 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Euro 2012===\n\n[[File:Iker Casillas Euro 2012 final trophy.jpg|right|thumb|Casillas lifting the [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]] trophy, the third consecutive major title for [[Spain national football team|Spain]], achieving a historic [[Double (association football)#International Double|treble]]]]\nPrior to [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]], there had been growing tensions in the dressing room among Spanish players who played for rival clubs Barcelona and Real Madrid; this led manager [[Vicente del Bosque]] to declare that any player who carried this hostility with them at international level would be dropped from the team. As such, Casillas, [[Carles Puyol]], and Xavi called a summit with the manager and the other Spanish players, in order to ease tensions; Casillas was praised in the media for his role in successfully uniting the dressing room.<ref name=\"head to head\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/spanish-primera-division/15/blog/post/3479536/barcelona-vs-real-madrid-el-clasico-storylines-to-watch |title=Insiders talk Clasico: Camp Nou hoodoo, Messi, Ronaldo, pasillo, more |publisher=ESPN FC |date=4 May 2018 |accessdate=5 November 2019 }}</ref> On 1 July 2012, Casillas became the first player to reach 100 international wins for his country as Spain defeated Italy 4\u20130 in the [[UEFA Euro 2012 Final|Euro 2012 final]], as Spain successfully defended their title to win their third consecutive major international trophy. He also set another record with his 509 minutes without conceding a goal in that year's [[UEFA Euro 2012|European Championship]], keeping five consecutive clean sheets and breaking the longstanding tally of 494 minutes set by Italian goalkeeper [[Dino Zoff]].<ref name=\"Casillas, world record-breaking goalkeeper\">{{cite web|author1=Javier Estepa|title=Casillas, world record-breaking goalkeeper|url=http://www.marca.com/2012/07/02/en/football/national_teams/1341180644.html|publisher=Marca|accessdate=1 June 2015|date=2 July 2012}}</ref> The only goal he conceded, scored by Antonio Di Natale, came in Spain's opening match of the tournament, a 1\u20131 draw against eventual runners-up Italy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Di Natale: \u201cThe goal I scored against Casillas at the 2012 European Championships is the most important. Reaching Roberto Baggio\u2019s tally is my goal now|url=http://vivoazzurro.it/en/news/di-natale-il-gol-casillas-alleuropeo-2012-il-piu-prestigioso-ora-voglio-raggiungere-roberto-baggio/|accessdate=14 May 2015|date=28 November 2014}}</ref> Casillas then continued his new record unbeaten streak with Spain to 817 minutes, until it was finally broken by [[Olivier Giroud]]'s injury-time goal on 16 October of that year, which came in a 1\u20131 home draw against France in a [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2014 World Cup qualifying match]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elartedf.com/the-saint/ |title=The Saint |publisher=www.elartedf.com |last1=Purty |first1=Varun |date=2 July 2017 |accessdate=5 November 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/olivier-giroud-ends-spains-perfect-run-after-hugo-lloris-turns-on-the-heroics-for-france-8214105.html |title=Olivier Giroud ends Spain's perfect run after Hugo Lloris turns on the heroics for France |work=The Independent |last1=Jenson |first1=Pete |date=17 October 2012 |accessdate=5 November 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/oct/16/spain-france-world-cup-report |title=France's Olivier Giroud levels in last minute to put Spain in jeopardy |work=The Guardian |last1=Lowe |first1=Sid |date=16 October 2012 |accessdate=5 November 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===2013 Confederations Cup and 2014 World Cup===\nIn June 2013, Casillas represented Spain at the [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup|2013 Confederations Cup]] in Brazil, making three appearances as Spain reached the [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup Final|final]], only to be defeated 3\u20130 by the [[Brazil national football team|hosts Brazil]] on 30 June, at the [[Maracan\u00e3 Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/jun/30/brazil-spain-live-confederations-cup-final|title= Brazil v Spain: Confederations Cup final \u2013 as it happened|date=1 July 2013|work=Guardian UK|accessdate=4 July 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Casillas was selected to represent Spain in his fourth [[2014 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2014/06/12/en/football/national_teams/1402602871.html|title=Casillas: \"Winning a second World Cup is in our hands\"|date=12 June 2014|accessdate=14 June 2014|work=Marca}}</ref> In the team's opening match, he made two mistakes leading to goals from [[Stefan de Vrij]] and [[Robin van Persie]] as the champions were defeated 5\u20131 by the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/06/13/us-soccer-world-m3-esp-ned-idUSKBN0EO2GF20140613|title=Superb Dutch destroy sorry Spain 5\u20131|date=13 June 2014|accessdate=14 June 2014|work=Reuters}}</ref> After the match, Casillas apologised for the defeat and called his performance the worst of his career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jun/14/spain-iker-casillas-worst-performance-holland|title=Spain's Iker Casillas apologises for 'worst performance of my career'|date=14 June 2014|accessdate=14 June 2014|work=The Guardian}}</ref> He also started in Spain's second group game against [[Chile national football team|Chile]], which they lost 2\u20130 and were subsequently eliminated from the World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Jacopo Gerna|title=Brasile 2014, la Spagna chiude un ciclo irripetibile. Come il Barcellona|trans-title=Brazil 2014, Spain ends an un-repeatable cycle. Just like Barcelona|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Mondiali/18-06-2014/brasile-2014-spagna-chiude-ciclo-irripetibile-come-barcellona-80972204252.shtml|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|accessdate=18 May 2015|language=Italian|date=18 June 2014}}</ref> He received criticism for his role in Chile's second goal, where he punched [[Alexis S\u00e1nchez]]'s free kick into the path of the goalscorer [[Charles Ar\u00e1nguiz]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/27912766|title=World Cup 2014: Iker Casillas mistake gifts Chile's second goal|date=18 June 2014|work=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/88/spain/2015/02/07/8706082/iker-casillas-five-biggest-blunders-from-the-past-year|title=Iker Casillas\u2019 five biggest blunders from the past year|date=7 February 2015|work=Goal.com}}</ref> On 23 June, Casillas was left on the bench for Spain's final game against [[Australia national soccer team|Australia]], with Pepe Reina playing instead.\n\n===Euro 2016===\nOn 5 September 2015, Casillas kept a clean sheet in his 100th game as Spain's captain, a 2\u20130 [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying|Euro 2016 qualifying]] win over [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]] at the [[Estadio Carlos Tartiere]] in [[Oviedo]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/match/spain-vs-slovakia/1653318/report|title=Spain 2\u20130 Slovakia: Alba and Iniesta put Spain top|publisher=Goal.com|date=5 September 2015|accessdate=6 September 2015}}</ref> On 13 November, Casillas kept his 100th international clean sheet with Spain in a 2\u20130 friendly win over England, in Alicante, becoming the first goalkeeper ever \u2013 male or female \u2013 to reach this landmark.<ref name=\"100 clean sheets for Spain\">{{cite web|url=https://as.com/diarioas/2015/11/13/english/1447451183_829981.html|title=Casillas into three figures \u2013 100 clean sheets for Spain|publisher=as.com|date=13 November 2015|accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref> He equalled the Latvian [[Vit\u0101lijs Astafjevs]]' European record of 167 caps on 27 March 2016 by playing in a friendly against [[Romania national football team|Romania]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=2158601.html?rss=2158601+Casillas+equals+European+caps+record|title=Casillas equals European caps record|publisher=UEFA|date=27 March 2016|accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 May, Casillas was named to Vicente del Bosque's final 23-man [[UEFA Euro 2016 squads#Spain|Spain squad]] for [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=2370011.html|title=Isco and Sa\u00fal cut from Spain squad|publisher=UEFA.com|author=Daniel Huerta|date=31 May 2016|accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref> The following day, he became the most-capped European player by earning his 167th cap in a 6\u20131 friendly win over South Korea in [[Salzburg]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/4961/international-football/2016/06/01/24156662/casillas-becomes-most-capped-player-in-european-history|title=Casillas becomes most capped player in European history|publisher=Goal.com|last1=Judge|first1=Matthew|date=1 June 2016|accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref> During the tournament, he was the second-choice goalkeeper behind [[David de Gea]]; Casillas did not make an appearance during the tournament as Spain was eliminated in the Round of 16 following a 2\u20130 defeat to Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/uefa-champions-league/2/blog/post/3081539/a-history-of-iker-casillas-vs-gianluigi-buffon-through-the-years|title=A history of Iker Casillas vs. Gianluigi Buffon through the years|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Dermot Corrigan|date=14 March 2017|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2018 World Cup===\nOn 21 May 2018, Casillas was left out of [[Julen Lopetegui]]'s final 23-man Spain squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/spain-world-cup-squad-2018-russia-julen-lopetegui-selection-team-alvaro-morata-cesc-fabregas-a8361736.html|title=Spain World Cup squad: Julen Lopetegui\u2019s team is as strong as they come and blessed with versatility|publisher=The Independent|author1=Ed Malyon|date=21 May 2018|accessdate=22 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/world-cup/news/2018-world-cup-spain-preview-schedule-tv-and-stream-info-squad-and-players-to-watch/|title=2018 World Cup: Spain preview, schedule, TV and stream info, squad and players to watch|publisher=CBS Sports|author1=Roger Gonzalez|date=22 May 2018|accessdate=22 May 2018}}</ref> In November, he hinted a return to the [[Spain national football team|Spain football team]] and Real Madrid.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://en.as.com/en/2018/11/16/football/1542407030_248646.html | title = Iker Casillas would happily return to Real Madrid and Spain squad | website = AS | date = 17 November 2018 | access-date = 14 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play and reception==\n[[File:Iker Casillas Euro 2012 final 02.jpg|thumb|right|Casillas making a save in the [[UEFA Euro 2012 Final]]]]\n{{Quote|width=100%|align=Center|quote=\"Honestly, I don't have to use up many words to say how good he is, the results are there for all to see. He has won everything there is to win and has been on the same great level for so many years now, which is possibly hardest of all for a goalkeeper. Spain almost never concede goals and Casillas is the main reason for that.\"|source=Juventus and Italy goalkeeper [[Gianluigi Buffon]] on Casillas prior to the [[UEFA Euro 2012 Final]].<ref name=\"head to head\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=1836741.html|title=Casillas and Buffon go head to head|publisher=UEFA|author1=Richard Aikman|author2=Graham Hunter|date=30 June 2012|accessdate=14 May 2015}}</ref>}}\nWidely considered by pundits, as well as both former and current goalkeeping colleagues, as one of the greatest goalkeepers of all time,<ref name=\"Trendsetters Buffon, Casillas keep it legendary\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/blog/tactics-and-analysis/67/post/1839716/trendsetting-goalkeepers-buffon-casillas-keep-it-legendary|title=Trendsetters Buffon, Casillas keep it legendary|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Michael Cox|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"king\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/en/2015/07/12/en/football/real_madrid/1436718760.html|title=King of the keepers|publisher=Marca|author1=J. L. HURTADO|author2=H. CEREZO|date=7 December 2015|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/75977/buffon-%E2%80%98casillas-best%E2%80%99|title=Buffon: \u2018Casillas the best\u2019|publisher=Football Italia|date=19 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ranks\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/sports/soccer/blog/_/name/schaerlaeckens_leander/id/6067671/manchester-united-edwin-van-der-sar-ranks-all-greats|title=Van der Sar ranks among the all-time greats|publisher=ESPN|date=28 January 2011|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/en/2015/05/04/en/football/real_madrid/1430759936.html|title=Zoff: \"Buffon or Casillas? I prefer Casillas\"|publisher=www.marca.com|date=5 April 2015|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref> Casillas was given the nickname \"''San Iker''\" (\"Saint Iker\") throughout his career, for his precocious performances as a youngster, and due to his ability to produce acrobatic and decisive saves. In his prime, he was a spectacular, well-rounded, and athletic keeper, who was known in particular for his outstanding agility, reflexes, consistency and shot-stopping, as well as his foot-work, positioning between the posts, concentration, and speed when [[Goalkeeper (association football)#Sweeper-keeper|rushing off his line]] in one on one situations;<ref name=\"Iker Casillas ESPN Profile\"/><ref name=\"king\"/><ref name=\"club\">{{cite web|url=http://it.uefa.com/news/newsid=520743.html|title=Casillas nel club dei numero uno|publisher=UEFA.com|language=Italian|date=28 March 2007|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Buffon-Casillas\">{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/speciali/calcio/europei/polonia-ucraina2012/squadre/italia/2012/06/30/news/italia_spagna_ruolo_per_ruolo-38269386/|title=Da Buffon-Casillas a Balotelli-Torres Italia contro Spagna ruolo per ruolo|publisher=La Repubblica|language=Italian|author1=Alessandro Vocalelli|date=30 June 2012|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"look up\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/spain/9367049/Euro-2012-I-look-up-to-Italy-goalkeeper-Gianluigi-Buffon-reveals-Spains-No-1-Iker-Casillas.html|title=Euro 2012: I look up to Italy goalkeeper Gianluigi Buffon, reveals Spain's No 1 Iker Casillas|publisher=The Telegraph|author1=Henry Winter|date=30 June 2012|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laliga.es/en/news/kiko-casilla-for-a-goalkeeper-messi-and-cristiano-are-the-opponents-to-beat|title=Kiko Casilla: \"For a goalkeeper, Messi and Cristiano are the opponents to beat\"|publisher=La Liga|date=2 January 2015|accessdate=25 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816020338/http://www.laliga.es/en/news/kiko-casilla-for-a-goalkeeper-messi-and-cristiano-are-the-opponents-to-beat|archive-date=16 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Left-Footed World XI\">{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1247190-picking-an-all-time-left-footed-world-football-xi#slide1 |title=The All-Time, Left-Footed World Football XI |publisher=Bleacher Report |author1=Karl Matchett |date=4 July 2012 |accessdate=21 January 2019 }}</ref> he has also stood out for his penalty-saving abilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/en/2015/10/05/en/football/international_football/1444072758.html|title=The game's top penalty-stoppers|publisher=Marca|date=10 May 2015|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/news/y=2012/m=2/news=meet-the-penalty-killers-1585700.html|title=Meet the penalty killers|publisher=FIFA.com|date=17 February 2012|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> In spite of his reserved character, he has been highly regarded for his strong personality, calm composure under pressure, ability to organise his defence, and leadership from the back throughout his career.<ref name=\"Iker Casillas ESPN Profile\"/><ref name=\"Left-Footed World XI\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/casillas-iker-final/|title=Spain victory lies in the hands of Casillas|publisher=Sportsnet.ca|date=15 September 2009|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Casillas vs. Buffon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11946/9846537/iker-casillas-versus-gianluigi-buffon-which-one-is-the-better-goalkeeper|title=Iker Casillas versus Gianluigi Buffon: Which one is the better goalkeeper?|publisher=Sky Sports|author=Adam Bate|date=13 May 2015|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref> Gianluigi Buffon described Casillas as the best goalkeeper of his era with his hands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://90min.com/posts/2732836-gianluigi-buffon-names-arsenal-s-petr-cech-as-the-best-goalkeeper-of-his-era|title=Gianluigi Buffon Names Arsenal's Petr Cech as the Best Goalkeeper of his Era|publisher=90min|author=Mahmoud Jaber|date=19 November 2015|accessdate=8 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nA precocious talent in his youth, Casillas has drawn praise for his longevity and consistency at the top level,<ref name=\"Trendsetters Buffon, Casillas keep it legendary\"/><ref name=\"king\"/><ref name=\"club\"/> as well as his discipline in training;<ref name=\"head to head\"/> despite his reputation and goalkeeping ability, however, due to his lack of notable height and strong physical attributes, he has been criticised at times by pundits for struggling to command his area, and for his handling and indecisiveness when coming out to claim crosses, as he often prefers to punch the ball away. He also received criticism in the media for a series of errors and less consistent performances in his later career, as he lost some of his speed and mobility with age.<ref name=\"Iker Casillas ESPN Profile\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/2013/09/16/en/football/real_madrid/1379348389.html|title=Casillas to face bombardment|publisher=Marca.com|author1=Hugo Cerezo|date=16 September 2013|accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Casillas is not commanding at crosses or good with his feet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/en/2014/12/23/en/football/real_madrid/1419339112.html|title=\"Casillas is not commanding at crosses or good with his feet\"|publisher=Marca.com|date=23 December 2014|accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/speciali/mondiali/brasile2014/spagna/2014/06/14/news/il_declino_di_san_iker_simbolo_di_una_squadra_che_non_c_pi-88923979/|title=l declino di San Iker, simbolo di una squadra che non c'\u00e8 pi\u00f9|publisher=La Repubblica|language=Italian|author1=Andrea Sorrentino|date=14 June 2014|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2627455-5-reasons-why-gianluigi-donnarumma-needs-to-continue-his-career-at-ac-milan#slide0 |title=5 Reasons Why Gianluigi Donnarumma Needs to Continue His Career at AC Milan |publisher=Bleacher Report |last1=Lopresti |first1=Sam |date=25 March 2016 |accessdate=8 October 2019 }}</ref> Although he has occasionally been criticised by pundits for his limited skills with the ball at his feet in comparison to other Spanish goalkeepers, Casillas's distribution with both his hands and feet has generally been reliable throughout his career, and he is capable of sending the ball into deep areas of the pitch with his long throws and kicks with his left foot.<ref name=\"Trendsetters Buffon, Casillas keep it legendary\"/><ref name=\"Left-Footed World XI\"/><ref name=\"Casillas is not commanding at crosses or good with his feet\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/2012/11/25/en/football/real_madrid/1353873213.html|title=Casillas has problems with his footwork|publisher=Marca.com|date=25 November 2012|accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Sponsorship==\nIn January 2012, Casillas agreed a sponsorship deal with [[Adidas]] to wear their Response goalkeeping gloves and Predator football boots.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.footballboots.co.uk/4655-adidas-sign-iker-casillas-from-reebok.html | title = Adidas sign Iker Casillas from Reebok| publisher = FootballBoots.co.uk | accessdate =16 January 2012 }}</ref> The move to Adidas ended a long running association for Casillas with [[Reebok]], which started in 2004. In February 2005, Casillas was the football face of Reebok's \"I Am What I Am\" global integrated advertising campaign that linked all the brand's marketing efforts under one umbrella.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://corporate.reebok.com/en/about_reebok/faq_section/marketing/default.asp | title = Reebok Marketing| publisher = corporate.reebok.com | accessdate =16 January 2012 }}</ref> Adidas has been the parent company of Reebok since 2005.\n\n==Outside football==\n===Personal life===\nBetween 2004 and 2008, Casillas dated beauty pageant winner [[Eva Gonz\u00e1lez]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ruiz |first1=Borja |title=Eva Gonz\u00e1lez: su car\u00e1cter acaba con sus relaciones |url=https://www.elmundo.es/loc/2013/11/30/529895b761fd3d8f578b4580.html |website=El Mundo |accessdate=6 March 2019 |language=es |date=30 November 2013}}</ref> Since 2009, Casillas has been in a relationship with sports journalist [[Sara Carbonero]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/10340039.stm|title=Iker Casillas in spotlight over girlfriend role|work=[[BBC News]]|date=17 June 2010|accessdate=17 June 2010}}</ref> Their son Mart\u00edn was born on 3 January 2014 in [[Madrid]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.marca.com/2014/01/03/en/football/real_madrid/1388772056.html |title=That's my boy! Iker Casillas' son is born |newspaper=Marca |date=3 January 2014 |accessdate=30 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.es/estilo/gente/20140601/abci-bautizo-martin-casillas-201406012045.html|title=\u00cdker Casillas bautiza al peque\u00f1o Mart\u00edn de viajar a Brasil|date=22 December 2014|work=Yahoo}}</ref> In November 2015, the couple announced they were expecting their second child. On 20 March 2016, the couple married. On 2 June 2016, Sara gave birth to the couple's second child, Lucas.<ref name=\"Tribal Football\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/sara-carbonero-on-real-madrid-legend-iker-casillas-i-m-lucky-to-share-my-life-with-him-4087403|title= Sara Carbonero on Real Madrid legend Iker Casillas: I'm lucky to share my life with him|date=22 July 2015|accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 May 2019, during Porto's morning training session, Casillas was rushed to hospital after suffering a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] at the club's training ground, where his situation was stabilized.<ref name=\"heart attack\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48125061|title=Iker Casillas: Porto goalkeeper taken to hospital following heart problems|date=1 May 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=1 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fcporto.pt/en/news/20190501-en-information-on-the-clinical-condition-of-iker-casillas|title=Information on the clinical condition of Iker Casillas|publisher=FC Porto|date=1 May 2019|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref> Later that evening, Casillas, whose situation had improved, published a statement on [[Twitter]] himself with a picture where he gave thumbs up and thanked for the support he had received.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1123664609641103360|title=Todo controlado por aqu\u00ed, un susto grande pero con las fuerzas intactas. Much\u00edsimas gracias a todos por los mensajes y el cari\u00f1o \ud83d\ude03\ud83d\udcaa\ud83c\udffc|user=IkerCasillas|language=Spanish|date=1 May 2019|access-date=1 May 2019}}</ref> Later that month, it was announced that his wife was suffering from cancer.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48362541|title=Iker Casillas: Wife battling cancer weeks after keeper's heart attack|date=22 May 2019 | website = BBC Sport | access-date = 22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nA street in M\u00f3stoles has been renamed ''Avenida de Iker Casillas'' in his honour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/wm/starfuerbrasilien/596070/2/slideshow_der-weg-des-san-iker.html#|title=Ein Madridista sagt Adios Real: Der Weg des \"San Iker\"|trans-title=A Madridista says \"Adios Real\": The path of 'San Iker'|language=German|work=[[Kicker (sports magazine)|kicker]]|date=16 December 2013|accessdate=19 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 17 February 2020, Casillas confirmed his intention to stand as a candidate in the [[RFEF]] presidential elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://r1ooooo.blogspot.com/2020/02/real-madrid-legend-iker-casillas-run-presidency-spanish-fa-rfef.html|title=Real Madrid legend to run for presidency of Spanish FA|work=inside World Soccer|date=18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Charity===\nIn 2011, Casillas was appointed as a Goodwill Ambassador for the [[United Nations Development Programme]]'s [[Millennium Development Goals]].<ref>[http://content.undp.org/go/newsroom/2011/january/le-footballer-iker-casillas--nouvel-ambassadeur-de-bonne-volont--des-nations-unies.en Iker Casillas appointed new UNDP Goodwill Ambassador] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110414152718/http://content.undp.org/go/newsroom/2011/january/le-footballer-iker-casillas--nouvel-ambassadeur-de-bonne-volont--des-nations-unies.en |date=14 April 2011 }}. Content.undp.org (24 January 2011). Retrieved on 17 March 2012.</ref><ref>[https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=37365&Cr=undp&Cr1= Spain\u2019s goalkeeper Casillas to score poverty reduction goals as UN Goodwill Ambassador]. Un.org (24 January 2011). Retrieved on 17 March 2012.</ref>\n\nHe has his own charitable foundation, the ''Fundaci\u00f3n Iker Casillas''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ikercasillasworld.com/es/fundacion/fundacion-iker-casillas/|title=Objetivos de la Fundaci\u00f3n Iker Casillas|publisher=www.ikercasillasworld.com|language=Spanish|last1=Iker Casillas Foundation|accessdate=29 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001190651/http://www.ikercasillasworld.com/es/fundacion/fundacion-iker-casillas/|archive-date=1 October 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|18 February 2020}}<ref name=Soccerway/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/j/j1090.html|title=BDFutbol profile|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|National Cup{{efn|Appearances in [[Copa del Rey]], [[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]] and [[Ta\u00e7a da Liga]]}}\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[Real Madrid Castilla|Real Madrid B]] \n|[[1999\u20132000 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B#Group I|1999\u20132000]]\n|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]\n|4||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4||0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"17\"|[[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] \n|[[1999\u20132000 Real Madrid CF season|1999\u20132000]]\n|rowspan=\"16\"|[[La Liga]]\n|27||0||5||0||12{{efn|name=UCL|Appearances in [[UEF