{"title_page": "Crazy Rich Asians (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2018 film by Jon M. Chu}}\n{{good article}}\n{{use MDY|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Crazy Rich Asians\n| image          = Crazy_Rich_Asians_poster.png\n| alt            = A couple hugs each other against a colorful Chinese fan background\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Jon M. Chu]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Nina Jacobson]]\n* [[Brad Simpson (producer)|Brad Simpson]]\n* John Penotti \n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* Peter Chiarelli\n* [[Adele Lim]]\n}}\n| story          =\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Crazy Rich Asians]]''|[[Kevin Kwan]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Constance Wu]] <!-- PER BILLING ORDER -->\n* [[Henry Golding]]\n* [[Gemma Chan]]\n* [[Lisa Lu]]\n* [[Awkwafina]]\n* [[Ken Jeong]]\n* [[Michelle Yeoh]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Brian Tyler]]\n| cinematography = Vanja Cernjul\n| editing        = Myron Kerstein\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* SK Global Entertainment<ref name=\"prod\">{{cite news|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/dentons-tax-lawyer-ny-plays-072643044.html|title=Dentons Tax Lawyer From NY Plays Unlikely Role in 'Crazy Rich Asians' Success|date=November 6, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018|work=[[Yahoo! Finance]]|author=ALM Media}}</ref>\n* Starlight Culture Entertainment<ref name=\"prod\" />\n* [[Color Force]]<!--Cited in body-->\n* Ivanhoe Pictures<!--Cited in body-->\n* Electric Somewhere<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/asia/crazy-rich-asians-sequel-shoot-in-china-1203008180/#!|title='Crazy Rich Asians' Sequel to Shoot in China|date=October 29, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Frater|first=Patrick}}</ref>\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|8|7|[[Grauman's Chinese Theatre|TCL Chinese Theatre]]|2018|08|15|United States}}\n| runtime        = 121 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 120:30--><ref>{{cite web |title=''CRAZY RICH ASIANS'' (12A) |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/crazy-rich-asians-film |accessdate=August 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180817045240/https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/crazy-rich-asians-film |archive-date=August 17, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| country        = United States<br/>Singapore\n| language       = English <!-- Primary language of the film -->\n| budget         = $30 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |title=Crazy Rich Asians (2018)|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=crazyrichasians.htm |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n| gross          = $238.5 million<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Crazy Rich Asians''''' is a 2018 American [[romantic comedy]] film directed by [[Jon M. Chu]], from a screenplay by Peter Chiarelli and [[Adele Lim]], based on the [[Crazy Rich Asians|2013 novel of the same title]] by [[Kevin Kwan]]. The film stars [[Constance Wu]], [[Henry Golding]], [[Gemma Chan]], [[Lisa Lu]], [[Awkwafina]], [[Ken Jeong]], and [[Michelle Yeoh]]. It follows a [[Chinese Americans|Chinese-American]] professor who travels to meet her boyfriend's family and is surprised to discover they are among the richest in [[Singapore]].\n\nThe film was announced in August 2013 after the rights to the book were purchased. Many of the cast members signed on in the spring of 2017, and filming took place from April to June of that year in parts of [[New York City]] and [[Singapore]]. It is the first film by a [[major film studio|major Hollywood studio]] to feature a majority cast of Asian descent in a modern setting since ''[[The Joy Luck Club (film)|The Joy Luck Club]]'' in 1993.<!--(Memoirs of a Geisha was a period piece)--> Despite praise for that, the film did receive some criticism for casting [[biracial]] actors over [[Overseas Chinese|fully ethnically Chinese]] ones in certain roles. Additional criticism was directed at the film for failing to include non-Chinese Singaporean ethnic groups\u2014notably [[Malays (ethnic group)|Malay]] and [[Indian people|Indian]] actors\u2014as characters.\n\n''Crazy Rich Asians'' premiered on August 7, 2018, at the [[TCL Chinese Theatre]] in [[Los Angeles]] and was released theatrically in the United States on August 15, 2018, by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]. The film received positive reviews from critics, with praise for its acting, production and costume design. The film grossed over $238 million worldwide, making it the highest-grossing romantic comedy in a decade. The film received numerous accolades, including the [[76th Golden Globe Awards]] earning nominations for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical]] for Wu. It also received four nominations at the [[24th Critics' Choice Awards]], winning one for [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Comedy|Best Comedy]], and a [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]] at the [[25th Screen Actors Guild Awards]]. Two sequels, based on the novel's follow-ups ''[[China Rich Girlfriend]]'' and ''[[Rich People Problems]]'', are currently in development.\n\n==Plot==\nNick Young and his girlfriend Rachel Chu, an [[economics]] professor at [[New York University]] and [[New York City|New York]] native, travel to [[Singapore]] for the wedding of his best friend Colin, who is marrying Araminta Lee. In Singapore, Rachel visits her college friend Peik Lin and her family, who are shocked when she tells them she is dating Nick Young. Peik Lin reveals that Nick's family is extremely wealthy and famous, and are members of high society. At a dinner party at the Young estate, Nick introduces Rachel to his mother Eleanor, while his cousin Astrid discovers that her husband Michael, who comes from a more humble background than the Youngs, has been having an affair. Rachel senses that Eleanor dislikes her.\n\nAt Araminta's [[bachelorette party]], Rachel meets Amanda, who reveals she is Nick's former girlfriend and hints Rachel may not be able to integrate into such a high-class family with her lower background. Rachel finds her hotel room vandalized by the other girls, who deem her a gold-digger, but is comforted by Astrid. Nick attends Colin's [[bachelor party]], where he reveals to Colin his plan to propose to Rachel. Colin expresses his concern about the trouble it will cause them, especially with Nick being expected to stay in Singapore and run his family's corporation and Rachel loving her job in New York, as well as the difference in their statuses. Nick apologizes to Rachel for not telling her who he really was and takes her to make [[jiaozi]] dumplings with his family. Here, Eleanor recounts the sacrifices she made to become a part of the Young family and makes jabs at Rachel for her American background. Eleanor later privately recounts to Rachel how Nick's father had to cast his own green ring to propose to her as Nick's grandmother refused to give him the family ring, owing to Eleanor not being the first or even second choice. She tells Rachel that she will never be enough for Nick or his family. Peik Lin convinces Rachel to stand up to Eleanor and earns her respect. On the day of the wedding, Astrid confronts Michael about his affair; Michael blames his unhappiness and the great financial disparity between them on her.\n\nDuring the wedding reception, Eleanor and Nick's grandmother privately confront Rachel and Nick. Using the findings of a private investigation, Eleanor reveals that Rachel's father is alive, and Rachel was conceived through an adulterous affair, after which her mother, Kerry, abandoned her husband and fled to the United States. They demand that Nick stop seeing Rachel for fear of a scandal, as they cannot be linked to such a family. Rachel is stunned, as Kerry told her that her father was dead. She flees and stays at Peik Lin's home, depressed and unwilling to speak to Nick. Kerry arrives in Singapore, explaining that her husband was abusive and that the comfort an old classmate provided turned into love and a surprise pregnancy. She fled with baby Rachel in fear that her husband would kill them. Kerry reveals that Nick was the one who had called her to Singapore and urges Rachel to talk to him. When they meet, Nick apologizes and proposes to Rachel, saying that he is willing to leave his family behind to be with her.\n\nRachel arranges to meet Eleanor at a [[mahjong]] parlor. Over a game of mahjong, she reveals to Eleanor that she declined Nick's proposal so his relationship with his family would not be ruined. She tells Eleanor to remember that when Nick eventually marries someone \"good enough\" for her, it will be because of a selfless act on the part of Rachel, a girl Eleanor looks down upon. Meanwhile, Astrid moves out, telling Michael his ego, insecurities, and unwillingness to make their marriage work caused it to fail. Elsewhere Eleanor has a meeting with Nick.\n\nRachel and Kerry board a flight back to New York City at [[Singapore Changi Airport]], but are interrupted by Nick, who proposes with Eleanor's green ring, revealing her blessing. In tears, Rachel accepts and they stay in Singapore one more night for an engagement party, where Eleanor nods at Rachel in acknowledgment, Rachel having finally earned her respect. In a [[Post-credits scene|mid-credits scene]], Astrid and her ex-boyfriend Charlie Wu spot each other at the party; she discreetly smiles.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{multiple image|direction=vertical|total_width=175\n| image1 = Constance Wu in 2015 (cropped).jpg\n| alt1   = Costance Wu smiles, facing forward\n| image2 = Henry Golding in 2014.jpg\n| alt2   = Henry Golding smiles, facing forward\n| footer = [[Constance Wu]] (above) and [[Henry Golding]] play the lead characters Rachel Chu and Nick Young.\n}}\n* [[Constance Wu]] as Rachel Chu, Nick's girlfriend and Kerry's daughter<ref name=\"constance\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/constance-wu-star-crazy-rich-asians-960077 |title=Constance Wu to Star in 'Crazy Rich Asians' (Exclusive) |last=Ford |first=Rebecca |date=February 15, 2017 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=April 11, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170412083854/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/constance-wu-star-crazy-rich-asians-960077 |archive-date=April 12, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Henry Golding]] as Nicholas \"Nick\" Young, Rachel's boyfriend and Phillip and Eleanor's son<ref name=\"henry\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/crazy-rich-asians-lands-male-lead-988732 |title='Crazy Rich Asians' Lands Its Male Lead (Exclusive) |last=Ford |first=Rebecca |date=March 28, 2017 |access-date=April 11, 2017 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170401055827/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/crazy-rich-asians-lands-male-lead-988732 |archive-date=April 1, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/asia/henry-golding-talks-crazy-rich-asians-casting-controversies-1202622817/|title=Henry Golding Talks 'Crazy Rich Asians' and Asian Casting Controversies|last=Ramachandran|first=Naman|date=November 25, 2017|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=February 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206073622/https://variety.com/2017/film/asia/henry-golding-talks-crazy-rich-asians-casting-controversies-1202622817/|archive-date=February 6, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Michelle Yeoh]] as Eleanor Sung-Young, Nick's domineering mother and Phillip's wife<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/crazy-rich-asians-adds-michelle-yeoh-981172 |title='Crazy Rich 