h Performer\n| Awkwafina\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goldderby.com/article/2019/2019-gold-derby-film-awards-nominations-the-favourite-news-159748620/ |title=Gold Derby Film Awards nominations 2019: 'The Favourite' and 'A Star is Born' come out on top |last=Montgomery |first=Daniel |date=January 30, 2019 |publisher=[[Gold Derby]] |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Costume Design\n| Mary E. Vogt\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Ensemble\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''Crazy Rich Asians''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Golden Globe Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[76th Golden Globe Awards|January 6, 2019]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/golden-globe-nominations-2019-1203082075/|title=Golden Globe Nominations: Complete List|last=Staff |first=Variety |date=December 6, 2018 |work=Variety |accessdate=December 6, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress in a Motion Picture \u2013 Comedy or Musical]]\n| Constance Wu\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Hollywood Film Awards]]\n| [[22nd Hollywood Film Awards|November 4, 2018]]\n| Breakout Ensemble Award\n| rowspan=\"3\"| ''Crazy Rich Asians''\n| {{won|Honoree}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=\"HFA18\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/incredibles-2-hollywood-film-awards-honorees-1156216 |title=Hollywood Film Awards: 'Black Panther,' 'Incredibles 2' Among Latest Honorees |last=Kilday |first=Gregg |date=October 30, 2018|website=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=October 30, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Humanitas Prize]]\n| February 8, 2019\n| Comedy Feature Film\n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref name=\"HP19\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/humanitas-prize-nominations-2018-list-black-panther-this-is-us-1202509603/ | title=Humanitas Prize: 'Black Panther', 'This Is Us' Among Nominations |last=Hipes |first=Patrick |date=November 27, 2018|website=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=November 27, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[International Cinematographers Guild|International Cinematographers Guild Publicists Awards]]\n| February 22, 2019\n| Maxwell Weinberg Publicist Showmanship of the Year \u2013 Motion Picture\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite news|author=THR Staff|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/icg-publicists-awards-2019-winners-list-1181253|title=''Crazy Rich Asians,' 'The Late Show with Stephen Colbert' Feted at 2019 Publicists Awards|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=February 22, 2019|accessdate=February 24, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Location Managers Guild Awards]]\n| September 21, 2019\n| Outstanding Locations in Contemporary Film\n| Guy Sahibjahn\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite news|title=Nominations Announced For The 6th Annual Location Managers Guild International Awards|url=https://www.shootonline.com/spw/nominations-announced-6th-annual-location-managers-guild-international-awards|publisher=SHOOT online|date=18 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[Make-Up Artists and Hair Stylists Guild Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| February 16, 2019\n| [[Make-Up Artists and Hair Stylists Guild Award for Best Contemporary Make-Up in a Feature-Length Motion Picture|Best Contemporary Make-Up]]\n| Heike Merker, Irina Strukova\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/make-up-artists-hair-styling-guild-applies-its-awards-nominations-1202532593/ |title=Make-Up Artists & Hair Stylists Guild Applies Its Awards Nominations |author= Erik Pedersen| website= [[Make-Up Artists & Hair Stylists Guild]] |publisher=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |access-date= January 10, 2019 |quote=}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Make-Up Artists and Hair Stylists Guild Award for Best Contemporary Hair Styling in a Feature-Length Motion Picture|Best Contemporary Hair Styling]]\n| Heike Merker, Sophia Knight\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[National Board of Review]]\n| [[National Board of Review Awards 2018|January 8, 2019]]\n| [[National Board of Review Award for Best Cast|Best Acting By an Ensemble]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''Crazy Rich Asians''\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lewis |first1=Hilary |title='Green Book' Named Best Film by National Board of Review |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/green-book-named-best-film-by-national-board-review-1164206 |accessdate=November 28, 2018 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=November 27, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"3\" | [[People's Choice Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[44th People's Choice Awards|November 11, 2018]]\n| The Comedy Movie of 2018\n| {{Nominated}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.eonline.com/shows/peoples_choice_awards/news/963752/2018-people-s-choice-awards-complete-list-of-nominations|title=2018 People's Choice Awards: Complete List of Nominations|accessdate=September 5, 2018|date=September 5, 2018|work=[[E! News]]|first=Johnni|last=Macke|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905154343/https://www.eonline.com/shows/peoples_choice_awards/news/963752/2018-people-s-choice-awards-complete-list-of-nominations|archivedate=September 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/shows/peoples_choice_awards/news/967279/2018-people-s-choice-awards-complete-list-of-finalists|title=2018 People's Choice Awards: Complete List of Finalist|work=[[E! News]]|first=Johnni|last=Macke|date=September 24, 2018|accessdate=October 5, 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20181005023925/https://www.eonline.com/shows/peoples_choice_awards/news/967279/2018-people-s-choice-awards-complete-list-of-finalists|archivedate=October 5, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | The Comedy Movie Star of 2018\n| [[Awkwafina]]\n| {{Shortlisted}}\n|-\n| {{sortname|Constance|Wu}}\n| {{Shortlisted}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Producers Guild of America Awards]]\n| [[Producers Guild of America Awards 2018|January 19, 2019]]\n| [[Producers Guild of America Award for Best Theatrical Motion Picture#2010s|Best Theatrical Motion Picture]]\n| ''Crazy Rich Asians'' \u2013 Nina Jacobson & Brad Simpson, John Penotti\n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref name=\"PGA18\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/producers-guild-awards-nominations-include-roma-black-panther-a-star-is-born-and-also-crazy-rich-asians/|title=Producers Guild Awards Nominations Include 'Roma,' 'Black Panther,' 'A Star Is Born' \u2013 and Also 'Crazy Rich Asians'|work=[[TheWrap]]| last=Pond|first=Steve|date=January 4, 2019|accessdate=January 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[San Diego Film Critics Society#Awards|San Diego Film Critics Society]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| December 10, 2018\n| Best Comedic Performance\n| Awkwafina\n| {{Nominated}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=\"SDFCS18\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sdfcs.org/2018-san-diego-film-nominations/ |title=2018 San Diego Film Critics Society's Award Nominations |date=December 7, 2018 |website=[[San Diego Film Critics Society]] |access-date=December 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209123837/http://www.sdfcs.org/2018-san-diego-film-nominations/ |archive-date=December 9, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Costume Design\n| Mary E. Vogt\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=2| [[Satellite Awards]]\n| rowspan=2| [[23rd Satellite Awards|February 17, 2019]]\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Film|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Comedy/Musical]]\n| ''Crazy Rich Asians''\n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pressacademy.com/2018-nominees/ |title=2018 Awards Nominees |publisher=[[International Press Academy]] |accessdate=December 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129220303/http://www.pressacademy.com/2018-nominees/ |archive-date=November 29, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Actress in a Motion Picture, Comedy/Musical]]\n| Constance Wu\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|[[Screen Actors Guild Award]]s\n| [[25th Screen Actors Guild Awards|January 27, 2019]]\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]]\n| ''Crazy Rich Asians''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web| url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/sag-awards-nominations-full-list-sag-award-nominees-1202518339/| title=SAG Awards Nominations: 'A Star Is Born', 'Mrs. Maisel', 'Ozark' Lead Way \u2013 The Full List| date=December 12, 2018| author=Patrick Hipes| website=Deadline}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[The Asian Awards]]\n|[[The Asian Awards|April 12, 2019]]\n| Outstanding Achievement in Cinema\n| The cast of [[Crazy Rich Asians]]\n|{{Won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://theasianawards.com/winners_9th_awards.html |website=The Asian Awards |accessdate=September 4, 2019|title=Winners of the 9th Asian Awards}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Sequels==\n[[File:Adele Lim by Gage Skidmore.jpg|Screenwriter [[Adele Lim]] left production on the two sequels to ''Crazy Rich Asians'' following a pay dispute, which she felt was founded in racism and sexism.|thumb|upright=0.8|alt=Adele Lim smiles, looking right.]]\nPrior to the film's release, Jon M. Chu said he would be eager to direct a sequel if the first film was a success, stating, \"We have other stories outside of the ''Crazy Rich Asians'' world that are ready to be told too, from filmmakers and storytellers who haven't had their stories told yet.\"<ref name=\"premiere\"/> On August 22, 2018, following the film's strong opening, Warner Bros. Pictures confirmed a sequel was in development, with Chiarelli and Lim returning to write the script, based on the book's sequel, ''[[China Rich Girlfriend]]''. Chu and actors Wu, Golding, and Yeoh all have options for a sequel, although several of the key actors are committed to other projects until 2020.<ref name=\"Time-KarenHo\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-sequel-in-development-at-warner-bros-1202450095/ |title='Crazy Rich Asians' Sequel In Development At Warner Bros. |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=August 22, 2018 |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822155159/https://deadline.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-sequel-in-development-at-warner-bros-1202450095/ |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Crazy Rich Asians 2: Everything We Know About The Sequel's Story |first=Ana |last=Dumaraog |date=August 28, 2018 |work=Screen Rant ORIGINALS |url=https://screenrant.com/crazy-rich-asians-2-story-china-rich-girlfriend/ |accessdate=August 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830004955/https://screenrant.com/crazy-rich-asians-2-story-china-rich-girlfriend/ |archive-date=August 30, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Producer Nina Jacobson later announced that ''China Rich Girlfriend'' and an adaptation of the final installment in Kwan's trilogy, ''[[Rich People Problems]]'', will be filmed back-to-back in 2020 to reduce the wait time between those two films.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/crazy-rich-asians-sequels-spoilers-nina-jacobson-brad-simpson-golden-globe-nominations-1202515361/ |title=Nina Jacobson & Brad Simpson Of Color Force Celebrate Diversity At Globe Noms, Tease 'Crazy Rich Asians' Sequels Details |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=December 6, 2018 |publisher=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=December 14, 2018 |quote=the current plan for the Crazy Rich Asians sequels is to shoot them back-to-back}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, screenwriter Adele Lim, who had co-written ''Crazy Rich Asians'' with Peter Chiarelli, left production on the film's sequels following a pay dispute. Lim had reportedly been offered 110,000 [[United States dollar]]s to pen the sequels, while Chiarelli had been offered $800,000-$1,000,000 for the same role.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/tanyatarr/2019/09/16/heres-what-we-learn-from-watching-adele-lim-walk-away-from-the-pay-gap/#23dd46053679|title=Here\u2019s What We Learn From Watching Adele Lim Walk Away From The Pay Gap|work=[[Forbes]]|date=September 16, 2019|accessdate=December 21, 2019|last=Tarr|first=Tanya}}</ref> Lim stated that the pay difference represented a greater issue of sexism and racism in Hollywood, as the industry views women and people of color as \"soy sauce\"\u2014or simply a means to add minor cultural details to screenplays, rather than to provide a substantial writing role.<ref name=\"alcnbc\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/09/06/crazy-rich-asians-co-writer-adele-lim-quits-sequel-due-to-pay-gap.html|title=The \u2018Crazy Rich Asians\u2019 sequel is delayed amid a pay dispute|date=September 6, 2019|accessdate=December 21, 2019|last=Liu|first=Jennifer|work=[[CNBC]]}}</ref> Director Jon M. Chu voiced support for Lim in a statement, explaining that, while he was disappointed she wouldn't return for the sequels, he would continue to work with Lim elsewhere and that \"the conversation this has started is MUCH more important than ourselves... so who am I to get in the way of that.\" He added that he agreed with Lim's criticisms of the film industry, and requested that people refrain from criticizing Chiarelli, as \"he is a good man, a creative force and has been a pro in the business for many many years\".<ref name=\"VFstatements\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/09/crazy-rich-asians-jon-chu-adele-lim-response|title=Crazy Rich Asians: Jon M. Chu Responds to Adele Lim\u2019s Exit Over Pay Parity|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|last=Bradley|first=Laura|date=September 10, 2019|accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref> Warner Bros.' business affairs department issued a response as well, stating that Chiarelli had more experience working on films as Lim's r\u00e9sum\u00e9 had only consisted of television credits prior to ''Crazy Rich Asians'', and that \"making an exception would set a troubling precedent in the business\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/crazy-rich-asians-screenwriter-adele-lim-exits-sequel-pay-disparity-dispute-1236431|title='Crazy Rich Asians' Co-Writer Exits Sequel Amid Pay Disparity Dispute (Exclusive)|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=September 4, 2019|accessdate=December 21, 2019|last=Sun|first=Rebecca}}</ref> They also noted that an alternative offer for Lim had been drafted, which she did not take.<ref name=\"alcnbc\" /> Lim later voiced thanks for the public support she had received, writing on Twitter: \"To people going through their own fight - you are not alone. Also, I have only love for Jon M. Chu and the cast & crew of ''Crazy Rich Asians''\".<ref name=\"VFstatements\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chinese in New York City]]\n* [[Overseas Chinese]]\n* [[Chinese Singaporeans]]\n* [[Flower Drum Song (film)|''Flower Drum Song'']], the 1961 American film cited as the first with a majority Asian cast set contemporaneously, which was also adapted from [[The Flower Drum Song|a novel]].<ref name=NBC-2018-08-13>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/six-decades-ago-flower-drum-song-featured-hollywood-s-first-n899576 |title=Six decades ago, 'Flower Drum Song' featured Hollywood's first Asian-American cast |date=August 13, 2018 |first=Melissa |last=Hung |work=NBC News |access-date=August 31, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180901044052/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/six-decades-ago-flower-drum-song-featured-hollywood-s-first-n899576 |archive-date=September 1, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=22em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Crazy Rich Asians (2018 film)|Crazy Rich Asians}}\n* [http://www.crazyrichasiansmovie.com/ Official website]\n* {{IMDb title|tt3104988}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|id=crazy_rich_asians}}\n* {{Mojo title|crazyrichasians}}\n\n{{Kevin Kwan}}\n{{Jon M. Chu}}\n{{Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Comedy}}\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:2010s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:Asian-American comedy films]]\n[[Category:Asian-American romance films]]\n[[Category:Chinese-American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about families]]\n[[Category:Films about weddings]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on romance novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on Singaporean novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jon M. Chu]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Brian Tyler]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1995]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2018]]\n[[Category:Films set in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Films set in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Films about the upper class]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n[[Category:Upper class culture]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2018 film by Jon M. Chu}}\n{{good article}}\n{{use MDY|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Crazy Rich Asians\n| image          = Crazy_Rich_Asians_poster.png\n| alt            = A couple hugs each other against a colorful Chinese fan background\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Jon M. Chu]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Nina Jacobson]]\n* [[Brad Simpson (producer)|Brad Simpson]]\n* John Penotti \n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* Peter Chiarelli\n* [[Adele Lim]]\n}}\n| story          =\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Crazy Rich Asians]]''|[[Kevin Kwan]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Constance Wu]] <!-- PER BILLING ORDER -->\n* [[Henry Golding]]\n* [[Gemma Chan]]\n* [[Lisa Lu]]\n* [[Awkwafina]]\n* [[Ken Jeong]]\n* [[Michelle Yeoh]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Brian Tyler]]\n| cinematography = Vanja Cernjul\n| editing        = Myron Kerstein\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* SK Global Entertainment<ref name=\"prod\">{{cite news|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/dentons-tax-lawyer-ny-plays-072643044.html|title=Dentons Tax Lawyer From NY Plays Unlikely Role in 'Crazy Rich Asians' Success|date=November 6, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018|work=[[Yahoo! Finance]]|author=ALM Media}}</ref>\n* Starlight Culture Entertainment<ref name=\"prod\" />\n* [[Color Force]]<!--Cited in body-->\n* Ivanhoe Pictures<!--Cited in body-->\n* Electric Somewhere<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/asia/crazy-rich-asians-sequel-shoot-in-china-1203008180/#!|title='Crazy Rich Asians' Sequel to Shoot in China|date=October 29, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Frater|first=Patrick}}</ref>\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|8|7|[[Grauman's Chinese Theatre|TCL Chinese Theatre]]|2018|08|15|United States}}\n| runtime        = 121 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 120:30--><ref>{{cite web |title=''CRAZY RICH ASIANS'' (12A) |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/crazy-rich-asians-film |accessdate=August 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180817045240/https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/crazy-rich-asians-film |archive-date=August 17, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| country        = United States<br/>Singapore\n| language       = English <!-- Primary language of the film -->\n| budget         = $30 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |title=Crazy Rich Asians (2018)|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=crazyrichasians.htm |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n| gross          = $238.5 million<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Crazy Rich Asians''''' is a 2018 American [[romantic comedy]] film directed by [[Jon M. Chu]], from a screenplay by Peter Chiarelli and [[Adele Lim]], based on the [[Crazy Rich Asians|2013 novel of the same title]] by [[Kevin Kwan]]. The film stars [[Constance Wu]], [[Henry Golding]], [[Gemma Chan]], [[Lisa Lu]], [[Awkwafina]], [[Ken Jeong]], and [[Michelle Yeoh]]. It follows a [[Chinese Americans|Chinese-American]] professor who travels to meet her boyfriend's family and is surprised to discover they are among the richest in [[Singapore]].\n\nThe film was announced in August 2013 after the rights to the book were purchased. Many of the cast members signed on in the spring of 2017, and filming took place from April to June of that year in parts of [[New York City]], and [[Singapore]]. It is the first film by a [[major film studio|major Hollywood studio]] to feature a majority cast of Asian descent in a modern setting since ''[[The Joy Luck Club (film)|The Joy Luck Club]]'' in 1993.<!--(Memoirs of a Geisha was a period piece)--> Despite praise for that, the film did receive some criticism for casting [[biracial]] actors over [[Overseas Chinese|fully ethnically Chinese]] ones in certain roles. Additional criticism was directed at the film for failing to include non-Chinese Singaporean ethnic groups\u2014notably [[Malays (ethnic group)|Malay]] and [[Indian people|Indian]] actors\u2014as characters.\n\n''Crazy Rich Asians'' premiered on August 7, 2018, at the [[TCL Chinese Theatre]] in [[Los Angeles]] and was released theatrically in the United States on August 15, 2018, by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]. The film received positive reviews from critics, with praise for its acting, production and costume design. The film grossed over $238 million worldwide, making it the highest-grossing romantic comedy in a decade. The film received numerous accolades, including the [[76th Golden Globe Awards]] earning nominations for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical]] for Wu. It also received four nominations at the [[24th Critics' Choice Awards]], winning one for [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Comedy|Best Comedy]], and a [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]] at the [[25th Screen Actors Guild Awards]]. Two sequels, based on the novel's follow-ups ''[[China Rich Girlfriend]]'' and ''[[Rich People Problems]]'', are currently in development.\n\n==Plot==\nNick Young and his girlfriend Rachel Chu, an [[economics]] professor at [[New York University]] and [[New York City|New York]] native, travel to [[Singapore]] for the wedding of his best friend Colin, who is marrying Araminta Lee. In Singapore, Rachel visits her college friend Peik Lin and her family, who are shocked when she tells them she is dating Nick Young. Peik Lin reveals that Nick's family is extremely wealthy and famous, and are members of high society. At a dinner party at the Young estate, Nick introduces Rachel to his mother Eleanor, while his cousin Astrid discovers that her husband Michael, who comes from a more humble background than the Youngs, has been having an affair. Rachel senses that Eleanor dislikes her.\n\nAt Araminta's [[bachelorette party]], Rachel meets Amanda, who reveals she is Nick's former girlfriend and hints Rachel may not be able to integrate into such a high-class family with her lower background. Rachel finds her hotel room vandalized by the other girls, who deem her a gold-digger, but is comforted by Astrid. Nick attends Colin's [[bachelor party]], where he reveals to Colin his plan to propose to Rachel. Colin expresses his concern about the trouble it will cause them, especially with Nick being expected to stay in Singapore and run his family's corporation and Rachel loving her job in New York, as well as the difference in their statuses. Nick apologizes to Rachel for not telling her who he really was and takes her to make [[jiaozi]] dumplings with his family. Here, Eleanor recounts the sacrifices she made to become a part of the Young family and makes jabs at Rachel for her American background. Eleanor later privately recounts to Rachel how Nick's father had to cast his own green ring to propose to her as Nick's grandmother refused to give him the family ring, owing to Eleanor not being the first or even second choice. She tells Rachel that she will never be enough for Nick or his family. Peik Lin convinces Rachel to stand up to Eleanor and earns her respect. On the day of the wedding, Astrid confronts Michael about his affair; Michael blames his unhappiness and the great financial disparity between them on her.\n\nDuring the wedding reception, Eleanor and Nick's grandmother privately confront Rachel and Nick. Using the findings of a private investigation, Eleanor reveals that Rachel's father is alive, and Rachel was conceived through an adulterous affair, after which her mother, Kerry, abandoned her husband and fled to the United States. They demand that Nick stop seeing Rachel for fear of a scandal, as they cannot be linked to such a family. Rachel is stunned, as Kerry told her that her father was dead. She flees and stays at Peik Lin's home, depressed and unwilling to speak to Nick. Kerry arrives in Singapore, explaining that her husband was abusive and that the comfort an old classmate provided turned into love and a surprise pregnancy. She fled with baby Rachel in fear that her husband would kill them. Kerry reveals that Nick was the one who had called her to Singapore and urges Rachel to talk to him. When they meet, Nick apologizes and proposes to Rachel, saying that he is willing to leave his family behind to be with her.\n\nRachel arranges to meet Eleanor at a [[mahjong]] parlor. Over a game of mahjong, she reveals to Eleanor that she declined Nick's proposal so his relationship with his family would not be ruined. She tells Eleanor to remember that when Nick eventually marries someone \"good enough\" for her, it will be because of a selfless act on the part of Rachel, a girl Eleanor looks down upon. Meanwhile, Astrid moves out, telling Michael his ego, insecurities, and unwillingness to make their marriage work caused it to fail. Elsewhere Eleanor has a meeting with Nick.\n\nRachel and Kerry board a flight back to New York City at [[Singapore Changi Airport]], but are interrupted by Nick, who proposes with Eleanor's green ring, revealing her blessing. In tears, Rachel accepts and they stay in Singapore one more night for an engagement party, where Eleanor nods at Rachel in acknowledgment, Rachel having finally earned her respect. In a [[Post-credits scene|mid-credits scene]], Astrid and her ex-boyfriend Charlie Wu spot each other at the party; she discreetly smiles.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{multiple image|direction=vertical|total_width=175\n| image1 = Constance Wu in 2015 (cropped).jpg\n| alt1   = Costance Wu smiles, facing forward\n| image2 = Henry Golding in 2014.jpg\n| alt2   = Henry Golding smiles, facing forward\n| footer = [[Constance Wu]] (above) and [[Henry Golding]] play the lead characters Rachel Chu and Nick Young.\n}}\n* [[Constance Wu]] as Rachel Chu, Nick's girlfriend and Kerry's daughter<ref name=\"constance\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/constance-wu-star-crazy-rich-asians-960077 |title=Constance Wu to Star in 'Crazy Rich Asians' (Exclusive) |last=Ford |first=Rebecca |date=February 15, 2017 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=April 11, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170412083854/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/constance-wu-star-crazy-rich-asians-960077 |archive-date=April 12, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Henry Golding]] as Nicholas \"Nick\" Young, Rachel's boyfriend and Phillip and Eleanor's son<ref name=\"henry\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/crazy-rich-asians-lands-male-lead-988732 |title='Crazy Rich Asians' Lands Its Male Lead (Exclusive) |last=Ford |first=Rebecca |date=March 28, 2017 |access-date=April 11, 2017 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170401055827/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/crazy-rich-asians-lands-male-lead-988732 |archive-date=April 1, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/asia/henry-golding-talks-crazy-rich-asians-casting-controversies-1202622817/|title=Henry Golding Talks 'Crazy Rich Asians' and Asian Casting Controversies|last=Ramachandran|first=Naman|date=November 25, 2017|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=February 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206073622/https://variety.com/2017/film/asia/henry-golding-talks-crazy-rich-asians-casting-controversies-1202622817/|archive-date=February 6, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Michelle Yeoh]] as Eleanor Sung-Young, Nick's domineering mother and Phillip's wife<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/crazy-rich-asians-adds-michelle-yeoh-981172 |title='Crazy Rich Asians' Adds Michelle Yeoh (Exclusive) |last=Ford |first=Rebecca |date=March 7, 2017 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=April 11, 2017 |last2=Kit |first2=Borys |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508234436/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/crazy-rich-asians-adds-michelle-yeoh-981172 |archive-date=May 8, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Gemma Chan]] as Astrid Leong-Teo, Nick's cousin and Michael's wife, a fashion icon and socialite<ref name=\"gemma\">{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/humans-gemma-chan-constance-wu-in-crazy-rich-asians-1202021919/|title=Gemma Chan to Star With Constance Wu in 'Crazy Rich Asians'|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=April 4, 2017|work=Variety|access-date=April 11, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406232541/http://variety.com/2017/film/news/humans-gemma-chan-constance-wu-in-crazy-rich-asians-1202021919/|archive-date=April 6, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>{{refn|name=first|group=note|While Astrid's full name is \"Astrid Leong-Teo\" in the novel, she is listed in the credits of the film as \"Astrid Young Teo\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.businesstimes.cn/articles/105621/20181207/crazy-rich-asians-filming-back-to-back-sequels-in-2020.htm|title=Crazy Rich Asians' Filming Back-To-Back Sequels In 2020|work=Business Times|date=December 7, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref> Similarly, her mother Felicity's full name has been changed from \"Felicity Young-Leong\" in the novel to \"Felicity Young\" in the film.<ref name=\"Janice Koh\">{{cite news|url=https://www.herworld.com/features/women-now/janice-koh-crazy-rich-asians-felicity-young-theatre-actress-arts-singapore|title=Cents and sensibilities: How Janice Koh and Felicity Young compare|work=Her World|publisher=[[Singapore Press Holdings]]|last=Soh|first=Mary-Ann|date=September 6, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref>}}\n* [[Lisa Lu]] as Shang Su Yi, Nick's grandmother and the matriarch of the family<ref name=\"usatodaycast\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2018/05/25/crazy-rich-asians-everything-we-know-movie/549312002/|title='Crazy Rich Asians': Everything we know about the movie|work=[[USA Today]]|date=May 25, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018|last=Reed|first=Anika}}</ref>\n* [[Awkwafina]] as Goh Peik Lin, Rachel's charismatic confidant and best friend, and Wye Mun's daughter<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/crazy-rich-asians-adds-awkwafina-996699 |title='Crazy Rich Asians' Adds Awkwafina |last=Ford |first=Rebecca |date=April 24, 2017 |access-date=April 24, 2017 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425085544/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/crazy-rich-asians-adds-awkwafina-996699 |archive-date=April 25, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Ken Jeong]] as Goh Wye Mun, Peik Lin's wealthy father<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sg.style.yahoo.com/heres-know-crazy-rich-asians-filming-singapore-030246690.html|title=Here's what we know about Crazy Rich Asians filming in Singapore|last=Yong|first=Nicolas|date=June 29, 2017|work=[[Yahoo!]] Lifestyle Singapore|access-date=July 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630185407/https://sg.style.yahoo.com/heres-know-crazy-rich-asians-filming-singapore-030246690.html|archive-date=June 30, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Sonoya Mizuno]] as Araminta Lee, Colin's fianc\u00e9e and heiress to a billion dollar resort chain<ref name=\"The Hollywood Reporter\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/machina-actress-sonoya-mizuno-joining-crazy-rich-asians-992498 |title='Ex Machina' Actress Sonoya Mizuno Joining 'Crazy Rich Asians' (Exclusive) |last=Galuppo |first=Mia |date=April 10, 2017 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=April 11, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170411022449/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/machina-actress-sonoya-mizuno-joining-crazy-rich-asians-992498 |archive-date=April 11, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Chris Pang]] as Colin Khoo, Nick's childhood best friend and Araminta's fianc\u00e9<ref name=\"cast\" />\n* [[Jimmy O. Yang]] as Bernard Tai, Nick and Colin's former classmate<ref name=\"cast\" />\n* [[Ronny Chieng]] as Eddie Cheng, Nick and Astrid's cousin and Fiona's husband from Hong Kong<ref name=\"cast\" />\n* [[Remy Hii]] as Alistair Cheng, Eddie's brother and Nick and Astrid's movie-making cousin from Taiwan<ref name=\"usatodaycast\" />\n* [[Nico Santos (actor)|Nico Santos]] as Oliver T'sien, Nick's second cousin<ref name=\"cast\" />\n* [[Jing Lusi]] as Amanda \"Mandy\" Ling, [[Chinatown, Manhattan|Manhattan]] lawyer and Nick's former girlfriend<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/pmn/news-pmn/crazy-rich-asians-a-movie-and-a-movement/wcm/79450fa6-4d9f-4e59-bb40-c714582a1840|title='Crazy Rich Asians' \u2013 a movie and a movement|work=[[Ottawa Citizen]]|date=August 17, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Carmen Soo]] as Francesca Shaw, Nick's snobby ex-girlfriend<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/08/08/18/remember-carmen-soo-shes-in-crazy-rich-asians-too|title=Remember Carmen Soo? She's in 'Crazy Rich Asians,' too|work=[[ABS-CBN News and Current Affairs|ABS-CBN News]]|date=August 8, 2018|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Pierre Png]] as Michael Teo, Astrid's husband<ref name=\"cast\">{{cite news|url=https://ew.com/movies/crazy-rich-asians-cast-characters/|title=Meet the cast and characters of Crazy Rich Asians|last=Li|first=Shirley|date=November 7, 2017|accessdate=November 27, 2018|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref>\n* [[Fiona Xie]] as Kitty Pong, Alistair's girlfriend and Taiwanese soap opera star<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elle.sg/lifestyle/pop-culture/fiona-xie-rejected-crazy-rich-asians-kitty-pong-role-at-first-10634946|title=Fiona Xie Actually Said No To Kitty Pong Role In Crazy Rich Asians At First|work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle Singapore]]|last=Wei Ning|first=Liu|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Victoria Loke]] as Fiona Tung-Cheng, Eddie's wife from Hong Kong and Nick's cousin-in-law<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/lauramanske/2018/08/25/crazy-rich-asians-actress-victoria-loke-reveals-her-top-20-travel-tips-for-new-york-and-singapore/#521806f7e389|title=Crazy Rich Asians: Actress Victoria Loke Reveals Her Top 20 Travel Tips For New York And Singapore|last=Manske|first=Laura|work=[[Forbes]]|date=August 25, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Janice Koh]] as Felicity Young, Astrid's mother and Su Yi's eldest child<ref name=\"Janice Koh\" />{{refn|name=first|group=note}}\n* [[Amy Cheng]] as Jacqueline Ling, Mandy's heiress mother and Eleanor's friend<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.herworld.com/features/women-now/amy-cheng-crazy-rich-asians-singapore-cast-acting-bad-guy|title=Good girl gone bad: Why Amy Cheng doesn't mind playing the bad guy|work=Her World|publisher=[[Singapore Press Holdings]]|last=Soh|first=Mary-Ann|date=September 4, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Koh Chieng Mun]] as Neena Goh, Peik Lin's mother<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.asiaone.com/entertainment/actress-koh-chieng-mun-only-cast-member-crazy-rich-asians-who-speaks-full-singlish|title=Actress Koh Chieng Mun is only cast member in Crazy Rich Asians who speaks full-on Singlish|date=August 8, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018|last=Sim|first=Sherlyn|work=Asia One}}</ref>\n* Calvin Wong as P.T. Goh, Peik Lin's brother<ref name=\"teenvougecast\">{{cite news|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/crazy-rich-asians-cast-characters|title=Meet the Entire Cast of \"Crazy Rich Asians\" and the Characters They Play: Constance Wu, Awkwafina, Henry Golding, and More|last=Ting|first=Jasmine Arielle|date=August 1, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018|work=[[Teen Vogue]]}}</ref>\n* [[Tan Kheng Hua]] as Kerry Chu, Rachel's mother<ref name=\"teenvougecast\" />\n* [[Constance Lau]] as Celine \"Radio One Asia\" Lim, gossiper and member of ''Radio One Asia''<ref name=\"ottawacast\">{{cite news|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/pmn/news-pmn/crazy-rich-asians-a-movie-and-a-movement/wcm/79450fa6-4d9f-4e59-bb40-c714582a1840|title='Crazy Rich Asians' -- a movie and a movement|work=[[Ottawa Citizen]]|date=August 17, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Selena Tan]] as Alexandra 'Alix' Young-Cheng, Su Yi's youngest child<ref name=\"teenvougecast\"/>\n* [[Daniel Jenkins]] as Reginald Ormsby, manager of the London Calthorpe Hotel<ref name=\"numbers-cast\" />\n* [[Peter Carroll (actor)|Peter Carroll]] as Lord Calthorpe, owner of the London Calthorpe Hotel<ref name=\"numbers-cast\">{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Crazy-Rich-Asians#tab=cast-and-crew|title=Crazy Rich Asians (2018) - Cast & Crew|website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Kris Aquino]] as Princess Intan, a wealthy royal<ref name=\"teenvougecast\" />\n* Tumurbaatar Enkhtungalag as Nadine Shao, one of Eleanor's best friends<ref>{{cite news|url=https://montsame.mn/en/read/136462|title=Mongolian actress stars in 'Crazy Rich Asians'|work=[[Montsame]]|date=August 23, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018|last=Misheel|first=B.}}</ref>\n\n''Crazy Rich Asians'' author [[Kevin Kwan]] has a cameo appearance during the ''Radio One Asia'' sequence.<ref name=\"cameos\" /> Singer [[Kina Grannis]] cameos as Colin and Araminta's wedding singer during the marriage sequence, and [[Harry Shum Jr.]] makes a brief appearance as Astrid's ex-fianc\u00e9 Charlie Wu in a mid-credits scene.<ref name=\"cameos\">{{cite news|url=https://slate.com/culture/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-kevin-kwan-kina-grannis-and-harry-shum-jr-cameos-and-other-easter-eggs.html|title=A Guide to Crazy Rich Asians' Many Cameos, Homages, and Easter Eggs|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=August 15, 2018|accessdate=December 24, 2018|last=Kang|first=Inkoo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2018/8/17/17704498/crazy-rich-asians-credits-scene-charlie-wu-astrid-leong-explained|title=Crazy Rich Asians' mid-credits scene is brief, but very revealing|last=Romano|first=Aja|date=August 31, 2018 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |access-date=December 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\n===Pre-production===\nKevin Kwan published his comedic novel ''[[Crazy Rich Asians]]'' on June 11, 2013. One of the first producers to contact Kwan was [[Wendi Deng Murdoch]], who had read an advance copy of the novel provided by [[Graydon Carter]].<ref name=Vulture-18>{{cite news |url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/08/the-long-crazy-road-to-crazy-rich-asians.html |title=The Long Crazy Road to 'Crazy Rich Asians' |first=Chris |last=Lee |date=August 9, 2018 |work=[[Vulture.com|Vulture]] |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822214438/http://www.vulture.com/2018/08/the-long-crazy-road-to-crazy-rich-asians.html |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=THR-HighStakes /> Another of the producers who was initially interested in the project proposed [[Whitewashing in film|whitewashing]] the role of heroine Rachel Chu by casting a Caucasian actress,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/bookmark/crazy-rich-asians-author-kevin-804381 |title='Crazy Rich Asians' Author Kevin Kwan: \"Why Does Hollywood Think We'd Want to See This Movie With White People?\" |first=Rebecca |last=Sun |date=June 26, 2015 |newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180813075855/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/bookmark/crazy-rich-asians-author-kevin-804381 |archive-date=August 13, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> prompting Kwan to option the rights to the film for just $1 in exchange for a continuing role for creative and development decisions.<ref name=Vulture-18 /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/crazy-rich-asians-author-kevin-kwan-optioned-book-one-dollar |title='Crazy Rich Asians' Author Kevin Kwan Optioned His Book for Only $1 |first=Devon |last=Elizabeth |date=August 1, 2018 |work=[[Teen Vogue]] |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821194200/https://www.teenvogue.com/story/crazy-rich-asians-author-kevin-kwan-optioned-book-one-dollar |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In August 2013, producer [[Nina Jacobson]] acquired rights to adapt the novel into a film. Jacobson and her partner Brad Simpson intended to produce under their production banner [[Color Force]], with Bryan Unkeless developing the project. Their initial plan was to produce the film adaptation outside the studio system and to structure financing for development and production from Asia and other territories outside the United States.<ref>{{cite journal | last=McNary | first=Dave | url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/crazy-rich-asians-movie-nina-jacobson-1200574689/ | title='Hunger Games' Producer Developing 'Crazy Rich Asians' Movie | journal=Variety | date=August 6, 2013 | accessdate=April 28, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027093642/http://variety.com/2013/film/news/crazy-rich-asians-movie-nina-jacobson-1200574689/ | archive-date=October 27, 2016 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/crazy-rich-asians-color-force-600258 |title='Crazy Rich Asians': Color Force Nabs Film Rights to Best-Seller |first=Tatiana |last=Siegel |date=August 6, 2013 |newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925070255/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/crazy-rich-asians-color-force-600258 |archive-date=September 25, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The freedom created by eschewing the typical funding structure would enable an all-Asian cast. Jacobson stated \"Getting something in development and even getting some upfront money is an easy way to not ever see your movie get made.\"<ref name=Vulture-18 />\n\nIn 2014, the US-based Asian film investment group Ivanhoe Pictures partnered with Jacobson to finance and produce ''Crazy Rich Asians''.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Frater | first=Patrick | url=https://variety.com/2014/film/asia/katherine-lee-to-head-asia-development-for-ivanhoe-pictures-1201346527/ | title=Katherine Lee to Head Asia Development for Ivanhoe Pictures | journal=Variety | date=November 3, 2014 | accessdate=April 28, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415144809/http://variety.com/2014/film/asia/katherine-lee-to-head-asia-development-for-ivanhoe-pictures-1201346527/ | archive-date=April 15, 2017 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> John Penotti, president of Ivanhoe, stated \"For us, the book fell in our lap kind of like, 'This is why we're doing the company.' Unlike the Hollywood second-guessing, 'Oh my God, will this work? We don't know. It's all Asian,' it was exactly the opposite for us: 'That's exactly why it will work.{{'\"}}<ref name=Vulture-18 />\n\nScreenwriter Peter Chiarelli was hired to write the screenplay before a director was brought on board.<ref name=THR-HighStakes /> Director [[Jon M. Chu]] entered negotiations with Color Force and Ivanhoe Pictures in May 2016 to direct the film adaptation.<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Ford | first1=Rebecca | last2=Kit | first2=Borys | url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jon-m-chu-talks-direct-888681 | title=Direct 'Crazy Rich Asians' (Exclusive) | journal=The Hollywood Reporter | date=May 4, 2016 | accessdate=April 28, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407065004/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jon-m-chu-talks-direct-888681 | archive-date=April 7, 2017 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> He was hired after giving executives a visual presentation about his experience as a first-generation Asian-American. Chu was actually mentioned obliquely in the source novel as Kwan was friends with Chu's cousin Vivian.<ref name=Vulture-18 />  Upon joining the project, Chu insisted on bringing in a screenwriter of Asian descent, [[Adele Lim]], to review and revise Chiarelli's script.<ref name=THR-HighStakes /> Chiarelli was credited with focusing the plot on the dynamic between Eleanor, Rachel, and Nick.  Lim, who was born in Malaysia, added specific cultural details and developed Eleanor's character.<ref name=Vulture-18 />\n\nIn October 2016, [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] acquired the distribution rights to the project after what ''Variety'' called a \"heated\" bidding war.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Lang | first=Brent | url=https://variety.com/2016/film/asia/crazy-rich-asians-movie-jon-chu-warner-bros-1201895221/ | title='Crazy Rich Asians' Adaptation Lands at Warner Bros. (Exclusive) | journal=Variety | date=October 20, 2016 | accessdate=April 28, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626064312/http://variety.com/2016/film/asia/crazy-rich-asians-movie-jon-chu-warner-bros-1201895221/ | archive-date=June 26, 2017 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Netflix reportedly fervently sought worldwide rights to the project, offering \"artistic freedom, a greenlighted trilogy and huge, seven-figure-minimum paydays for each stakeholder, upfront\". However, Kwan and Chu selected Warner Bros. for the cultural impact of a wide theatrical release.<ref name=Vulture-18 /><ref name=THR-HighStakes>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/crazy-rich-asians-story-behind-rom-com-1130965 |title=The Stakes Are High for 'Crazy Rich Asians' \u2014 And That's the Point |last=Sun |first=Rebecca |date=August 1, 2018 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=August 19, 2018 |last2=Ford |first2=Rebecca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180818212218/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/crazy-rich-asians-story-behind-rom-com-1130965 |archive-date=August 18, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n{{quotebox |float=right |width=25em |quote=Dates are dates, and if those are immovable, I understand. But I would put all of my heart, hope, humor, and courage into the role. What this could do means so much to me. It's why I advocate so much for young Asian-American girls so they might not spend their life feeling small or being commanded to feel grateful to even be at the table. |author={{pad|1.0em}}\u2014&nbsp;[[Constance Wu]], correspondence to [[Jon M. Chu]] (2016)<ref name=Vulture-18 />}}\nAlthough she had initially auditioned for the role of Rachel in mid-2016, Constance Wu could not accept due to a conflict with her work on the television series ''[[Fresh Off the Boat]]''. However, Wu wrote to Chu explaining her connection with Rachel's character, and convinced him to push back the production schedule by four months.<ref name=Vulture-18 /> Production was slated to begin in April 2017 in Singapore and Malaysia.<ref name=\"gemma\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/02/crazy-rich-asians-movie-constance-wu-to-star-jon-m-chus-adaptation-1201783800/ |title=Crazy Rich Asians Movie: Constance Wu in Talks to Star |last=Acevedo |first=Yoselin |work=[[IndieWire]] |access-date=March 28, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329141232/http://www.indiewire.com/2017/02/crazy-rich-asians-movie-constance-wu-to-star-jon-m-chus-adaptation-1201783800/ |archive-date=March 29, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nst.com.my/lifestyle/jom/2018/09/408117/crazy-rich-asians-5-filming-locations-malaysia-visit|title=Crazy Rich Asians: 5 filming locations in Malaysia to visit|work=[[New Straits Times]]|date=September 4, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nAfter Wu was chosen to play the lead Rachel Chu,<ref name=\"constance\"/> newcomer [[Henry Golding]] was cast to play the male lead Nick Young.<ref name=\"henry\"/> [[Michelle Yeoh]] joined the cast as Eleanor Young, Nick's mother, in March 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/crazy-rich-asians-michelle-yeoh-constance-wu-1202003796/|title=Michelle Yeoh Joins Constance Wu in 'Crazy Rich Asians'|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=March 7, 2017|work=Variety|access-date=March 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329141830/http://variety.com/2017/film/news/crazy-rich-asians-michelle-yeoh-constance-wu-1202003796/|archive-date=March 29, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Rounding out the supporting cast was [[Gemma Chan]] as Nick's cousin Astrid Young and [[Sonoya Mizuno]] as Araminta Lee.<ref name=\"The Hollywood Reporter\"/> Wu, Yeoh, and Chan were part of director Chu's \"dream casting sheet\" before casting was confirmed, along with [[Ronny Chieng]] and [[Jimmy O. Yang]].<ref name=THR-HighStakes/> On April 18, 2017, Filipino actress [[Kris Aquino]] was cast in a cameo role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/889921/kris-aquino-goes-to-hollywood|title=Kris Aquino goes to Hollywood|first=Thelma Sioson|last=San Juan|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|accessdate=February 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620180644/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/889921/kris-aquino-goes-to-hollywood|archive-date=June 20, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On May 12, it was announced that [[Ken Jeong]] had joined the cast.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/ken-jeong-joins-cast-crazy-rich-asians-n758486 |title=Ken Jeong joins cast of 'Crazy Rich Asians' |last=Gandhi |first=Lakshmi |date=May 12, 2017 |website=[[NBC News]] |access-date=February 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207005233/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/ken-jeong-joins-cast-crazy-rich-asians-n758486 |archive-date=February 7, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Although Jeong had a minor role involving less than a week of filming, he stated \"It's just something I wanted to be part of. It's about wanting to be part of something monumental. Something that's bigger than me. I'm so giddy I'm part of this, I can't even tell you.\"<ref name=Vulture-18 />\n\nThe casting of Nick Young, Golding's eventual role, initially had been challenging for the filmmakers, as director Jon M. Chu reportedly was unsatisfied with the preliminary finalists from Los Angeles and China, as he felt that none of the actors could properly replicate the British accent Nick was described as having from the original book.<ref name=THR-HighStakes /> After receiving a tip from his accountant Lisa-Kim Kuan,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-star-henry-golding-discovered-by-accountant.html |title=The Accountant Who 'Discovered ''Crazy Rich Asians'' Star Henry Golding Speaks! |author=Lee, Chris |date=August 22, 2018 |work=Vulture |accessdate=August 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831035458/http://www.vulture.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-star-henry-golding-discovered-by-accountant.html |archive-date=August 31, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Chu began actively pursuing Golding for the role of Nick, whom he felt had the proper accent and look for the character.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/08/henry-golding-crazy-rich-asians-casting.html |title=There's Something About Henry |author=Jung, E. Alex |date=August 2018 |work=Vulture |accessdate=30 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826174416/http://www.vulture.com/2018/08/henry-golding-crazy-rich-asians-casting.html |archive-date=August 26, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nBiscuit Films, a production company based in [[Petaling Jaya]] that provided support for the film, commissioned casting director Jerrica Lai to provide local talent which included [[Carmen Soo]] (as Francesca Shaw, a socialite) and Calvin Wong (Peik Lin's awkward brother).<ref name=Star-locations />\n\nThe film's casting prior to release was met with both praise\u2014in the U.S. for its all-Asian cast\u2014and criticism for its lack of Asian ethnic diversity, based on issues ranging from non-Chinese actors (Golding and Mizuno) playing Chinese roles; the film's ethnic Chinese and East Asian predominance as being poorly representative of Singapore; and as being a perpetuation of existing Chinese dominance in its media and pop culture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/aug/21/where-are-the-brown-people-crazy-rich-asians-draws-tepid-response-in-singapore|title=Where are the brown people? Crazy Rich Asians draws tepid response in Singapore|last=Ellis-Petersen|first=Hannah|last2=Kuo|first2=Lily|date=August 21, 2018|website=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=August 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823120359/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/aug/21/where-are-the-brown-people-crazy-rich-asians-draws-tepid-response-in-singapore|archive-date=August 23, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n:''For more discussion on the criticism of casting choices, refer to {{slink||Casting criticism}}.''\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Carcosa Seri Negara.jpg|thumb|The [[Carcosa Seri Negara]] in Malaysia, featured in the film as the Tyersall Park mansion.|alt=A multi-story white building stands with a small front garden|upright=0.8]]\n\nPrincipal photography began on April 24, 2017,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.warnerbros.com/studio/news/filming-commences-crazy-rich-asians|title=Filming Commences on \"Crazy Rich Asians\"|publisher=[[Warner Bros.]]|access-date=April 25, 2017|date=April 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426061642/https://www.warnerbros.com/studio/news/filming-commences-crazy-rich-asians|archive-date=April 26, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and completed on June 23.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.yomyomf.com/crazy-rich-asians-has-finished-shooting/ |title=Crazy Rich Asians has Finished Shooting |date=June 23, 2017 |website=You Offend Me You Offend My Family |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |author=YOMYOF Staff |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823210410/https://www.yomyomf.com/crazy-rich-asians-has-finished-shooting/ |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The film was shot at locations in [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Langkawi]] and [[Penang]], Malaysia, and in Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asiaone.com/showbiz/crazy-rich-asians-filming-malaysia |title=Crazy Rich Asians filming in Malaysia |work=[[AsiaOne]] |date=May 17, 2017 |accessdate=June 24, 2018 |first=June H.L. |last=Wong |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624210110/http://www.asiaone.com/showbiz/crazy-rich-asians-filming-malaysia |archive-date=June 24, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=CNT-18>{{cite news |url=https://www.cntraveler.com/gallery/where-was-crazy-rich-asians-filmed |title=Where Was 'Crazy Rich Asians' Filmed? |first=Meredith |last=Carey |date=August 9, 2018 |work=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast Traveler]] |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821093807/https://www.cntraveler.com/gallery/where-was-crazy-rich-asians-filmed |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The film was shot by Vanja \u010cernjul using Panasonic [[Varicam|VariCam]] PURE cameras equipped with [[anamorphic lens]]es.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://codex.online/casestudies/Vanja-Cernjul-Frames-Crazy-Rich-Asians |title=Framing Crazy Rich Asians |publisher=[[Codex Digital]] |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822214236/https://codex.online/casestudies/Vanja-Cernjul-Frames-Crazy-Rich-Asians |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Production design is credited to [[Nelson Coates]].<ref name=Wrap-30mil />\n\nProducer Tim Coddington contacted Biscuit Films for potential locations in Malaysia similar to photographs he had of mansions in Thailand, and Biscuit convinced him to switch locations to Malaysia, which is culturally more similar to Singapore, where the source novel is set.<ref name=Star-locations /> The ancestral Young family home, set at [[Tyersall Park]] in Singapore, was actually filmed at two abandoned mansions that make up [[Carcosa Seri Negara]] within the [[Perdana Botanical Gardens]] of Kuala Lumpur.<ref name=CNN-locations>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/crazy-rich-asians-travel-guide-singapore/index.html |title=The 'Crazy Rich Asians' guide to Singapore |first=Sonia |last=Kolesnikov-Jessop |date=August 12, 2018 |work=[[CNN]] |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823182624/https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/crazy-rich-asians-travel-guide-singapore/index.html |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Interior scenes were filmed at one building, and the exterior scenes were filmed at another; they had originally been built as residences for the [[List of High Commissioners of the United Kingdom to Malaya|British High Commissioner to Malaya]] in the early 20th century,<ref name=CNN-locations /> and were recently used as a boutique hotel until it closed in 2015.<ref name=Straits-18 /> The Carcosa Seri Negara buildings, owned by the Malaysian government, were then abandoned; as found in 2017, they were in disrepair and \"filled with monkey feces\".<ref name=THR-sets /><ref name=AD-2018>{{cite news |url=https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/crazy-rich-asians-sets |title=Here's Why All the Sets in Crazy Rich Asians Look So Authentic and, Well, Rich |first=Cathy |last=Whitlock |date=August 9, 2018 |work=[[Architectural Digest]] |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823041912/https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/crazy-rich-asians-sets |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The set designers were inspired to decorate the interior set in the [[Peranakan]] style. Kevin Kwan, who was born in Singapore and lived with his paternal grandparents before moving to the United States, contributed vintage family photographs for the set.<ref name=AD-2018 /> The set designers removed carpets, painted the floors to look like tiles, and commissioned local artists to create murals. The stuffed tiger in the foyer was a simulacrum created from foam and fur in Thailand; customs inspectors delayed the shipment because they thought it was an actual taxidermied animal.<ref name=THR-sets />\n\n{{multiple image|direction=horizontal|total_width=300\n| image1 = CHIJMES (8026595662).jpg\n| alt1 = A white, lit up church stands against a night sky\n| image2 = CHIJMES 20, Jan 06.JPG\n| alt2 = A large metal gate stands connects to a small wall\n| footer = [[CHIJMES]] complex in Singapore, where the wedding in the film was held.\n}}\n\nThe opening urban scenes set in London and the [[West Village]] were actually shot in Kuala Lumpur and Penang:<ref name=AD-2018 /> the Calthorpe Hotel purchased by the Youngs is the [[Eastern & Oriental Hotel|E&O Hotel]] in Penang; the lecture auditorium set at NYU was filmed in [[Putrajaya]]; and the restaurant where Nick asks Rachel to travel was filmed at BLVD House, Naza Towers at Platinum Park in Kuala Lumpur.<ref name=Star-locations>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/08/31/how-msia-became-a-big-part-of-crazy-rich-asians-from-location-to-acting-talent-and-crew-the-country/ |title=How Malaysia became a big part of 'Crazy Rich Asians' |last=Yeoh |first=Angelin |date=August 31, 2018 |newspaper=The Star |accessdate=September 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831130208/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/08/31/how-msia-became-a-big-part-of-crazy-rich-asians-from-location-to-acting-talent-and-crew-the-country/ |archive-date=August 31, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The taxi drop-off scene set at John F. Kennedy International Airport also was filmed at [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kftv.com/news/2018/09/13/crazy-rich-asians-filmed-malaysia-as-global-locations |title=Crazy Rich Asians filmed Malaysia as global locations |last=Goundry |first=Nick |date=September 13, 2018 |publisher=KFTV |access-date=December 14, 2018 |quote=Locations in Kuala Lumpur stood in for New York, where the story starts, and the city\u2019s airport doubled for New York\u2019s JFK. }}</ref> Singapore Airlines was asked to participate in exchange for product placement, but declined as \"they were not sure the movie would represent the airline and their customer[s] in a good light\", according to producer Brad Simpson, leading to the creation of the fictional Pacific Asean Airlines for the film.<ref name=Wrap-30mil /> After Nick asks Rachel to travel with him to Araminta and Colin's wedding, rumors about his mystery girlfriend soon reach Eleanor at a Bible study session, filmed in the private residence Be-landa House in Kuala Lumpur.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/life/homes/2018/08/10/how-a-toronto-architecht-designed-the-home-in-crazy-rich-asians.html |title=How a Toronto architect designed the home in Crazy Rich Asians |first=Carola |last=Vyhnak |date=August 10, 2018 |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823210434/https://www.thestar.com/life/homes/2018/08/10/how-a-toronto-architecht-designed-the-home-in-crazy-rich-asians.html |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.architecturalrecord.com/articles/13600-tropical-malaysian-residence-makes-its-hollywood-debut-in-crazy-rich-asians |title=Tropical Malaysian Residence Makes Its Hollywood Debut in 'Crazy Rich Asians' |first=Alex |last=Klimoski |date=August 20, 2018 |work=[[Architectural Record]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823210416/https://www.architecturalrecord.com/articles/13600-tropical-malaysian-residence-makes-its-hollywood-debut-in-crazy-rich-asians |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The luxurious first-class suite on the Pacific Asean flight was a set built at the Malaysia International Exhibition & Convention Centre (MIECC) in [[Seri Kembangan|Serdang]], [[Selangor]].<ref name=Star-locations /> The scenes where Rachel and Nick arrive at [[Changi Airport]] and are then whisked away to [[Newton Food Centre]] by Colin and Araminta were shot on location.<ref name=CNT-18 /><ref name=Straits-18>{{cite news |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/hit-the-hot-spots |title=Hit the hot spots featured in Crazy Rich Asians |first=John |last=Lui |date=August 23, 2018 |work=[[The Straits Times]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823105651/https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/hit-the-hot-spots |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=Bustle-18>{{cite news |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/13-crazy-rich-asians-singapore-filming-locations-that-you-can-actually-visit-in-real-life-10137339 |title=13 'Crazy Rich Asians' Singapore Filming Locations That You Can Actually Visit In Real Life |first=Jessica |last=Booth |date=August 16, 2018 |work=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180818214513/https://www.bustle.com/p/13-crazy-rich-asians-singapore-filming-locations-that-you-can-actually-visit-in-real-life-10137339 |archive-date=August 18, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> After settling in, Rachel and Nick stay at a luxury hotel (scenes were shot at the Raffles Hotel) instead of the ancestral Young estate at Tyersall.<ref name=CNT-18 /><ref name=SCMP-locations /> Astrid's character is introduced by showing her shopping for jewelry at an exclusive designer; the shop was created by redecorating the Astor Bar at the St. Regis Hotel in Kuala Lumpur.<ref name=THR-sets /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.galeriemagazine.com/crazy-rich-asians-6-secrets-from-the-set/|title=6 Secrets from the High-Flying Set of Crazy Rich Asians|last=Jovanovic|first=Rozalia|work=Galerie Magazine|date=August 17, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref> The Goh family's home is an actual residence off Cluny Park in Singapore, although the set decorators were responsible for the excessive gilding and pillars.<ref name=Straits-18 /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/travel/destinations/asia/106438079/holiday-like-crazy-rich-asians-in-singapore |title=Holiday like 'Crazy Rich Asians' in Singapore |first=Lorna |last=Thornber |date=August 21, 2018 |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nColin and Nick escape the party barge (the set was built in a parking lot at MIECC, and a container ship was rented for exterior shots)<ref name=CNT-18 /><ref name=THR-sets/><ref name=Star-locations /> to relax on [[Rawa Island]] (scenes filmed on Langkawi Island),<ref name=Star-locations /><ref name=\"CNtraveler\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cntraveler.com/gallery/where-was-crazy-rich-asians-filmed|title=Where Was 'Crazy Rich Asians' Filmed?|date=August 9, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018|work=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast Traveler]]|last=Carey|first=Meredith}}</ref> and the bachelorette party takes place at the [[Four Seasons Hotels and Resorts|Four Seasons]] on Langkawi.<ref name=Bustle-18 /> After Eleanor intimidates Rachel at the dumpling party, she is cheered up by Peik Lin at the restaurant Humpback on [[Bukit Pasoh Road]].<ref name=CNT-18 /><ref name=Straits-18 /><ref name=SCMP-locations>{{cite news |url=https://www.scmp.com/magazines/post-magazine/travel/article/2160819/crazy-rich-asians-guide-singapore-film-locations-you |title=The Crazy Rich Asians guide to Singapore: film locations you can actually visit |first=Gillian |last=Rhys |date=August 23, 2018 |newspaper=[[South China Morning Post|South China Morning Post Magazine]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823075746/https://www.scmp.com/magazines/post-magazine/travel/article/2160819/crazy-rich-asians-guide-singapore-film-locations-you |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The wedding of Araminta and Colin was shot at the [[CHIJMES]], a former convent in Singapore built in the 19th century.<ref name=CNT-18 /><ref name=AD-2018 /><ref name=Bustle-18 /> After the wedding, the reception is held in the Supertree Grove at [[Gardens by the Bay]].<ref name=CNT-18 /><ref name=Bustle-18 /> Rachel agrees to meet Nick at [[Merlion Park]] (this scene also featured locations filmed at [[Esplanade Park]])<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/travel/world-travel/asia/where-to-find-the-reallife-crazy-rich-asians-in-singapore/news-story/498acf13f9d616fde44c2700f13a4610|title=Where to find the real-life crazy rich Asians in Singapore|last=Ma|first=Wenlei|website=news.com.au|date=September 3, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref> before she returns to New York.<ref name=Bustle-18 /><ref name=\"CNtraveler\" /> Eleanor strides through archways in [[Ann Siang Hill]] near Singapore's Chinatown<ref name=\"CNtraveler\" /> before arriving for the mahjong showdown with Rachel, which was filmed at the [[Cheong Fatt Tze Mansion]] in Penang, redecorated for the film as a mahjong parlor.<ref name=Straits-18/><ref name=Bustle-18 /> Chu wanted that mahjong scene to be \"very specifically choreographed\", and had hired a mahjong expert to advise on the choreography.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-mahjong-scene-explained.html|title=The Story Behind Crazy Rich Asians' Mahjong Showdown|date=August 17, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018|work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|last=Dibdin|first=Emma}}</ref> Nick's second proposal to Rachel with Eleanor's ring was filmed inside a [[wide-body aircraft|twin-aisle jet]] parked at Kuala Lumpur International Airport.<ref name=\"Vulture-Proposal\">{{cite news |url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-proposal-scene-the-backstory.html |title=''Crazy Rich Asians''' Proposal Scene Was Changed at the Last Minute |first=E. Alex |last=Jung |date=August 23, 2018 |department=Vulture |accessdate=August 24, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823205007/http://www.vulture.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-proposal-scene-the-backstory.html |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> After that scene had been fully scripted, storyboarded, and planned to be filmed as a static side-by-side conversation with simple [[over the shoulder shot]]s, Chu realized the day before that the energy level was all wrong and changed it to a [[walk and talk]] improvised on the spot.<ref name=\"Vulture-Proposal\" /> The film's closing scenes are set at the [[Marina Bay Sands]].<ref name=Bustle-18 />\n\n===Costumes===\n{{quotebox |float=right |width=25em |quote=[The Youngs] are really \u2018old money.\u2019 Peik Lin Goh\u2019s family are \u2018new money.\u2019 They just made their money and are really enjoying [it]. They\u2019re just flinging it around, wanting to show it [off]. The Young family is used to having money, and they are quiet about it. They dress in a more elegant way. Their house looks more like a museum, and it\u2019s all very understated.|author={{pad|1.0em}}\u2014&nbsp;Costume designer Mary Vogt on costuming the film (2018)<ref name=Vulture-fashion />}}\nCostume design was handled by Mary Vogt, with Andrea Wong serving as a consultant and senior costume buyer.<ref name=SCMP-fashion /> They used dresses and suits from fashion designers such as Ralph Lauren, Elie Saab, Dolce & Gabbana, Valentino, and Christian Dior;<ref name=Vulture-fashion>{{cite news |url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-costume-design-key-looks.html |title=How ''Crazy Rich Asians''' Costume Designer Picked 8 Key Looks |first=Tomris |last=Laffly |date=August 20, 2018 |department=[[Vulture.com|Vulture]] |accessdate=August 24, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824183249/http://www.vulture.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-costume-design-key-looks.html |archive-date=August 24, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=Fashionista /> many of the brands were eager to have their clothes shown off in the film.<ref name=SCMP-fashion /> Looks were influenced by other movies cited by director Jon Chu, including [[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|''The Wizard of Oz'']], [[Cinderella (1950 film)|''Cinderella'']], and ''[[In the Mood for Love]]''.<ref name=Vulture-fashion /> 30 makeup artists were on set to help the actors, who were filming scenes in conditions of high heat and humidity while wearing formal clothing.<ref name=EWB-game />\n\nBefore traveling to Malaysia and Singapore, Vogt received help from Kwan, who shared vintage family photographs to explain how the [[old money]] society in Singapore \"was very classy, very elegant\",<ref name=SCMP-fashion /><ref name=Fashionista>{{cite news |url=https://fashionista.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-movie-costumes |title=The fabulous costumes of 'Crazy Rich Asians' are stacked with Dolce & Gabbana, Valentino and lots of Asian designers |author=Hoo, Fawnia Soo |date=August 15, 2018 |work=Fashionista |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> contrasting with the [[nouveau riche|new money]] Goh family, who are \"just flinging it around, wanting to show it [off]\".<ref name=Vulture-fashion /> Andrea Wong pointed Vogt to designers around Kuala Lumpur, who contributed not only clothes but also insight into local high-society fashions.<ref name=SCMP-fashion>{{cite news |url=https://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/fashion-beauty/article/2149549/dressing-crazy-rich-asians-how-costume-designer-mary-vogt |title=Dressing the Crazy Rich Asians: how costume designer Mary Vogt shaped look of film's stars \u2013 with help of Michelle Yeoh's jewellery |first=Kavita |last=Daswani |date=June 8, 2018 |newspaper=South China Morning Post |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823174402/https://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/fashion-beauty/article/2149549/dressing-crazy-rich-asians-how-costume-designer-mary-vogt |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Kwan, who had worked as a design consultant before writing the novel, relied on people he knew working in the fashion industry to bring in clothes for the film.<ref name=SCMP-fashion />\n\nIn an early scene, Astrid gives a watch to her husband Michael; it is a [[Rolex Daytona#Daytona \"Paul Newman\" dial|\"Paul Newman\" Rolex Daytona]] loaned following a request from Kwan for the filming.<ref name=EWB-game>{{cite news |url=https://www.eastwestbank.com/ReachFurther/News/Article/Crazy-Rich-Asians-a-Game-Changer-for-Asians-in-Hollywood |title=Crazy rich Asians, a Game Changer for Asians in Hollywood |author=Yuan, Melody |publisher=[[East West Bank]] |date=June 14, 2018 |accessdate=August 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827110356/https://www.eastwestbank.com/ReachFurther/News/Article/Crazy-Rich-Asians-a-Game-Changer-for-Asians-in-Hollywood |archive-date=August 27, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=Galerie-jewelry>{{cite news |url=http://www.galeriemagazine.com/jewelry-crazy-rich-asians/ |title=Take a Look at the Real, High-End Jewelry of Crazy Rich Asians |author=Choinard, Haley |date=August 22, 2018 |work=Galerie Magazine |accessdate=August 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827075343/http://www.galeriemagazine.com/jewelry-crazy-rich-asians/ |archive-date=August 27, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.windvintage.com/blog/2018/8/23/the-story-of-the-rolex-paul-newman-daytona-in-crazy-rich-asians |title=The Story Of The Rolex 'Paul Newman' Daytona In 'Crazy Rich Asians' |author=Wind, Eric |work=Wind Vintage |date=August 26, 2018 |accessdate=September 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180915001936/https://www.windvintage.com/blog/2018/8/23/the-story-of-the-rolex-paul-newman-daytona-in-crazy-rich-asians |archive-date=September 15, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Yeoh used her friendships with wealthy Singaporean and Hong Kong [[tai tai]]s to help shape final wardrobe choices, and loaned pieces from her personal jewelry collection, including the distinctive emerald engagement ring.<ref name=Vulture-Proposal /><ref name=SCMP-fashion /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theknotnews.com/crazy-rich-asians-emerald-ring-32686 |title=Exclusive: Everything to Know About the Emerald Ring in 'Crazy Rich Asians' |first=Joyce |last=Chen |date=August 17, 2018 |work=The Knot |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823210631/https://www.theknotnews.com/crazy-rich-asians-emerald-ring-32686 |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Kwan and director Chu insisted that all the pieces worn by the Young family must be real; the orchid brooch worn by Su Yi (Ah Ma) at the wedding and a belt buckle for Eleanor (also originally a brooch, but used to make the dress fit Yeoh) were designed by Michelle Ong and loaned from Carnet.<ref name=Vulture-fashion /><ref name=Galerie-jewelry /> Some of the other jewelry pieces, including Astrid's pearl earrings, were loaned from [[Mouawad]], and guards were employed to protect the jewelry,<ref name=THR-sets>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/crazy-rich-asians-inside-fabulous-amazing-costumes-sets-1130966 |title=Inside the \"Gigantic, Fabulous, Amazing\" Costumes and Sets of 'Crazy Rich Asians' |first=Booth |last=Moore |date=August 2, 2018 |newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823175612/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/crazy-rich-asians-inside-fabulous-amazing-costumes-sets-1130966 |archive-date=August 23, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=Vulture-fashion /> which sometimes dictated the filming.<ref name=Wrap-30mil>{{cite news |url=https://www.thewrap.com/crazy-rich-asians-how-mega-rich-world-was-created-for-30-million/ |title=Ballin' on a Budget: How 'Crazy Rich Asians' Made Mega-Rich World for $30 Million |first1=Beatrice |last1=Verhoeven |first2=Matt |last2=Donnelly |date=August 17, 2018 |work=The Wrap |accessdate=August 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827110410/https://www.thewrap.com/crazy-rich-asians-how-mega-rich-world-was-created-for-30-million/ |archive-date=August 27, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The extras who attended the wedding reception were drawn from the Peranakan Association, a historical society, and were asked to wear their own vintage formal clothing to add local flavor to the party.<ref name=THR-sets /><ref name=Fashionista />\n\n=== Music ===\n{{Main|Crazy Rich Asians (soundtrack)}}\n\nDuring the production process, Chu and music supervisor Gabe Hilfer assembled a list of hundreds of songs about money, including songs by [[Kanye West]] (\"[[Gold Digger (Kanye West song)|Gold Digger]]\"), [[Hall & Oates]] (\"[[Rich Girl (Hall & Oates song)|Rich Girl]]\"), [[the Notorious B.I.G.]] (\"[[Mo Money Mo Problems]]\"), [[Lady Gaga]] (\"[[The Fame|Money Honey]]\"), and [[Barrett Strong]] (\"[[Money (That's What I Want)]]\").<ref name=\"EWsoundtrack\">{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2018/08/17/crazy-rich-asians-soundtrack-coldplay-madonna-kina-grannis/|title=''Crazy Rich Asians'': Behind the soundtrack's multilingual covers of Madonna, Coldplay, and more|date=August 17, 2018|first=Shirley|last=Li|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=August 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180819182228/https://ew.com/movies/2018/08/17/crazy-rich-asians-soundtrack-coldplay-madonna-kina-grannis/|archive-date=August 19, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"HPmusic\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/crazy-rich-asians-madonna-coldplay-soundtrack_us_5b75c29de4b02b415d76ddb1|title=How Chinese Covers Of Madonna And Coldplay Made The 'Crazy Rich Asians' Soundtrack|first=Matthew|last=Jacobs|date=August 17, 2018|work=[[HuffPost]]|accessdate=August 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180819181959/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/crazy-rich-asians-madonna-coldplay-soundtrack_us_5b75c29de4b02b415d76ddb1|archive-date=August 19, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Seeking to create a multilingual soundtrack, Chu and Hilfer compiled Chinese songs from the 1950s and 1960s by [[Ge Lan]] (Grace Chang) and [[Yao Lee]], as well as contemporary songs, then searched through YouTube videos for singers fluent in [[Mandarin Chinese]] to provide cover versions of songs.<ref name=\"EWsoundtrack\" /> The film's soundtrack album and score album, by [[Brian Tyler]], were both released on August 10, 2018, through [[WaterTower Music]].<ref name=\"WaterTower\">{{Cite press release|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20180810005021/en/WaterTower-Music-Release-Albums-Music-Romantic-Comedy|title=WaterTower Music to Release Two Albums of Music from the Romantic Comedy ''Crazy Rich Asians''|date=August 10, 2018|location=Los Angeles|first=Joe|last=Kara|agency=[[Business Wire]]|accessdate=August 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821032010/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20180810005021/en/WaterTower-Music-Release-Albums-Music-Romantic-Comedy|archive-date=August 21, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n=== Theatrical ===\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = vertical\n | image1    = Constance Wu, Henry Golding & Gemma Chan.png\n | alt1      = Constance Wu, Henry Golding, and Gemma Chan hold white cards with \"never\" and \"have\" on them\n | image2    = Ken Jeong & Awkwafina.png\n | caption2  =  [[Constance Wu]], [[Henry Golding]], and [[Gemma Chan]] (above, from left) with [[Ken Jeong]] and [[Awkwafina]] promoting the film for [[MTV International]].\n | alt2      = Ken Jeong and Awkwafina hold purple MTV cards\n}}\n''Crazy Rich Asians'' was released in the United States on August 15, 2018, after previously having been scheduled for August 17.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2018/05/six-billion-dollar-man-shining-sequel-doctor-sleep-1202396965 |title='Six Billion Dollar Man' Pushed to Summer 2020 As Pic Looks for New Director; 'The Shining' Sequel Finds Date; 'Godzilla 2' & Others Shift |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=May 23, 2018 |accessdate=May 24, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524000227/http://deadline.com/2018/05/six-billion-dollar-man-shining-sequel-doctor-sleep-1202396965/ |archive-date=May 24, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> An early screening was held in April 2018 at the [[Theatre at Ace Hotel]] in Los Angeles, garnering strong emotional reactions from the audience; other advance screenings were held in San Francisco, Washington D.C., and New York City.<ref name=THR-HighStakes/> The film premiered on August 7, 2018 at the [[TCL Chinese Theatre]] in Los Angeles.<ref name=premiere>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/rambling-reporter/inside-crazy-rich-asians-premiere-director-cast-talk-goldopen-sequel-plans-1133169 |title=Inside 'Crazy Rich Asians' Premiere: Director Jon M. Chu, Cast Talk #GoldOpen, Sequel Plans |last=Gardner |first=Chris |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=August 8, 2018 |accessdate=August 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180809002941/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/rambling-reporter/inside-crazy-rich-asians-premiere-director-cast-talk-goldopen-sequel-plans-1133169 |archive-date=August 9, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The social media hashtag #GoldOpen was used to bring attention to the film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/08/19/media/crazy-rich-asians-box-office/index.html|title='Crazy Rich Asians' exceeds expectations, takes top spot at box office|last=Pallotta|first=Frank|work=CNN|access-date=August 20, 2018|date=August 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820011901/https://money.cnn.com/2018/08/19/media/crazy-rich-asians-box-office/index.html|archive-date=August 20, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The studio spent an estimated $72.18 million on prints and advertisements for the film.<ref name=profit/>\n\nInternationally, ''Crazy Rich Asians'' was released in Singapore on August 22, 2018,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imda.gov.sg/infocomm-and-media-news/sg-spotlight/2018/8/awesome-shows-in-august|title=Awesome shows in August to catch|last=|first=|date=August 6, 2018|website=Info-communications Media Development Authority|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821160517/https://www.imda.gov.sg/infocomm-and-media-news/sg-spotlight/2018/8/awesome-shows-in-august|archive-date=August 21, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=August 21, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and was scheduled for a later release in parts of Europe, although the planned November 2018 U.K. release date was moved forward to September 14, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/crazy-rich-asians-film|title=Crazy Rich Asians|last=|first=|date=|website=British Board of Film Classification|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821185125/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/crazy-rich-asians-film|archive-date=August 21, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=August 21, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/when-is-crazy-rich-asians-out-in-the-uk-its-way-sooner-than-you-think-10164700 |title=When Is 'Crazy Rich Asians' Out In The UK? It's Way Sooner Than You Think |first=Lauren |last=Sharkey |date=August 20, 2018 |work=Bustle |accessdate=August 24, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821114003/https://www.bustle.com/p/when-is-crazy-rich-asians-out-in-the-uk-its-way-sooner-than-you-think-10164700 |archive-date=August 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Later that month, on September 28, 2018, ''Crazy Rich Asians'' released to 75 theaters in Japan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/asia/japan-not-crazy-for-asians-1202958048/|title=Japan Not Expecting Crazy Rich Business With 'Asians'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=September 26, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018|last=Schilling|first=Mark}}</ref> In October 2018, it was announced the film would be released in China on November 30, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/crazy-rich-asians-aquaman-china-release-dates-1202482668/|title='Crazy Rich Asians' Finally Gets China Release Date; 'Aquaman' Diving In Early|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=October 15, 2018|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|accessdate=October 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015162232/https://deadline.com/2018/10/crazy-rich-asians-aquaman-china-release-dates-1202482668/|archive-date=October 15, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''Crazy Rich Asians'' was originally planned to premiere in every Nordic country in September. However, it was delayed and eventually cancelled in Sweden and Denmark without any particular reason. The Swedish distributor Fox told [[:sv:Kulturnyheterna|Kulturnyheterna]] they do not know why the film will not have a Swedish or Danish premiere, and that the decision was made by Warner Bros. Los Angeles office. [[:sv:Kulturnyheterna|Kulturnyheterna]] has on several occasions tried to get Warner Bros. Los Angeles to comment, but to no avail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.svt.se/kultur/film/crazy-rich-asians-far-ingen-svensk-premiar|title=Crazy Rich Asians does not get a Swedish Premiere|last=|first=|date=|website=SVT Nyheter|language=Swedish|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref>\n\nThe film was well received by Singaporean audiences, though some felt it overrepresented and dramatized the wealthy families living there.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/21/movies/crazy-rich-asians-reaction-singapore-intl/index.html|title='Crazy Rich Asians' plays well to hometown crowd in Singapore|last=Putz|first=Ulrike|date=August 22, 2018|accessdate=December 26, 2018|work=[[CNN Entertainment]]}}</ref> Writers and producers in the British film and television industry expressed a hope that ''Crazy Rich Asians''' positive financial reception would lead to more East Asian representation following the film's release in the United Kingdom. The film was considered especially notable due to the presence of multiple British actors of East Asian descent acting in the picture.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://europe.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201810/16/WS5bc5c88aa310eff303282b45.html|title='Crazy Rich Asians' offers new hope to British actors|work=[[China Daily|China Daily UK]]|last=Leung|first=Bo|date=October 16, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn China, however, ''Crazy Rich Asians'' was met a tepid reception among viewers despite initial high expectations from Warner Bros. Pictures.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/12/04/673398040/why-crazy-rich-asians-missed-the-mark-in-chinas-box-offices|title=Why 'Crazy Rich Asians' Missed The Mark In China's Box Offices|work=[[NPR]]|date=December 4, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018|last1=Kelly|first1=Mary Louise|last2=Fritz|first2=Ben}}</ref> Multiple possible reasons were cited for its failure to resonate with Chinese moviegoers. The film's discussion of excessive wealth felt off-putting to audiences due to the start of an [[Recession|economic slowdown]],<ref name=\"CNA\" /> and the film has been compared to the Chinese film ''[[Tiny Times]]'' by some media in China,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forbeschina.com/review/201812/0067417.shtml|title=\u7f8e\u56fd\u7248\"\u5c0f\u65f6\u4ee3\"\u300a\u6458\u91d1\u5947\u7f18\u300b\u5185\u5730\u9996\u6620\u6251\u8857_\u751f\u6d3b\u798f\u5e03\u65af\u4e2d\u6587\u7f51|work=Forbes China|language=chinese|date=December 3, 2018|accessdate=January 24, 2019|last=Xie|first=Charlene}}</ref> and the themes of ethnic and cultural identity were unrelatable and possibly bothersome to viewers.<ref name=\"CRVariety\" /> Unlike in the film's country of origin, the United States, an all-Asian cast was not considered novel in China, and the film lacked notable Chinese stars, other than Michelle Yeoh and Lisa Lu.<ref name=\"CRAtlantic\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/12/crazy-rich-asians-china-box-office/577282/|title=Crazy Rich Asians Tanked in China\u2014But That's Okay|work=[[The Atlantic]]|last=Sims|first=David|date=December 4, 2018|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref> The delayed release of about three-and-a-half months was also said to have hurt ticket sales, as much of the film's potential audience had pirated it or viewed it overseas.<ref name=\"CRAtlantic\" /> Even with its lackluster reception, a Chinese theatrical release was deemed important by producers, as ''China Rich Girlfriend'', the second film in the series, was planned to be partially filmed in Shanghai, potentially as a Chinese co-production.<ref name=\"CRFortune\" /><ref name=\"CRVariety\" />\n\nTourism to Singapore increased following the release of ''Crazy Rich Asians'', attributed in part to the numerous attractions showcased in the film, such as the Marina Bay Sands and [[Raffles Hotel]].<ref name=bloomberg /> The [[Singapore Tourism Board]] partnered with Warner Bros. Pictures during the picture's premiere and contributed to talent and location scouting during production.<ref>\n{{cite news|url=https://qz.com/quartzy/1362090/singapore-hopes-crazy-rich-asians-will-bring-it-luxury-tourism/|title=Singapore is Turning \"Crazy Rich Asians\" into a Rebranding Opportunity|first=Sangeeta|last=Singh-Kurtz|date=August 18, 2018|accessdate=April 29, 2019|work=[[Quartzy]]}}</ref><ref>{{\ncite news|url=https://www.marketing-interactive.com/stb-disappointed-with-crazy-rich-asians-errors-acknowledges-warners-apology/|title=STB disappointed with Crazy Rich Asians mishap, acknowledges Warner's apology|last=Tan|first=Janice|date=August 13, 2018|accessdate=April 29, 2019|work=Marketing Interactive}}</ref> The [[2018 North Korea\u2013United States summit]] held in Singapore, however, was also said to have increased tourist numbers.<ref name=bloomberg>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-12-18/singapore-hotels-get-boost-from-crazy-rich-asian-tourism-boom|title=Singapore's Hotels Get a 'Crazy Rich Asians' Boost|work=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|last=Mahrotri|first= Pooja Thakur|date=December 18, 2018|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref> Sales of the original novel saw an increase of about 1.5 million copies after the film's theatrical release.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2018/09/17/crazy-rich-asians-film-boosts-book-sales-1-5-million-copies/1334172002/|title='Crazy Rich Asians' movie boosts sales for books to 1.5 million copies|work=[[USA Today]]|last=Cadden|first=Mary|date=September 7, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Home video ===\n''Crazy Rich Asians'' was released on digital on November 6, 2018 and on DVD, Blu-ray and Ultra HD Blu-ray on November 20, 2018. The Blu-ray Combo Pack special features include commentary by director Jon M. Chu and novelist Kwan, a gag reel, and deleted scenes.<ref>{{cite web |last=Prange |first=Stephanie |url=https://www.mediaplaynews.com/crazy-rich-asians-coming-to-digital-nov-6-disc-nov-20-from-warner/ |title='Crazy Rich Asians' Coming to Digital Nov. 6, Disc Nov. 20 From Warner |work=[[Media Play News]] |date=October 10, 2018 |accessdate=October 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011133309/https://www.mediaplaynews.com/crazy-rich-asians-coming-to-digital-nov-6-disc-nov-20-from-warner/ |archive-date=October 11, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> As of January 27, 2019, roughly twelve weeks after the film's home video release, ''Crazy Rich Asians'' grossed an estimated $19.1 million domestically from 782,390 collective DVD and Blu-ray sales.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crazy Rich Asians (2018) \u2013 Financial Information|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Crazy-Rich-Asians#tab=summary|website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|access-date=January 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Crazy Rich Asians'' grossed $174.5 million in the United States and Canada, and $64 million elsewhere, for a worldwide gross of $239 million, against a production budget of $30 million.<ref name=BOM/> In October 2018, it became the highest-grossing romantic comedy of the last 10 years, and the 6th-highest-grossing ever.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.msn.com/en-sg/entertainment/movies/news/%e2%80%9ccrazy-rich-asians%e2%80%9d-is-the-top-grossing-romantic-comedy-in-10-years/ar-BBNNtKe |title=\"Crazy Rich Asians\" is the top-grossing romantic comedy in 10 years |first=Ashley |last=Rodriguez |date=October 1, 2018 |work=MSN Entertainment |accessdate=October 2, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002215037/https://www.msn.com/en-sg/entertainment/movies/news/%e2%80%9ccrazy-rich-asians%e2%80%9d-is-the-top-grossing-romantic-comedy-in-10-years/ar-BBNNtKe |archive-date=October 2, 2018 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' calculated the net profit of the film to be $120.8 million, when factoring together all expenses and revenues.<ref name=profit>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/best-movie-profit-2018-green-book-halloween-a-quiet-place-the-nun-crazy-rich-asians-1202589429/|title=Small Movies, Big Profits: 2018 Most Valuable Blockbuster Tournament|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|publisher=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 8, 2019|accessdate=April 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThree weeks before its United States and Canada release, ''Crazy Rich Asians'' was projected to gross $18\u201320 million during its five-day opening weekend.<ref name=THR>{{cite web|last=McClintock|first=Pamela|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/crazy-rich-asians-tracking-20m-us-debut-at-box-office-1129979|title=Box-Office Preview: 'Crazy Rich Asians' Preps for $26M-Plus Walk Down the Aisle|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|date=July 26, 2018|accessdate=July 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726174239/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/crazy-rich-asians-tracking-20m-us-debut-at-box-office-1129979|archive-date=July 26, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> By the week of its release, estimates had reached $26\u201330 million, with [[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] reporting pre-sale tickets were outpacing ''[[Girls Trip]]'' (which debuted to $31.2 million in July 2017).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-box-office-opening-fandango-presales-online-buzz-1202445334/ |title='Crazy Rich Asians' Could Hit $30M In 5-Day Opening; Fandango Presales Currently Besting 'Girls Trip' |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=August 14, 2018 |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=August 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180814232738/https://deadline.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-box-office-opening-fandango-presales-online-buzz-1202445334/ |archive-date=August 14, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=McClintock|first=Pamela|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-crazy-rich-asians-preps-26m-debut-1134632|title='Crazy Rich Asians' Tracking for $20M U.S. Debut|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|date=August 14, 2018|accessdate=August 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180814164826/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-crazy-rich-asians-preps-26m-debut-1134632|archive-date=August 14, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The film held special advance screenings on August 8, 2018, and made an estimated $450,000\u2013500,000, selling out most of its 354 theaters.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-box-office-sneak-previews-1202443100/ |title='Crazy Rich Asians' Sells Out Bulk Of Paid Sneak Previews Wednesday Night |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=August 9, 2018 |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=August 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180809190120/https://deadline.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-box-office-sneak-previews-1202443100/ |archive-date=August 9, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> It then took in $5 million on its first day and $3.8 million on its second. It went on to gross $26.5 million in its opening weekend, for a five-day total of $35.2 million, finishing [[List of 2018 box office number-one films in the United States|first at the box office]]. 38% of its audience was of Asian descent, which was the highest Asian makeup for a film in U.S. in the previous three years (besting ''[[The Foreigner (2017 film)|The Foreigner]]''{{'}}s 18.4% in 2017).<ref name=opening>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-wednesday-opening-box-office-1202446094/ |title='Crazy Rich Asians' Even Richer On Saturday With $10M+; Weekend Bling Now At $25M+ With $34M 5-Day Debut |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=August 19, 2018 |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=August 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816194613/https://deadline.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-wednesday-opening-box-office-1202446094/ |archive-date=August 16, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In its second weekend the film made $24.8 million, a [[second weekend in box office performance|box office drop]] of just 6%, which ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' called \"unbelievable.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/melissa-mccarthy-happytime-murders-crazy-rich-asians-meg-weekend-box-office-1202451694/ |title='Why 'Happytime Murders' Reps A Solo Career B.O. Low For Melissa McCarthy In A 'Crazy Rich' Weekend |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=August 26, 2018 |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=August 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825073010/https://deadline.com/2018/08/melissa-mccarthy-happytime-murders-crazy-rich-asians-meg-weekend-box-office-1202451694/ |archive-date=August 25, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2018/08/27/crazy-rich-asians-box-office-constance-wu-henry-golding-jon-m-chu/#492270815459 |title=Box Office: 'Crazy Rich Asians' Fell Just 6% In Its Second Weekend |website=[[Forbes]] |date=August 27, 2018 |first=Scott |last=Mendelson |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905042635/https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2018/08/27/crazy-rich-asians-box-office-constance-wu-henry-golding-jon-m-chu/#492270815459 |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The film continued to play well in its third weekend, making $22 million (a drop of just 11% from the previous week) and remaining in first.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-operation-finale-the-meg-labor-day-weekend-box-office-1202454590/ |title='Crazy Rich Asians' Accumulates Wealth Over Labor Day With $116M+ Total; Bigger Than 'The Help' & 'The Butler' |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=September 2, 2018 |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=September 2, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831035413/https://deadline.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-operation-finale-the-meg-labor-day-weekend-box-office-1202454590/ |archive-date=August 31, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The film was finally dethroned in its fourth weekend, finishing third behind newcomers ''[[The Nun (2018 film)|The Nun]]'' and ''[[Peppermint (2018 film)|Peppermint]]'' with $13.1 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/the-nun-weekend-box-office-conjuring-records-peppermint-jennifer-garner-1202459068/ |title='The Nun' Hits The Hallelujah With $54M Opening, Best Ever In 'Conjuring' Universe \u2013 Sunday AM Update |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=September 9, 2018 |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=September 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912121836/https://deadline.com/2018/09/the-nun-weekend-box-office-conjuring-records-peppermint-jennifer-garner-1202459068/ |archive-date=September 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn Singapore, where the film takes place, ''Crazy Rich Asians'' grossed over $5 million.<ref name=\"CNA\">{{cite news|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/commentary/why-movie-crazy-rich-asians-flopped-in-china-dismal-showing-11004954|title=Commentary: Why Crazy Rich Asians was the last movie China wanted to watch|last=McGregor|first=Tom|date=December 7, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018|work=[[Channel NewsAsia]]}}</ref> The first-week ticket sales for the film, $2.5 million, were considered unusually high. Large numbers of organizations and individuals buying out theaters to host screenings, as well as general interest in seeing how Hollywood portrayed the city-state, were noted as major contributors to the film's high Singaporean box office totals.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://sg.style.yahoo.com/singapore-gives-crazy-rich-asians-warm-box-office-reception-103303388.html|title=Singapore gives 'Crazy Rich Asians' warm box office reception|last=Yong Ping|first=Teng|work=[[Yahoo!]] Lifestyle Singapore|date=August 28, 2018|accessdate=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe film's theatrical release in China was considered unsuccessful, finishing eighth at the box office opening weekend and losing half of its screens from Saturday to Sunday.<ref name=\"CRVariety\">{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/asia/crazy-rich-asians-flops-in-china-box-office-debut-1203071333/|title='Crazy Rich Asians' Flops at the Chinese Box Office|last=Davis|first=Patrick|last2=Frater|first2=Becky|date=December 2, 2018|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=December 4, 2018}}</ref> Initial reports stated that the film failed to pass one million dollars opening weekend following a combined $810,000 on Friday and Saturday,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2018/12/02/crazy-rich-asians-china-box-office/|title='Crazy Rich Asians' Struggles at Chinese Box Office|last=Neto|first=Veronica|date=December 2, 2018|accessdate=December 26, 2018|work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]}}</ref> but the figure was later updated to a total of $1.2 million.<ref name=\"CRFortune\">{{cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2018/12/02/crazy-rich-asians-china-box-office/|title='Crazy Rich Asians' had a crazy bad opening weekend in China|work=[[CNN Business]]|last=Pham|first=Sherisse|date=December 3, 2018|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn South Korea, the film failed at the box office, finishing sixth at the box office on its opening weekend and by its second week the film fell to fourteenth place.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3055337|title=\u2018Crazy Rich Asians\u2019 doesn\u2019t find love in Korea: A box office sensation in the U.S., the movie has failed to resonate in Asia|last=Jin|first=Min-Ji|date=November 8, 2018|work=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|access-date=January 20, 2020}}</ref> In total, the film only made a little over $1.1 million at the South Korean box office.<ref name=BOM/>\n\n===Critical response===\n[[File:Michelle Yeoh Cannes 2017.jpg|thumb|alt=Michelle Yeoh smiles, facing forward and waving|[[Michelle Yeoh]]'s performance as Eleanor Sung-Young received widespread critical praise.<ref name=\"lat\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/movies/michelle-yeoh-crazy-rich-asians-fans-hug-me-in-the-street-37492473.html|title=Michelle Yeoh: Crazy Rich Asians fans hug me in the street|last1=Southern|first1=Keiran|date=November 5, 2018|website=Irish Independent|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/ap/news/996537/where-are-the-crazy-rich-asians-now#photo-965075|title=Where Are the Crazy Rich Asians Now?|last=Chiun|first=Adriel|date=December 13, 2018|work=[[E!]]|access-date=December 26, 2018|quote=And so convincing is Michelle Yeoh's performance in Crazy Rich Asians, as Nick Young (Golding)'s mother that she received widespread critical praise.}}</ref>|upright=0.8]]\nOn review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 91% based on 338 reviews, with an average rating of 7.66/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"With a terrific cast and a surfeit of visual razzle dazzle, ''Crazy Rich Asians'' takes a satisfying step forward for screen representation while deftly drawing inspiration from the classic\u2014and still effective\u2014rom-com formula.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/crazy_rich_asians|title=Crazy Rich Asians (2018)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=June 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824040248/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/crazy_rich_asians|archive-date=August 24, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 74 out of 100, based on 50 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/crazy-rich-asians|title=Crazy Rich Asians Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=September 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823061625/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/crazy-rich-asians|archive-date=August 23, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\" on an A+ to F scale, while [[PostTrak]] reported filmgoers gave it an 85% positive score and a 65% \"definite recommend\".<ref name=opening/> On the Chinese review aggregation website [[Douban]], however, the film scored merely 6.1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://movie.douban.com/subject/26786642/|title=\u6458\u91d1\u5947\u7f18 Crazy Rich Asians (2018)|work=[[Crazy Rich Asians]]|accessdate=May 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Joe Morgenstern]], writing for ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', found the film to be \"Bright, buoyant, and hilarious,\" making special note of the large number of quality performances from the cast members: \"And anyone with a sense of movie history will be moved by the marvelous Ms. Yeoh, who was so memorable as the love-starved fighter in ''[[Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon]],'' and by 91-year-old [[Lisa Lu]], who plays Nick's grandmother and the matriarch of his family. Anyone, in this case, means anyone. ''Crazy Rich Asians'' includes us all\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Joe |last=Morgenstern |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |title=Conspicuously Consuming Fun |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/crazy-rich-asians-review-conspicuously-consuming-fun-1534456267 |date=August 16, 2018 |accessdate=August 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822232612/https://www.wsj.com/articles/crazy-rich-asians-review-conspicuously-consuming-fun-1534456267 |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Ann Hornaday]], writing for ''[[The Washington Post]]'', deemed the film a \"escapist rom-com delight\" and remarked that \"It will more than satisfy the sweet tooth of romantic comedy fans everywhere who have lately despaired that the frothy, frolicsome genre they adore has been subsumed by raunch and various shades of gray\"; she also compared the film's rom-com themes to ''[[Four Weddings and a Funeral]]'' (1994).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/crazy-rich-asians-is-an-escapist-rom-com-delight-its-also-a-lot-more-than-that/2018/08/14/0015bfe0-9d9a-11e8-843b-36e177f3081c_story.html |date=August 14, 2018 |title='Crazy Rich Asians' is an escapist rom-com delight. It's also a lot more than that. |author-link=Ann Hornaday |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |first=Ann |last=Hornaday |accessdate=September 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905215529/https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/crazy-rich-asians-is-an-escapist-rom-com-delight-its-also-a-lot-more-than-that/2018/08/14/0015bfe0-9d9a-11e8-843b-36e177f3081c_story.html |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine published an extended cultural review of the film by Karen Ho, which compared the [[Haute couture|high fashion appeal]] of the film to rival the best of previous films such as ''[[The Devil Wears Prada (film)|The Devil Wears Prada]]''. Ho summarizes the film's success as a notable uphill battle against the season's predominantly superhero oriented audiences: \"To many in Hollywood, ''Crazy Rich Asians'' might look like a risky bet. It's the first modern story with an all-Asian cast and an Asian-American lead in 25 years; the last ''[[The Joy Luck Club (film)|Joy Luck Club]]'', was in 1993. It's an earnest romantic comedy in a sea of action and superhero films...In fact, it seems destined to be a hit.\"<ref name=Time-KarenHo>{{cite magazine |url=http://time.com/longform/crazy-rich-asians/ |magazine=Time |first=Karen |last=Ho |title=''Crazy Rich Asians'' Is Going to Change Hollywood. It's About Time |date=August 15, 2018 |pages=40\u201346 |accessdate=August 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180902002626/http://time.com/longform/crazy-rich-asians/ |archive-date=September 2, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }} (physically published in August 27, 2018 issue; digitally published on August 15)</ref> In the same magazine, [[Stephanie Zacharek]] called the film as \"simply great fun, a winsome romantic comedy and an occasionally over-the-top luxury fantasy that never flags,\" while at the same time hailing the film as a breakthrough in representation and lauded the performances and chemistry of Wu and Golding as well as the supporting performances (particularly Yeoh, [[Ken Jeong]], [[Nico Santos (actor)|Nico Santos]] and [[Awkwafina]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/5368281/crazy-rich-asians-review/|title=Crazy Rich Asians Is a Breakthrough in Representation. But It's Also Simply Great Fun|author=Zacharek, Stephanie|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=August 15, 2018|accessdate=September 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825004642/http://time.com/5368281/crazy-rich-asians-review/|archive-date=August 25, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the film four stars out of five; he called it \"frothy fun\" and a \"hilarious, heartfelt blast\" while hailing the film as \"making history\" in its cultural representation in mainstream cinema and highlighting the performances (particularly Yeoh, whose performance he called \"layered\").<ref>{{cite web|first=Peter|last=Travers|authorlink=Peter Travers|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/crazy-rich-asians-movie-review-707789/|title='Crazy Rich Asians' Review: Romcom Is Crazy Representative, Frothy Fun|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=August 13, 2018|access-date=September 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907011000/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/crazy-rich-asians-movie-review-707789/|archive-date=September 7, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', [[Richard Roeper]] described the film as a \"pure escapist fantasy fun\" and \"24-karat entertainment\" while praising Wu's and Golding's performances and chemistry, and complimented Golding's natural onscreen presence and his good sense of comedic timing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/crazy-rich-asians-review-movie-henry-golding-constance-wu-michelle-yeoh/|title=Upbeat and upscale, 'Crazy Rich Asians' delivers 24-karat entertainment|author=Richard Roeper|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=August 14, 2018|accessdate=September 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907071426/https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/crazy-rich-asians-review-movie-henry-golding-constance-wu-michelle-yeoh/|archive-date=September 7, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Richard Roeper}}</ref> David Sims of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' lauded the film as a \"breath of fresh air\" and a \"charming throwback\" to the classic romantic comedy films while commending Chu's direction, the \"hyperactive\" screenplay, and the performances of Wu and Yeoh.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-review/566921/|title=Crazy Rich Asians Is a Breath of Fresh Air|author=David Sims|work=[[The Atlantic]]|date=August 15, 2018|accessdate=September 11, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911152244/https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-review/566921/|archive-date=September 11, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Justin Chang]] in a review for the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' found the film worthy of comparison to other notable films using an Asian ensemble cast including ''[[Memoirs of a Geisha (film)|Memoirs of a Geisha]]'', ''[[Letters from Iwo Jima]]'', and ''The Joy Luck Club''. Chang found the supporting cast performance of [[Michelle Yeoh]] to be exceptional, stating \"you can't help but hang on Eleanor's (Michelle Yeoh's) every word. In a crisp, authoritative, sometimes startlingly vulnerable performance that never lapses into dragon-lady stereotype, Yeoh brilliantly articulates the unique relationship between Asian parents and their children, the intricate chain of love, guilt, devotion and sacrifice that binds them for eternity\".<ref name=\"lat\">{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-crazy-rich-asians-review-20180808-story.html |title=Review: A flawed but vital milestone, 'Crazy Rich Asians' pays exuberant tribute to Singapore's 1% |first=Justin |last=Chang |author-link=Justin Chang |date=August 8, 2018 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=August 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826231728/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-crazy-rich-asians-review-20180808-story.html |archive-date=August 26, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn his review for ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[A. O. Scott]] indicates that the film's appeal surpasses contemporary [[social more]]s dealing with wealth and touches on themes examined in the literature of \"[[conspicuous consumption|endless luxury]]\" over the centuries stating that this is \"...part of the film's sly and appealing old-fashionedness. Without betraying any overt nostalgia, ''Crazy Rich Asians'' casts a fond eye backward as well as Eastward, conjuring a world defined by hierarchies and prescribed roles in a way that evokes classic novels and films. Its keenest romantic impulse has less to do with Nick and Rachel's rather pedestrian love story than with the allure of endless luxury and dynastic authority. Which I guess is pretty modern after all\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/14/movies/crazy-rich-asians-review.html |title=Review: 'Crazy Rich Asians' Is a Party With a First-Rate Guest List |first=A.O. |last=Scott |author-link=A. O. Scott |date=August 14, 2018 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=August 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827174051/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/14/movies/crazy-rich-asians-review.html |archive-date=August 27, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Peter Debruge of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote that the movie \"expertly manages to balance the opulence of incalculable wealth with the pragmatic, well-grounded sensibility\" of its protagonist; he also drew comparisons of the film's visual style and tone to [[Baz Luhrmann]]'s ''[[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|The Great Gatsby]]'' (2013) as well to the wedding sequence in ''[[Mamma Mia! (film)|Mamma Mia!]]'' (2008).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/crazy-rich-asians-review-1202900373/|title=Film Review: 'Crazy Rich Asians'|work=Variety|first=Peter|last=Debruge|date=August 8, 2018|accessdate=September 10, 2018|df=mdy-all|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906085602/https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/crazy-rich-asians-review-1202900373/|archive-date=September 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Robbie Collin]] of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' gave the film four stars out of five, and wrote that the film was \"a mouthwatering slice of deluxe romcom escapism\" and \"plays like a [[Jane Austen]] novel crossed with a ''[[Mr. & Mrs. Smith (2005 film)|Mr. & Mrs. Smith]]'' brochure\" while lending his praise on the performances of Wu, Golding, Yeoh, and Awkwafina.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crazy Rich Asians review: a mouthwatering slice of deluxe romcom escapism|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/0/crazy-rich-asians-review-mouthwatering-slice-deluxe-romcom-escapism/|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|accessdate=September 23, 2018|date=September 13, 2018|first=Robbie|last=Collin|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923202053/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/0/crazy-rich-asians-review-mouthwatering-slice-deluxe-romcom-escapism/|archive-date=September 23, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nScott Mendelson, writing for ''[[Forbes]]'', found the film to be below average and to have an uneven plot line with contrived humor similar to his opinion of the 2002 film ''[[My Big Fat Greek Wedding]]'' stating: \"Without having read the book, I might argue that the core flaw of ''Crazy Rich Asians'' is that it's so determined to be the Asian-American version of the conventional Hollywood romantic comedy that it becomes a deeply conventional romantic comedy, complete with the bad, the good and the generic tropes. It's well-acted and offers plenty of cultural specificity, but the supporting characters are thin and the need to be universal hobbles its drama\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2018/08/13/crazy-rich-asians-review-too-much-rich-not-enough-crazy/ |title=Review: 'Crazy Rich Asians' Is A Disappointingly Generic Romcom |first=Scott |last=Mendelson |date=August 13, 2018 |work=Forbes |accessdate=August 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827175137/https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2018/08/13/crazy-rich-asians-review-too-much-rich-not-enough-crazy/ |archive-date=August 27, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHe was joined in his criticism by [[Kate Taylor (novelist)|Kate Taylor]] of ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', who wrote: \"As the obscenities of wealth accumulate while a large cast of Asian and Eurasian actors render their many silly characters, the source of the laughter becomes troubling.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/reviews/article-review-yes-of-course-love-is-far-more-important-than-money-crazy/ |title=Review: Love is more important than money, Crazy Rich Asians tells us \u2013 but way too blandly |first=Kate |last=Taylor |date=August 14, 2018 |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |author-link=Kate Taylor (novelist) |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |quote=A white viewer such as myself witnessing this overblown display may find themselves in that awkward territory where somebody else's ethnic comedy leaves them feeling complicit in racial prejudice. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905134630/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/reviews/article-review-yes-of-course-love-is-far-more-important-than-money-crazy/ |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> David Rooney of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' gave a mixed review, in which he criticized the film's pacing as \"uneven\" but nevertheless similarly praised the performances and chemistry of Wu and Golding, and singled out Wu's performance as the film's real heart.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rooney|first1=David|title='Crazy Rich Asians': Film Review|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/crazy-rich-asians-review-1133077|accessdate=September 16, 2018|work=The Hollywood Reporter|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180915124515/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/crazy-rich-asians-review-1133077|archive-date=September 15, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Tony Wong of ''[[Toronto Star]]'' argued the film \"doesn't blow away stereotypes. It reinforces them. There is little room for subtlety here\u2014the title underlines the mission statement. Asians are rich, vulgar and clueless.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/opinion/2018/08/18/crazy-rich-asians-doesnt-break-stereotypes-it-reinforces-them.html |title=Crazy Rich Asians doesn't break stereotypes, it reinforces them |last=Wong |first=Tony |date=August 18, 2018 |work=Toronto Star |accessdate=December 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|CastingCriticism|Controversy}}\n\n==Casting criticism==\nAlthough the film has been lauded in the United States for featuring a predominantly Asian cast,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-box-office-crazy-rich-asians-20180819-story.html |title='Crazy Rich Asians' dominates the box office, makes history for representation |last=Kelley |first=Sonaiya |date=August 19, 2018 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=September 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906071908/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-box-office-crazy-rich-asians-20180819-story.html |archive-date=September 6, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> it was criticized elsewhere for casting biracial and non-Chinese actors in ethnically Chinese roles.<ref name=\"ST-2017-04-26\" /> The film was also criticized for having characters speak British English and American English over [[Singapore English|Singaporean English]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/film/106395816/crazy-rich-asians-is-not-us-say-singaporeans |title=Crazy Rich Asians is not us, say Singaporeans |first=Kirsten |last=Han |date=August 20, 2018 |newspaper=Stuff New Zealand |accessdate=September 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.star2.com/entertainment/2018/05/04/crazy-rich-asians-trailer-controversies/ |accessdate=August 20, 2018 |author=Agency |work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|Star2]] |title='Crazy Rich Asians' criticised for being too Chinese, not Singlish enough |date=May 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620101248/https://www.star2.com/entertainment/2018/05/04/crazy-rich-asians-trailer-controversies/ |archive-date=June 20, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In addition, the film has received criticism for poorly representing the actual makeup of Singapore by virtually erasing non-Chinese citizens.<ref name=Econ-1809>{{cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/asia/2018/09/01/for-a-different-take-on-crazy-rich-asians-cross-the-pacific |title=For a different take on \"Crazy Rich Asians\", cross the Pacific |author=Banyan |date=September 1, 2018 |work=The Economist |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905120621/https://www.economist.com/asia/2018/09/01/for-a-different-take-on-crazy-rich-asians-cross-the-pacific |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/16/world/asia/crazy-rich-asians-cast-singapore.html |title=For Some Viewers, 'Crazy Rich Asians' Is Not Asian Enough |last=Ives |first=Mike |date=August 16, 2018 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=September 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904042044/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/16/world/asia/crazy-rich-asians-cast-singapore.html |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Lead actors===\nThe casting of biracial actor Henry Golding, who is of [[Iban people|Malaysian Iban]] and English descent, as the [[Chinese Singaporeans|Chinese Singaporean]] character Nick Young was highly controversial, drawing accusations of [[Discrimination based on skin color|colorism]]. The casting of Sonoya Mizuno, a multiracial actress of Japanese, Argentinian and English ancestry, as Araminta Lee, another Singaporean Chinese character, also attracted criticism. [[Korean American]] actress [[Jamie Chung]], who had auditioned for a role but was turned down allegedly for not being \"ethnically Chinese\", responded to a question about Golding's casting with \"That is some bullshit. Where do you draw the line to be ethnically conscious? But there's so many loopholes...\" in an interview published on April 24, 2017.<ref name=CBS-2017-04-24>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/jamie-chung-on-the-double-edged-sword-of-being-a-minority-in-hollywood/ |title=Jamie Chung on the \"double-edged sword\" of being a minority in Hollywood |first=Andrea |last=Park |work=[[CBS News]] |date=April 24, 2017 |accessdate=February 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180317222231/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/jamie-chung-on-the-double-edged-sword-of-being-a-minority-in-hollywood/ |archive-date=March 17, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Chung's remarks were met with backlash on social media, with some accusing her of being biased against [[Eurasian (mixed ancestry)|Eurasians]] and noting that she had previously played [[Hua Mulan|Mulan]], an ethnic Chinese character, in the television series ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]'',<ref name=\"chungns\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/10/asian-american-actors-tv-roles-jamie-chung-kal-penn-1201886012/2/|work=[[IndieWire]]|title=Asian American TV Actors Expose the Difficulty of Landing Parts \u2013 With or Without an Accent|last=Nguyen|first=Hanh|date=October 11, 2017|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> causing Chung to clarify her comments on social media.<ref name=\"chungns\">{{cite news|url=https://nextshark.com/jamie-chung-clarifies-bullsht-remark-hapa-actor-crazy-rich-asians/|title=Jamie Chung Calls 'Crazy Rich Asians' Casting of Half-White Actor 'Bullsh*t'|date=April 24, 2018|accessdate=December 29, 2018|work=Next Shark|last=Casino|first=Khier}}</ref> Chung subsequently apologized to Golding for her comments, which he accepted.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/jamie-chung-apology-henry-golding_us_5a254b23e4b0a02abe926905|title=Jamie Chung Apologizes For Attacking 'Crazy Rich Asians' Casting Of Half-Asian Actor|last=Yam|first=Kimberly|date=December 4, 2017|accessdate=December 28, 2018|work=[[HuffPost]]}}</ref> She later expressed her support for ''Crazy Rich Asians'' and its cast, stating that because of them \"there will be other projects [...] that will be full Asian casts.\"<ref>{{cite interview |last=Chung |first=Jamie |subjectlink=Jamie Chung |interviewer=Courtney Tezeno |title=Why Jamie Chung Isn't Asking for a Role in 'Crazy Rich Asians 2' (Exclusive)|work=[[Entertainment Tonight]] |publisher=[[CBS Television Distribution]] |location=Los Angeles |date=November 9, 2018|accessdate=December 31, 2018|url=https://www.etonline.com/media/videos/why-jamie-chung-isnt-asking-for-a-role-in-crazy-rich-asians-2-exclusive-113463}}</ref>\n\nGolding initially called the criticism towards his casting \"quite hurtful\",<ref name=Time-2017-11-02>{{cite web |url=http://ew.com/movies/2017/11/02/crazy-rich-asians-henry-golding-defends-casting/ |title='Crazy Rich Asians' star Henry Golding defends his casting |date=November 2, 2017 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |first=Shirley |last=Li |accessdate=February 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201024726/http://ew.com/movies/2017/11/02/crazy-rich-asians-henry-golding-defends-casting/ |archive-date=February 1, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> but was later more open towards criticism as he felt that there \"should be a conversation about it\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.instyle.com/news/henry-golding-crazy-rich-asians-casting |title=''Crazy Rich Asians'' Star Henry Golding Says It's Fair to Question His Casting |work=InStyle |first=Isabel |last=Jones |date=July 13, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |quote=Ultimately, Golding, who moved from his native Malaysia to the UK at age 7, felt the dialogue his casting sparked was a good sign. 'There ''should'' be a conversation about it, because if there wasn't, I think we wouldn't be able to educate people. There are allowed to be questions like that, because the past has dictated that roles have been whitewashed.'<br />{{pad|1.0em}}But here, he assures, 'That wasn't the case. I was the one who fit the role as perfectly as possible for [director] Jon [M. Chu], after seeing everybody. I literally was the last person they saw.' |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831002536/https://www.instyle.com/news/henry-golding-crazy-rich-asians-casting |archive-date=August 31, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> while Mizuno said that the criticism towards her casting \"pissed [her] off\".<ref name=TheCut-2018-08>{{cite interview |url=https://www.thecut.com/2018/08/interview-ex-machina-crazy-rich-asians-star-sonoya-mizuno.html |title=Sonoya Mizuno Doesnt't Just Want to Dance |subject=Sonoya Mizuno |interviewer=Kathleen Hou |date=August 2018 |work=The Cut |accessdate=August 30, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830210424/https://www.thecut.com/2018/08/interview-ex-machina-crazy-rich-asians-star-sonoya-mizuno.html |archivedate=August 30, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Several of Golding's costars also defended his casting, with Ronny Chieng declaring that Golding was \"more Malaysian than most Malaysians\"<ref>{{youtube|id=oPG8GKJ9U6Y |title=Eating nice Chinese food w/ Crazy Rich Asians cast \u2013 Ronny Chieng}} at timestamp 5:34</ref> while Awkwafina jokingly stated it would have been bad only if the producers had cast [[Emma Stone]] as Nick, referring to the 2015 film ''[[Aloha (2015 film)#Whitewashing controversy|Aloha]]''.<ref name=HuffPo-2017-12-01>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/crazy-rich-asians-awkwafina_us_5a203433e4b0392a4ebc04eb |title='Crazy Rich Asians' Star: Hollywood Caves To Diversity When It's Scared |work=HuffPost |first=Kimberly |last=Yam |date=December 2, 2017 |accessdate=June 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617191248/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/crazy-rich-asians-awkwafina_us_5a203433e4b0392a4ebc04eb |archive-date=June 17, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nSociologist and the author of ''Reel Inequality: Hollywood Actors and Racism'', Nancy Wang Yuen, defended Golding's casting, surmising that criticism was fueled out of [[Racial hygiene|racial purity]]. By deeming Golding \"not Asian enough\", detractors were choosing to ignore his Asian heritage. Yuen contrasted Golding's situation to the public perception of former U.S. President [[Barack Obama]], who is also biracial. She noted how \"the world sees President Obama as black, but his mother is white\" and called out the double standard in \"[erasing] Golding's Asian ancestry while obliterating Obama's white ancestry.\"<ref name=\"HuffPo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/crazy-rich-asians-henry-golding-casting_us_5a1f172ce4b0d52b8dc2632e |title='Crazy Rich Asians' Star Claps Back At Criticism That He's 'Not Asian Enough' |work=HuffPost |first=Kimberly |last=Yam |date=November 30, 2017 |accessdate=February 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204123522/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/crazy-rich-asians-henry-golding-casting_us_5a1f172ce4b0d52b8dc2632e |archive-date=February 4, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nDirector Jon M. Chu defended his decision to cast Golding, stating that questions about the cast and particularly Golding made him uneasy,<ref name=NYT-SoLongCast>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/08/movies/crazy-rich-asians-cast.html|first=Robert|last=Ito|title='Crazy Rich Asians': Why Did It Take So Long to See a Cast Like This?|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 8, 2018|access-date=August 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180819190509/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/08/movies/crazy-rich-asians-cast.html|archive-date=August 19, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> later acknowledging:\n\n{{cquote|I realized that I was only getting angry at the people who felt that they had been burned. They were people like me who had watched Hollywood whitewash things, and watched roles go away because someone said an Asian man can't be the lead of this or that.<ref name=NYT-SoLongCast />}}\n\nJohn Lui, an ethnic Chinese Singaporean reporter for ''The Straits Times'', criticized the casting, opining that [[One-drop rule|a single drop of Asian blood]] was enough for Hollywood, who was motivated to cast Golding (an \"ethnically ambiguous face\") because of his appeal to a wide variety of audiences. Lui tempered his criticism, stating \"it is wrong to sort actors into 'Asian' and 'not Asian enough' piles\".<ref name=\"ST-2017-04-26\">{{cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/viewpoint-colourism-mars-crazy-rich-asians-main-casting|title=Colourism mars Crazy Rich Asians main casting|first=John|last=Lui|date=April 26, 2017|work=The Straits Times|accessdate=February 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426043625/https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/viewpoint-colourism-mars-crazy-rich-asians-main-casting|archive-date=April 26, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Nick Chen of ''The Independent'' also spoke negatively about the casting, labeling Golding's casting as whitewashing gone unnoticed by critics and moviegoers. Chung's initial comments were cited as one of the few instances of backlash.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/crazy-rich-asians-film-henry-golding-constance-wu-whitewashing-a8536001.html|title=Why I'm only half-crazy about Crazy Rich Asians|last=Chen|first=Nick|work=[[The Independent]]|date=September 15, 2018|accessdate=December 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with ''[[Teen Vogue]]'' in November 2019, American actress [[Brenda Song]] stated that she was not permitted to audition for ''Crazy Rich Asians'' as, according to Song, her \"image was basically not Asian enough, in not so many words\". Song continued that she felt disappointed by the response, questioning why the filmmakers were \"fault[ing] [her] for having worked [her] whole life.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/brenda-song-dollface|title=Brenda Song on Her New Series Dollface, the Disney Channel Years, and Growing Up|work=[[Teen Vogue]]|first=Gabe|last=Bergado|date=November 20, 2019|accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref> Song's alleged denial was met with backlash within the [[Asian Americans|Asian American]] community online, as Song portrayed the \"original crazy rich Asian\" [[London Tipton]] in the 2005 [[Disney Channel]] series ''[[The Suite Life of Zack and Cody]]''.<ref name=\"nbc brenda song\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/crazy-rich-asians-director-denies-brenda-song-was-told-she-n1089346|title='Crazy Rich Asians' director denies Brenda Song was told she wasn't 'Asian enough' for film|work=[[NBC News]]|date=November 21, 2019|accessdate=December 21, 2019|last=Yam|first=Kimmy}}</ref> Specially, Rachel Chang of ''[[Forbes]]'' stated that Song \"single-handedly represented Asian Americans to a new generation of a impressionable television viewers.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/rachelchang1/2019/11/22/crazy-rich-and-not-asian-enough-why-brenda-song-never-got-to-audition-for-crazy-rich-asians/#7d24f94f5196|title=Crazy, Rich and \u2018Not Asian Enough\u2019: Why Brenda Song Never Got to Audition for \u2018Crazy Rich Asians\u2019|last=Chang|first=Rachel|work=[[Forbes]]|date=November 22, 2019|accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref> Director Jon M. Chu responded to the comments on Twitter, stating that \"it sucks if anything of that nature was ever communicated. It\u2019s gross actually\". He added that he was a big fan of Song's work, and would have cast her in the film without an audition if he knew. He later followed up the tweet with an article about the open casting call held for the film, citing it as one of his favorite memories during production.<ref name=\"nbc brenda song\" />\n\n===Ethnic representation of Singapore===\n{{See also|Race in Singapore|Demographics of Singapore}}\n\nIn contrast to those calling for Chinese or East Asian actors to fill its roles, others, particularly those in Asian countries, expressed disappointment in the film's lack of ethnic [[South Asia|South]] and [[Southeast Asia]]ns, who have prominent presence in Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://quartzy.qz.com/1260412/crazy-rich-asians-trailer-south-asians-criticize-film-for-lack-of-ethnic-diversity-and-singaporean-accent/ |first=Alice |last=Truong |title=The Trailer For \"Crazy Rich Asians\" Has Some Asking: Where Are The Brown Faces? |work=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartzy]] |date=April 24, 2018 |accessdate=June 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620051054/https://quartzy.qz.com/1260412/crazy-rich-asians-trailer-south-asians-criticize-film-for-lack-of-ethnic-diversity-and-singaporean-accent/ |archive-date=June 20, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"ISN\"/> Kirsten Han, a Singaporean journalist, said that the film \"obscur[ed] the [[Malay Singaporeans|Malay]], [[Indian Singaporeans|Indian]], and [[Eurasians in Singapore|Eurasian]] (and more) populations who make the country the culturally rich and unique place that it is.\"<ref name=\"Kirsten Han\">{{cite web |url=https://theestablishment.co/crazy-rich-asians-is-a-win-for-diverse-representation-not-quite-7b93f131fafd |title=Why 'Crazy Rich Asians' Isn't Really A Win For Diverse Representation |work=The Establishment |first=Kirsten |last=Han |date=March 20, 2017 |accessdate=June 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180818160019/https://theestablishment.co/crazy-rich-asians-is-a-win-for-diverse-representation-not-quite-7b93f131fafd/ |archive-date=August 18, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Some were critical towards the omission of the country's Malays and Indians\u2014the second and third largest ethnic groups in Singapore, respectively\u2014thus not representing its multiracial population accurately.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/aug/21/where-are-the-brown-people-crazy-rich-asians-draws-tepid-response-in-singapore|title=Where are the brown people? Crazy Rich Asians draws tepid response in Singapore|last=Ellis-Petersen|first=Hannah|last2=Kuo|first2=Lily|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=August 21, 2018|accessdate=January 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Newton Food Centre 6, Aug 06.JPG|thumb|upright=0.8|The film's scene at the [[Newton Food Centre]] received criticism for its lack of cultural diversity when showing vendors and the food they serve.<ref name=\"NFC\" />|alt=A row of food stalls and picnic tables, with an awning above.]]\nIan Chong, a political scientist at the National University of Singapore, commented that the film \"represents the worst of Singapore. Erases minorities. Erases the poor and marginalized. All you get are rich, privileged ethnic Chinese.\"<ref name=\"ISN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.inkstonenews.com/society/really-singapore-crazy-rich-asians-trailer-stirs-debate/article/2143269 |work=Inkstone News |first1=Viola |last1=Zhou |first2=Grace |last2=Tsoi |title=Is this really Singapore? Crazy Rich Asians trailer stirs debate |date=April 25, 2018 |accessdate=June 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622192855/https://www.inkstonenews.com/society/really-singapore-crazy-rich-asians-trailer-stirs-debate/article/2143269 |archive-date=June 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Alfian Sa'at]], a [[Malay Singaporeans|Malay Singaporean]] poet and playwright, commented on the film's title, referring to it as \"Crazy Rich EAST Asians\", and adding \"Does a win for representation mean replacing white people with white people wannabes[?]\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cleo.com.sg/entertain-me/crazy-rich-asians-chinese-singapore/|title=Crazy Rich Asians: Is The Chinese Cast An Accurate Representation?|work=[[Cleo (magazine)|Cleo]]|last=Hong|first=Sophie|date=April 26, 2018|accessdate=January 11, 2019}}</ref> Multiple critics also criticized the comedic scene in which the characters Rachel Chu and Peik Lin were frightened by [[Sikh]] guards, noting that \"the presentation of brown men as scary predators is played for laughs\",<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goh |first1=Li Sian |title=Imperial Fantasies: On The Costs of Misrepresentation |url=https://www.bitchmedia.org/article/crazy-rich-asians-representation |work=[[Bitch (magazine)|Bitch Media]] |accessdate=November 4, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927113654/https://www.bitchmedia.org/article/crazy-rich-asians-representation |archivedate=September 27, 2018}}</ref> is \"blind to racial politics in Singapore\",<ref>{{cite web |last1=Steains |first1=Timothy |title=Crazy Rich Asians is a great moment for representation \u2013 but slides over some important question |url=http://theconversation.com/crazy-rich-asians-is-a-great-moment-for-representation-but-slides-over-some-important-questions-100326 |website=The Conversation |accessdate=November 4, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824074842/http://theconversation.com/crazy-rich-asians-is-a-great-moment-for-representation-but-slides-over-some-important-questions-100326 |archivedate=August 24, 2018}}</ref> and presented a \"buffoonish performance [that is] as excruciating as [[Mickey Rooney]]'s as the Japanese photographer living above [[Audrey Hepburn]] in [[Breakfast at Tiffany's (film)|''Breakfast at Tiffany's'']].\"<ref name=Econ-1809/> However, one commenter noted that the book which the film is based on \"is aware of its lack of minority representation [and] actually alludes to the closed minded attitude of some social circles in Singapore. One of the family members got disowned for marrying a [[Malay (ethnic group)|Malay]].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/8/12/crazy-rich-asians-feature/|title='Crazy Rich Asians' Stars on How the Film 'Transcends Race'|last=Park|first=Claire N.|date=August 12, 2018|accessdate=January 3, 2019|work=[[The Harvard Crimson]]}}</ref>\n\nOther critics defended the film's portrayal of ethnic representation. Ilyas Sholihyn, a Malay Singaporean writing for ''[[Coconuts Media|Coconuts]]'', stated that \"it\u2019s hard to imagine the story is even relatable to most Chinese Singaporeans\" due to film's focus on the extremely wealthy, noting that ''Crazy Rich Asians'' was not made for native Singaporeans, but rather \"a high-fantasy Hollywood film made for maximum appeal to East Asian-Americans.\" He did, however, criticize the film for certain decisions regarding representation, notably that the scene at the Newton Food Centre lacked accurate cultural diversity, and the roles for the limited number of non-Chinese Singaporeans, such as guards and valets, suffered from [[tokenism]].<ref name=\"NFC\">{{cite news|url=https://coconuts.co/singapore/features/native-singaporean-malay-crazy-rich-asians-nothing-thats-okay/|title=As a native Singaporean Malay, 'Crazy Rich Asians' did nothing for me (and that's okay)|last=Sholihyn|first=Ilyas|work=[[Coconuts Media|Coconuts]]|date=August 23, 2018|accessdate=January 3, 2019}}</ref> Surekha A. Yadav of the ''Malay Mail'' defended the film's lack of diversity, describing it as an accurate portrayal of Chinese Singaporeans, particularly wealthy ones, who, per statistics from the [[Institute of Policy Studies (Singapore)|Institute of Policy Studies]], have minimal and even discriminatory interactions with Singaporean minority groups. Regarding the film specifically, Yadav explained that \"it is the extremely privileged edge of this upper segment of Singapore society that ''Crazy Rich Asians'' depicts. In reality, this is a world where minorities play a very small role.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.malaymail.com/s/1665967/crazy-rich-asians-isnt-racist-it-is-right|title='Crazy Rich Asians' isn't racist, it is right|work=[[Malay Mail]]|last=Yadav|first=Surekha A.|date=August 26, 2018|accessdate=January 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Date of ceremony\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\" style