an Ensemble]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''Crazy Rich Asians''\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lewis |first1=Hilary |title='Green Book' Named Best Film by National Board of Review |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/green-book-named-best-film-by-national-board-review-1164206 |accessdate=November 28, 2018 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=November 27, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"3\" | [[People's Choice Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[44th People's Choice Awards|November 11, 2018]]\n| The Comedy Movie of 2018\n| {{Nominated}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.eonline.com/shows/peoples_choice_awards/news/963752/2018-people-s-choice-awards-complete-list-of-nominations|title=2018 People's Choice Awards: Complete List of Nominations|accessdate=September 5, 2018|date=September 5, 2018|work=[[E! News]]|first=Johnni|last=Macke|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905154343/https://www.eonline.com/shows/peoples_choice_awards/news/963752/2018-people-s-choice-awards-complete-list-of-nominations|archivedate=September 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/shows/peoples_choice_awards/news/967279/2018-people-s-choice-awards-complete-list-of-finalists|title=2018 People's Choice Awards: Complete List of Finalist|work=[[E! News]]|first=Johnni|last=Macke|date=September 24, 2018|accessdate=October 5, 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20181005023925/https://www.eonline.com/shows/peoples_choice_awards/news/967279/2018-people-s-choice-awards-complete-list-of-finalists|archivedate=October 5, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | The Comedy Movie Star of 2018\n| [[Awkwafina]]\n| {{Shortlisted}}\n|-\n| {{sortname|Constance|Wu}}\n| {{Shortlisted}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Producers Guild of America Awards]]\n| [[Producers Guild of America Awards 2018|January 19, 2019]]\n| [[Producers Guild of America Award for Best Theatrical Motion Picture#2010s|Best Theatrical Motion Picture]]\n| ''Crazy Rich Asians'' \u2013 Nina Jacobson & Brad Simpson, John Penotti\n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref name=\"PGA18\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/producers-guild-awards-nominations-include-roma-black-panther-a-star-is-born-and-also-crazy-rich-asians/|title=Producers Guild Awards Nominations Include 'Roma,' 'Black Panther,' 'A Star Is Born' \u2013 and Also 'Crazy Rich Asians'|work=[[TheWrap]]| last=Pond|first=Steve|date=January 4, 2019|accessdate=January 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[San Diego Film Critics Society#Awards|San Diego Film Critics Society]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| December 10, 2018\n| Best Comedic Performance\n| Awkwafina\n| {{Nominated}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=\"SDFCS18\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sdfcs.org/2018-san-diego-film-nominations/ |title=2018 San Diego Film Critics Society's Award Nominations |date=December 7, 2018 |website=[[San Diego Film Critics Society]] |access-date=December 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209123837/http://www.sdfcs.org/2018-san-diego-film-nominations/ |archive-date=December 9, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Costume Design\n| Mary E. Vogt\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=2| [[Satellite Awards]]\n| rowspan=2| [[23rd Satellite Awards|February 17, 2019]]\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Film|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Comedy/Musical]]\n| ''Crazy Rich Asians''\n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pressacademy.com/2018-nominees/ |title=2018 Awards Nominees |publisher=[[International Press Academy]] |accessdate=December 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129220303/http://www.pressacademy.com/2018-nominees/ |archive-date=November 29, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Actress in a Motion Picture, Comedy/Musical]]\n| Constance Wu\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|[[Screen Actors Guild Award]]s\n| [[25th Screen Actors Guild Awards|January 27, 2019]]\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]]\n| ''Crazy Rich Asians''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web| url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/sag-awards-nominations-full-list-sag-award-nominees-1202518339/| title=SAG Awards Nominations: 'A Star Is Born', 'Mrs. Maisel', 'Ozark' Lead Way \u2013 The Full List| date=December 12, 2018| author=Patrick Hipes| website=Deadline}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[The Asian Awards]]\n|[[The Asian Awards|April 12, 2019]]\n| Outstanding Achievement in Cinema\n| The cast of [[Crazy Rich Asians]]\n|{{Won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://theasianawards.com/winners_9th_awards.html |website=The Asian Awards |accessdate=September 4, 2019|title=Winners of the 9th Asian Awards}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Sequels==\n[[File:Adele Lim by Gage Skidmore.jpg|Screenwriter [[Adele Lim]] left production on the two sequels to ''Crazy Rich Asians'' following a pay dispute, which she felt was founded in racism and sexism.|thumb|upright=0.8|alt=Adele Lim smiles, looking right.]]\nPrior to the film's release, Jon M. Chu said he would be eager to direct a sequel if the first film was a success, stating, \"We have other stories outside of the ''Crazy Rich Asians'' world that are ready to be told too, from filmmakers and storytellers who haven't had their stories told yet.\"<ref name=\"premiere\"/> On August 22, 2018, following the film's strong opening, Warner Bros. Pictures confirmed a sequel was in development, with Chiarelli and Lim returning to write the script, based on the book's sequel, ''[[China Rich Girlfriend]]''. Chu and actors Wu, Golding, and Yeoh all have options for a sequel, although several of the key actors are committed to other projects until 2020.<ref name=\"Time-KarenHo\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-sequel-in-development-at-warner-bros-1202450095/ |title='Crazy Rich Asians' Sequel In Development At Warner Bros. |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=August 22, 2018 |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822155159/https://deadline.com/2018/08/crazy-rich-asians-sequel-in-development-at-warner-bros-1202450095/ |archive-date=August 22, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Crazy Rich Asians 2: Everything We Know About The Sequel's Story |first=Ana |last=Dumaraog |date=August 28, 2018 |work=Screen Rant ORIGINALS |url=https://screenrant.com/crazy-rich-asians-2-story-china-rich-girlfriend/ |accessdate=August 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830004955/https://screenrant.com/crazy-rich-asians-2-story-china-rich-girlfriend/ |archive-date=August 30, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Producer Nina Jacobson later announced that ''China Rich Girlfriend'' and an adaptation of the final installment in Kwan's trilogy, ''[[Rich People Problems]]'', will be filmed back-to-back in 2020 to reduce the wait time between those two films.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/crazy-rich-asians-sequels-spoilers-nina-jacobson-brad-simpson-golden-globe-nominations-1202515361/ |title=Nina Jacobson & Brad Simpson Of Color Force Celebrate Diversity At Globe Noms, Tease 'Crazy Rich Asians' Sequels Details |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=December 6, 2018 |publisher=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=December 14, 2018 |quote=the current plan for the Crazy Rich Asians sequels is to shoot them back-to-back}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, screenwriter Adele Lim, who had co-written ''Crazy Rich Asians'' with Peter Chiarelli, left production on the film's sequels following a pay dispute. Lim had reportedly been offered 110,000 [[United States dollar]]s to pen the sequels, while Chiarelli had been offered $800,000-$1,000,000 for the same role.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/tanyatarr/2019/09/16/heres-what-we-learn-from-watching-adele-lim-walk-away-from-the-pay-gap/#23dd46053679|title=Here\u2019s What We Learn From Watching Adele Lim Walk Away From The Pay Gap|work=[[Forbes]]|date=September 16, 2019|accessdate=December 21, 2019|last=Tarr|first=Tanya}}</ref> Lim stated that the pay difference represented a greater issue of sexism and racism in Hollywood, as the industry views women and people of color as \"soy sauce\"\u2014or simply a means to add minor cultural details to screenplays, rather than to provide a substantial writing role.<ref name=\"alcnbc\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/09/06/crazy-rich-asians-co-writer-adele-lim-quits-sequel-due-to-pay-gap.html|title=The \u2018Crazy Rich Asians\u2019 sequel is delayed amid a pay dispute|date=September 6, 2019|accessdate=December 21, 2019|last=Liu|first=Jennifer|work=[[CNBC]]}}</ref> Director Jon M. Chu voiced support for Lim in a statement, explaining that, while he was disappointed she wouldn't return for the sequels, he would continue to work with Lim elsewhere and that \"the conversation this has started is MUCH more important than ourselves... so who am I to get in the way of that.\" He added that he agreed with Lim's criticisms of the film industry, and requested that people refrain from criticizing Chiarelli, as \"he is a good man, a creative force and has been a pro in the business for many many years\".<ref name=\"VFstatements\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/09/crazy-rich-asians-jon-chu-adele-lim-response|title=Crazy Rich Asians: Jon M. Chu Responds to Adele Lim\u2019s Exit Over Pay Parity|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|last=Bradley|first=Laura|date=September 10, 2019|accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref> Warner Bros.' business affairs department issued a response as well, stating that Chiarelli had more experience working on films as Lim's r\u00e9sum\u00e9 had only consisted of television credits prior to ''Crazy Rich Asians'', and that \"making an exception would set a troubling precedent in the business\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/crazy-rich-asians-screenwriter-adele-lim-exits-sequel-pay-disparity-dispute-1236431|title='Crazy Rich Asians' Co-Writer Exits Sequel Amid Pay Disparity Dispute (Exclusive)|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=September 4, 2019|accessdate=December 21, 2019|last=Sun|first=Rebecca}}</ref> They also noted that an alternative offer for Lim had been drafted, which she did not take.<ref name=\"alcnbc\" /> Lim later voiced thanks for the public support she had received, writing on Twitter: \"To people going through their own fight - you are not alone. Also, I have only love for Jon M. Chu and the cast & crew of ''Crazy Rich Asians''\".<ref name=\"VFstatements\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chinese in New York City]]\n* [[Overseas Chinese]]\n* [[Chinese Singaporeans]]\n* [[Flower Drum Song (film)|''Flower Drum Song'']], the 1961 American film cited as the first with a majority Asian cast set contemporaneously, which was also adapted from [[The Flower Drum Song|a novel]].<ref name=NBC-2018-08-13>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/six-decades-ago-flower-drum-song-featured-hollywood-s-first-n899576 |title=Six decades ago, 'Flower Drum Song' featured Hollywood's first Asian-American cast |date=August 13, 2018 |first=Melissa |last=Hung |work=NBC News |access-date=August 31, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180901044052/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/six-decades-ago-flower-drum-song-featured-hollywood-s-first-n899576 |archive-date=September 1, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=22em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Crazy Rich Asians (2018 film)|Crazy Rich Asians}}\n* [h